jan]], Indian politician (b. 1949)\n*  2006   &ndash; [[Earl Woods]], American colonel, baseball player, and author (b. 1932)\n*[[2007]] &ndash; [[Warja Honegger-Lavater]], Swiss illustrator (b. 1913)\n*  2007   &ndash; [[Wally Schirra]], American captain, pilot, and astronaut (b. 1923)\n*  2007   &ndash; [[Knock Yokoyama]], Japanese politician (b. 1932)\n*[[2008]] &ndash; [[Leopoldo Calvo-Sotelo]], Spanish engineer and politician, [[Prime Minister of Spain]] (b. 1926)\n*[[2009]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9e Morisset]], Canadian pianist (b. 1928)\n*  2009   &ndash; [[Ram Balkrushna Shewalkar]], Indian author and critic (b. 1931)\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Roy Carrier]], American accordion player (b. 1947)\n*  2010   &ndash; [[Peter O'Donnell]], English soldier and author (b. 1920)\n*  2010   &ndash; [[Guenter Wendt]], German-American engineer (b. 1923)\n*[[2011]] &ndash; [[Jackie Cooper]], American actor, television director, producer and executive (b. 1922)\n*  2011   &ndash; [[Sergo Kotrikadze]], Georgian footballer and manager (b. 1936)\n*  2011   &ndash; [[Thanasis Veggos]], Greek actor and director (b. 1927)\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[Jorge Illueca]], Panamanian politician, 30th [[President of Panama]] (b. 1918)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Felix Werder]], German-Australian composer, conductor, and critic (b. 1922)\n*[[2013]] &ndash; [[Joe Astroth]], American baseball player (b. 1922)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Herbert Blau]], American engineer and academic (b. 1926)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Cedric Brooks]], Jamaican-American saxophonist and flute player (b. 1943)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Keith Carter (swimmer)|Keith Carter]], American swimmer and soldier (b. 1924)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Brad Drewett]], Australian tennis player and sportscaster (b. 1958)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[David Morris Kern]], American pharmacist, co-invented [[Orajel]] (b. 1909)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Curtis Rouse]], American football player (b. 1960)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Branko Vukeli\u0107]], Croatian politician, 11th [[Ministry of Defence (Croatia)|Minister of Defence for Croatia]] (b. 1958)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Gary Becker]], American economist and academic, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1930)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Francisco Icaza]], Mexican painter (b. 1930)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Jim Oberstar]], American educator and politician (b. 1934)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Revaz Chkheidze]], Georgian director and screenwriter (b. 1926)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Danny Jones (rugby league)|Danny Jones]], Welsh rugby player (b. 1986)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Warren Smith (golfer)|Warren Smith]], American golfer and coach (b. 1915)\n*[[2016]] &ndash; [[Ian Deans]], Canadian politician (b. 1937)\n*  2016   &ndash; [[Jadranka Stojakovi\u0107]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] singer-songwriter  (b. 1950)\n*[[2017]] &ndash; [[Daliah Lavi]], Israeli actress, singer and model (b. 1942)\n<!--Do not add people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \u201cthis year in history\u201d websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n* Christian [[feast day]]:\n** [[Abhai (saint)|Abhai]] ([[Syriac Orthodox Church]])\n** [[Antonia and Alexander]]\n** [[Juvenal of Narni]]\n** [[Saint Moura|Moura]] ([[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Church]])\n** [[Philip the Apostle|Philip]] and [[James, son of Alphaeus|James the Lesser]]\n** [[Pope Alexander I]]\n** [[Sarah the Martyr]] ([[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Church]])\n** [[Gloriosam Reginam|The Most Holy Virgin Mary Queen of Poland]] \n** [[Theodosius of Kiev]] ([[Eastern Orthodox Church]])\n** [[May 3 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n* [[Constitution Memorial Day]] ([[Japan]])\n* [[May 3rd Constitution Day|Constitution Day (Poland)]]\n* [[Feast of the Cross#May 3|Finding of the Holy Cross]]-related observances:\n** [[Fiesta de las Cruces]] (Spain and [[Hispanic America]])\n** [[Roodmas]], or Feast of the [[Finding of the Holy Cross]] ([[Gallican Rite]] of the [[Catholic Church]])\n* [[Sun Day]] ([[International observance|International]])\n* [[World Press Freedom Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/may/3 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=05|day=03}}\n* [https://archive.is/20121208165033/http://www1.sympatico.ca/cgi-bin/on_this_day?mth=May&day=03 On This Day in Canada]\n\n{{months}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:May 03}}\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:May]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|The Third of May|the Goya painting|The Third of May 1808}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n* {{0}}[[752]] &ndash; Mayan king [[Yaxun B'alam IV|Bird Jaguar IV]] of [[Yaxchilan]] in modern-day [[Chiapas]], Mexico assumes the throne.\n*[[1294]] &ndash; [[John II, Duke of Brabant|John II]] becomes Duke of Brabant, Lothier and Limburg.\n*[[1481]] &ndash; The [[1481 Rhodes earthquake|largest of three earthquakes]] strikes the island of [[Rhodes]] and causes an estimated 30,000 casualties.\n*[[1491]] &ndash; [[Kingdom of Kongo|Kongo]] monarch [[Nkuwu Nzinga]] is baptised by [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese]] missionaries, adopting the baptismal name of [[Jo\u00e3o I of Kongo|Jo\u00e3o I]].\n*[[1616]] &ndash; [[Treaty of Loudun]] ends French civil war.\n*[[1715]] &ndash; A [[solar eclipse of May 3, 1715|total solar eclipse]] was visible across northern Europe, and northern Asia, as predicted by [[Edmond Halley]] to within 4 minutes accuracy.\n*[[1791]] &ndash; The [[Constitution of May 3, 1791|Constitution of May 3]] (the first modern [[constitution]] in Europe) is proclaimed by the [[Sejm]] of [[Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth]].\n*[[1802]] &ndash; [[Washington, D.C.]] is incorporated as a city after [[United States Congress|Congress]] abolishes the Board of Commissioners, the District's founding government. The \"City of Washington\" is given a [[Mayor\u2013council government|mayor-council]] form of government.<ref>{{cite book|last=Costanzo|first=Adam|title=George Washington's Washington: Visions for the National Capital in the Early American Republic|location=Athens, Ga.|publisher=The University of Georgia Press|date=2018|isbn=9780820352855|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rd5PDwAAQBAJ|pages=76\u201377, 200 fn. 28}}</ref>\n*[[1808]] &ndash; [[Finnish War]]: Sweden loses the fortress of [[Sveaborg]] to Russia.\n*  1808   &ndash; [[Peninsular War]]: The [[Madrid]] rebels who [[Dos de Mayo Uprising|rose up]] on [[May 2]] are executed near [[Pr\u00edncipe P\u00edo (hill)|Pr\u00edncipe P\u00edo]] hill.\n*[[1815]] &ndash; [[Neapolitan War]]: [[Joachim Murat]], King of [[Kingdom of Naples|Naples]] is defeated by the Austrians at the [[Battle of Tolentino]], the decisive engagement of the war.\n*[[1830]] &ndash; The [[Canterbury and Whitstable Railway]] is opened; it is the first steam-hauled passenger railway to issue season tickets and include a tunnel.\n*[[1837]] &ndash; The [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|University of Athens]] is founded in [[Athens]], Greece.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; The boar-crested [[Anglo-Saxon]] [[Benty Grange helmet]] is discovered in a [[Tumulus|barrow]] on the [[Benty Grange]] farm in [[Derbyshire]].\n*[[1849]] &ndash; The [[May Uprising in Dresden]] begins: The last of the [[German revolutions of 1848\u201349]].\n*[[1855]] &ndash; American adventurer [[William Walker (filibuster)|William Walker]] departs from [[San Francisco]] with about 60 men to conquer [[Nicaragua]].\n*[[1860]] &ndash; [[Charles XV of Sweden|Charles XV]] of [[Sweden\u2013Norway]] is crowned king of Sweden.\n*[[1867]] &ndash; The [[Hudson's Bay Company]] gives up all claims to [[Vancouver Island]].\n*[[1901]] &ndash; The [[Great Fire of 1901]] begins in [[Jacksonville, Florida]].\n*[[1913]] &ndash; ''[[Raja Harishchandra]]'' the first full-length Indian [[feature film]] is released, marking the beginning of the [[Cinema of India|Indian film industry]].\n*[[1920]] &ndash; A [[1920 Georgian coup attempt|Bolshevik coup]] fails in the [[Democratic Republic of Georgia]].\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[West Virginia]] becomes the first state to legislate a broad [[sales tax]], but does not implement it until a number of years later due to enforcement issues.\n*  1921   &ndash; The [[Government of Ireland Act 1920]] is passed, dividing [[Ireland]] into [[Northern Ireland]] and [[Southern Ireland (1921\u201322)|Southern Ireland]].\n*[[1928]] &ndash; The [[Jinan incident]] begins with the deaths of twelve Japanese civilians by Chinese forces in Jinan, China, which leads to Japanese retaliation and the deaths of over 2,000 Chinese civilians in the following days.<ref>C. Martin Wilbur, \"The Nationalist Revolution: from Canton to Nanking, 1923\u20131928,\" ''Cambridge History of China'', Volume 12 ''Republican China, 1912\u20131949'' Pt I (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1983), 702\u2013706.</ref>\n*[[1939]] &ndash; The [[All India Forward Bloc]] is formed by Netaji [[Subhas Chandra Bose]].\n*[[1942]] &ndash; World War II: [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] naval troops [[Invasion of Tulagi (May 1942)|invade Tulagi]] Island in the [[Solomon Islands]] during the first part of [[Operation Mo]] that results in the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]] between Japanese forces and forces from the United States and Australia.\n*[[1945]] &ndash; World War II: Sinking of the [[prison ship]]s ''[[SS Cap Arcona (1927)|Cap Arcona]]'', ''[[SS Thielbek (1940)|Thielbek]]'' and ''[[SS Deutschland (1923)|Deutschland]]'' by the [[Royal Air Force]] in  [[L\u00fcbeck Bay]].\n*[[1947]] &ndash; New post-war [[Constitution of Japan|Japanese constitution]] goes into effect.\n*[[1948]] &ndash; The [[U.S. Supreme Court]] rules in ''[[Shelley v. Kraemer]]'' that covenants prohibiting the sale of [[real estate]] to blacks and other minorities are legally unenforceable.<ref>{{cite book|last=Meyer|first=Stephen Grant|title='As Long as They Don't Move Next Door': Segregation and Racial Conflict in American Neighborhoods|location=Lanham, Md.|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date=2000|isbn=978-0-8476-9700-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0jQtLcwuOLkC|page=265, fn. 41}}</ref>\n*[[1951]] &ndash; London's [[Royal Festival Hall]] opens with the [[Festival of Britain]].\n*  1951   &ndash; The [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]] and [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]] begin their closed door hearings into the dismissal of General [[Douglas MacArthur]] by U.S. President [[Harry Truman]].\n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[Lieutenant Colonel]]s [[Joseph O. Fletcher]] and [[William P. Benedict]] of the United States land a plane at the [[North Pole]].\n*  1952   &ndash; The [[Kentucky Derby]] is televised nationally for the first time, on the [[CBS]] network.\n*[[1957]] &ndash; [[Walter O'Malley]], the owner of the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]], agrees to move the team from [[Brooklyn]] to Los Angeles.\n*[[1960]] &ndash; The [[Off-Broadway]] [[musical comedy]] ''[[The Fantasticks]]'' opens in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]], eventually becoming the longest-running [[musical theatre|musical]] of all time.\n*  1960   &ndash; The [[Anne Frank House]] museum opens in [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands.\n*[[1963]] &ndash; The police force in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] switches tactics and [[Birmingham campaign#Fire hoses and police dogs|responds with violent force]] to stop the \"[[Birmingham campaign]]\" protesters.  Images of the violent suppression are transmitted worldwide, bringing new-found attention to the [[civil rights movement]].\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Erich Honecker]] becomes [[Leadership of East Germany#Leaders of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED)|First Secretary of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany]], remaining in power until 1989.<ref>{{cite book|last=Winkler|first=Heinrich August|title=Germany: The Long Road West, Vol. 2: 1933\u20131990|pages=266\u2013268|year=2007|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>\n*[[1973]] &ndash; The 108-story [[Sears Tower]] in Chicago is topped out at 1,451 feet as the [[world's tallest building]].\n*[[1978]] &ndash; The first unsolicited bulk commercial [[email]] (which would later become known as \"[[spam (electronic)|spam]]\") is sent by a [[Digital Equipment Corporation]] marketing representative to every [[ARPANET]] address on the west coast of the United States. \n*[[1986]] &ndash; Twenty-one people are killed and forty-one are injured after a bomb explodes on [[Air Lanka Flight 512]] at Colombo airport in Sri Lanka.\n*[[1987]] &ndash; A crash by [[Bobby Allison]] at the [[Talladega Superspeedway]], [[Alabama]] fencing at the start-finish line would lead [[NASCAR]] to develop the [[restrictor plate]] for the following season both at [[Daytona International Speedway]] and Talladega.\n*[[1999]] &ndash; The southwestern portion of [[Oklahoma City]] is devastated by an [[1999 Bridge Creek\u2013Moore tornado|F5 tornado]], killing forty-five people, injuring 665, and causing $1 billion in damage.  The tornado is one of 66 from the [[1999 Oklahoma tornado outbreak]]. This tornado also produces the highest wind speed ever recorded, measured at 301 +/- 20&nbsp;mph (484 +/- 32&nbsp;km/h).\n*[[2000]] &ndash; The sport of [[geocaching]] begins, with the first cache placed and the coordinates from a [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] posted on [[Usenet]].\n*[[2001]] &ndash; The United States loses its seat on the [[U.N. Human Rights Commission]] for the first time since the commission was formed in [[1947]].\n*[[2002]] &ndash; An [[Indian Air Force]] MiG-21 [[2002 Jalandhar MiG-21 crash|crashes into a bank in Jalandhar]], killing eight and injuring 17.\n*[[2007]] &ndash; The 3-year-old British girl [[Disappearance of Madeleine McCann|Madeleine McCann]] disappears in Praia da Luz, Portugal, starting \"the most heavily reported missing-person case in modern history\".\n*[[2015]] &ndash; Two gunmen [[Curtis Culwell Center attack|launch an attempted attack]] on an anti-Islam event in [[Garland, Texas]], which was held in response to the [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|''Charlie Hebdo'' shooting]].\n*[[2016]] &ndash; Eighty-eight thousand people were evacuated from their homes in Fort McMurray, Alberta, Canada as [[2016 Fort McMurray Wildfire|a wildfire ripped through the community]], destroying approximately 2,400 homes and buildings.\n\n==Births==\n* [[490]] &ndash; [[K'an Joy Chitam I]], ruler of [[Palenque]] (d. 565)\n* [[612]] &ndash; [[Constantine III (Byzantine emperor)|Constantine III]], Byzantine emperor (d. 641)\n*[[1238]] &ndash; [[Emilia Bicchieri]], Italian saint (d. 1314)\n*[[1276]] &ndash; [[Louis, Count of \u00c9vreux]], son of King [[Philip III of France]] (d. 1319)\n*[[1415]] &ndash; [[Cecily Neville, Duchess of York]] (d. 1495)\n*[[1428]] &ndash; [[Pedro Gonz\u00e1lez de Mendoza]], Spanish cardinal (d. 1495)\n*[[1446]] &ndash; [[Margaret of York]] (d. 1503)\n*[[1461]] &ndash; [[Raffaele Riario]], Italian cardinal (d. 1521)\n*[[1469]] &ndash; [[Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli]], Italian historian and philosopher (d. 1527)\n*[[1479]] &ndash; [[Henry V, Duke of Mecklenburg]] (d. 1552)\n*[[1481]] &ndash; [[Juana de la Cruz V\u00e1zquez Guti\u00e9rrez]], Spanish abbess of the Franciscan Third Order Regular (d. 1534)\n*[[1536]] &ndash; [[Stephan Praetorius]], German theologian (d. 1603)\n*[[1632]] &ndash; [[Catherine of St. Augustine]], French-Canadian nurse and saint, founded the [[H\u00f4tel-Dieu de Qu\u00e9bec]] (d. 1668)\n*[[1662]] &ndash; [[Matth\u00e4us Daniel P\u00f6ppelmann]], German architect, designed the [[Pillnitz Castle]] (d. 1736)\n*[[1678]] &ndash; [[Amaro Pargo]], Spanish corsair (d. 1747)\n*[[1695]] &ndash; [[Henri Pitot]], French physicist and engineer, invented the [[Pitot tube]] (d. 1771)\n*[[1729]] &ndash; [[Florian Leopold Gassmann]], Czech composer (d. 1774)\n*[[1761]] &ndash; [[August von Kotzebue]], German playwright and author (d. 1819)\n*[[1764]] &ndash; [[Princess \u00c9lisabeth of France]] (d. 1794)\n*[[1768]] &ndash; [[Charles Tennant]], Scottish chemist and businessman (d. 1838)\n*[[1783]] &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 de la Riva Ag\u00fcero]], Peruvian soldier and politician, 1st President of Peru and 2nd President of North Peru (d. 1858)<ref>{{cite book|title=The Century Dictionary: The Century cyclopedia ofnames ... ed. by Benjamin E. Smith ... v. 12. Atlas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oUJFAQAAMAAJ|year=1911|publisher=Century Company|page=858}}</ref>\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[Adams George Archibald]], Canadian lawyer and politician, 4th [[Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia]] (d. 1892)\n*[[1826]] &ndash; [[Charles XV of Sweden]] (d. 1872)\n*[[1844]] &ndash; [[Richard D'Oyly Carte]], English talent agent and composer (d. 1901)\n*[[1849]] &ndash; [[Jacob Riis]], Danish-American journalist and photographer (d. 1914)\n*  1849   &ndash; [[Bernhard von B\u00fclow]], German soldier and politician, [[Chancellor of Germany (German Reich)|Chancellor of Germany]] (d. 1929)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[George Gore]], American baseball player and manager (d. 1933)\n*[[1859]] &ndash; [[August Herrmann]], American executive in [[Major League Baseball]] (d.1931)\n*[[1860]] &ndash; [[Vito Volterra]], Italian mathematician and physicist (d. 1940)\n*[[1867]] &ndash; [[Andy Bowen]], American boxer (d. 1894)\n*  1867   &ndash; [[J. T. Hearne]], English cricketer (d. 1944)\n*[[1870]] &ndash; [[Princess Helena Victoria of Schleswig-Holstein]] (d. 1948)\n*[[1871]] &ndash; [[Emmett Dalton]], American criminal (d. 1937)\n*[[1873]] &ndash; [[Pavlo Skoropadskyi]], German-Ukrainian general and politician, [[Hetman of Ukraine]] (d. 1945)\n*[[1874]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Coty]], French businessman and publisher, founded [[Coty, Inc.]] (d. 1934)\n*  1874   &ndash; [[Vagn Walfrid Ekman]], Swedish oceanographer and academic (d. 1954)<ref>{{cite web |title=V. Walfrid Ekman {{!}} Swedish scie