002]] &ndash; [[Barbara Castle, Baroness Castle of Blackburn]], English politician, [[First Secretary of State]] (b. 1910)\n*  2002   &ndash; [[Yevgeny Svetlanov]], Russian pianist, composer, and conductor (b. 1928)\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[Suzy Parker]], American model and actress (b. 1932)\n*[[2004]] &ndash; [[Ken Downing]], English race car driver (b. 1917)\n*  2004   &ndash; [[Darrell Johnson]], American baseball player, coach, and manager (b. 1928)\n*[[2006]] &ndash; [[Karel Appel]], Dutch painter, sculptor, and poet (b. 1921)\n*  2006   &ndash; [[Pramod Mahajan]], Indian politician (b. 1949)\n*  2006   &ndash; [[Earl Woods]], American colonel, baseball player, and author (b. 1932)\n*[[2007]] &ndash; [[Warja Honegger-Lavater]], Swiss illustrator (b. 1913)\n*  2007   &ndash; [[Wally Schirra]], American captain, pilot, and astronaut (b. 1923)\n*  2007   &ndash; [[Knock Yokoyama]], Japanese politician (b. 1932)\n*[[2008]] &ndash; [[Leopoldo Calvo-Sotelo]], Spanish engineer and politician, [[Prime Minister of Spain]] (b. 1926)\n*[[2009]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9e Morisset]], Canadian pianist (b. 1928)\n*  2009   &ndash; [[Ram Balkrushna Shewalkar]], Indian author and critic (b. 1931)\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Roy Carrier]], American accordion player (b. 1947)\n*  2010   &ndash; [[Peter O'Donnell]], English soldier and author (b. 1920)\n*  2010   &ndash; [[Guenter Wendt]], German-American engineer (b. 1923)\n*[[2011]] &ndash; [[Jackie Cooper]], American actor, television director, producer and executive (b. 1922)\n*  2011   &ndash; [[Sergo Kotrikadze]], Georgian footballer and manager (b. 1936)\n*  2011   &ndash; [[Thanasis Veggos]], Greek actor and director (b. 1927)\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[Jorge Illueca]], Panamanian politician, 30th [[President of Panama]] (b. 1918)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Felix Werder]], German-Australian composer, conductor, and critic (b. 1922)\n*[[2013]] &ndash; [[Joe Astroth]], American baseball player (b. 1922)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Herbert Blau]], American engineer and academic (b. 1926)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Cedric Brooks]], Jamaican-American saxophonist and flute player (b. 1943)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Keith Carter (swimmer)|Keith Carter]], American swimmer and soldier (b. 1924)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Brad Drewett]], Australian tennis player and sportscaster (b. 1958)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[David Morris Kern]], American pharmacist, co-invented [[Orajel]] (b. 1909)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Curtis Rouse]], American football player (b. 1960)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Branko Vukeli\u0107]], Croatian politician, 11th [[Ministry of Defence (Croatia)|Minister of Defence for Croatia]] (b. 1958)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Gary Becker]], American economist and academic, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1930)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Francisco Icaza]], Mexican painter (b. 1930)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Jim Oberstar]], American educator and politician (b. 1934)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Revaz Chkheidze]], Georgian director and screenwriter (b. 1926)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Danny Jones (rugby league)|Danny Jones]], Welsh rugby player (b. 1986)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Warren Smith (golfer)|Warren Smith]], American golfer and coach (b. 1915)\n*[[2016]] &ndash; [[Ian Deans]], Canadian politician (b. 1937)\n*  2016   &ndash; [[Jadranka Stojakovi\u0107]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] singer-songwriter  (b. 1950)\n*[[2017]] &ndash; [[Daliah Lavi]], Israeli actress, singer and model (b. 1942)\n<!--Do not add people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \u201cthis year in history\u201d websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n* Christian [[feast day]]:\n** [[Abhai (saint)|Abhai]] ([[Syriac Orthodox Church]])\n** [[Antonia and Alexander]]\n** [[Juvenal of Narni]]\n** [[Saint Moura|Moura]] ([[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Church]])\n** [[Philip the Apostle|Philip]] and [[James, son of Alphaeus|James the Lesser]]\n** [[Pope Alexander I]]\n** [[Sarah the Martyr]] ([[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Church]])\n** [[Gloriosam Reginam|The Most Holy Virgin Mary Queen of Poland]] \n** [[Theodosius of Kiev]] ([[Eastern Orthodox Church]])\n** [[May 3 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n* [[Constitution Memorial Day]] ([[Japan]])\n* [[May 3rd Constitution Day|Constitution Day (Poland)]]\n* [[Feast of the Cross#May 3|Finding of the Holy Cross]]-related observances:\n** [[Fiesta de las Cruces]] (Spain and [[Hispanic America]])\n** [[Roodmas]], or Feast of the [[Finding of the Holy Cross]] ([[Gallican Rite]] of the [[Catholic Church]])\n* [[Sun Day]] ([[International observance|International]])\n* [[World Press Freedom Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/may/3 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=05|day=03}}\n* [https://archive.is/20121208165033/http://www1.sympatico.ca/cgi-bin/on_this_day?mth=May&day=03 On This Day in Canada]\n\n{{months}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:May 03}}\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:May]]\n", "name_user": "Googgoollman7777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBirths:Removed unnecessary link.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/May_3"}
{"title_page": "Legal drinking age", "text_new": "[[File:Alkoholersterwerbsalter (Weltweit)2.svg|thumb|500px|'''Minimum legal age to purchase alcohol by country (2015):'''<br />{{legend|#000000|Prohibited regardless of age}}{{legend|#441200|Minimum age is 25}}{{legend|#7F0000|Minimum age is 21}}{{legend|#FF0000|Minimum age is 20}}{{legend|#B200FF|Minimum age is 19}}{{legend|#0026FF|Minimum age is 18}}{{legend|#00FFFF|Minimum age is 17}}{{legend|#267F00|Minimum age is 16}}{{legend|#00FF00|Minimum age is 15}}{{legend|#B9B9B9|No regulation/no age set}}|alt=]]\n\nThe '''legal drinking age''' is the minimum age at which a person can [[legally]] consume [[alcoholic beverage|alcohol beverage]]s. The minimum age alcohol can be legally consumed can be different from the age when it can be purchased in some countries. These laws vary between different countries and many laws have exemptions or special circumstances. Most laws apply only to [[Drinking in public|drinking alcohol in public places]] with alcohol consumption in the home being mostly unregulated (an exception being the UK, which has a minimum legal age of five for supervised consumption in private places). Some countries also have different age limits for different [[List of alcoholic drinks|types of alcohol drinks]].<ref name=\"IARD\" />\n\nThe most commonly known reason for the law behind the legal drinking age is the [[Long-term impact of alcohol on the brain|effect on the brain]] in adolescents. Since the brain is still maturing, alcohol can have a [[Effects of alcohol on memory|negative effect on the memory]] and long-term thinking. Alongside that, it can cause [[Alcoholic liver disease|liver failure]], and create a [[Long-term effects of alcohol consumption#Hormonal imbalance|hormone imbalance]] in teens due to the constant changes and maturing of hormones during [[puberty]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pubs.niaaa.nih.gov/publications/AA67/AA67.htm |title=Underage Drinking |publisher=National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism |date=January 2006 |access-date=13 May 2018}}</ref> Young people are also especially at increased risk of injury when drinking alcohol.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peltzer|date=2015|title=Factors associated with unintentional injury among university students in 26 countries|url=|journal=Public Health Nurs|volume=32|issue=5|pages=440\u2013452|doi=10.1111/phn.12179|pmid=25644243}}</ref>\n\n==Africa==\n[[File:Drinking age Africa.svg|thumb|230px|'''Minimum legal age to purchase alcohol by country (2015):'''<br />{{legend|#000000|Prohibited}}{{legend|#7F0000|Minimum purchase age of 21 years}}{{legend|#0026FF|Minimum purchase age of 18 years}}{{legend|#00FFDD|Minimum purchase age of 17 years}}{{legend|#267F00|Minimum purchase age of 16 years}}{{legend|#00FF00|Minimum purchase age of 15 years}}{{legend|#808080|No minimum purchase age}}|alt=]]\nThe most common minimum age to purchase alcohol in Africa is 18. However, Angola (except Luanda Province), Central African Republic, Comoros, Equatorial Guinea, Guinea-Bissau, Mali, and Togo have no laws on the book restricting the sale of alcohol to minors. In Libya, Somalia and Sudan the sale, production and consumption of alcohol is completely prohibited.{{synthesis inline|date=October 2018}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:15%;\"| Country\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:15%;\"| State/region/province\n! colspan=2 style=\"width:30%;\"| ''[[De jure]]''\n! rowspan=2 style=\"width:40%;\"| Notes\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Drinking age\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Purchase age\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Algeria}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | None{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n|18<ref name=\"Icap Reports 4\">[https://www.iard.org/science-resources/detail/Minimum-Legal-Age-Limits Minimum legal age limits] - International Alliance for Responsible Drinking</ref>\n|Order No. 26-75 (1975), Article 14\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{flag|Angola}}\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"  colspan=\"2\" | None <ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.africanchildforum.org/clr/Harmonisation%20of%20Laws%20in%20Africa/other-documents-harmonisation_8_en.pdf|title=PROTECTION FROM DRUG ABUSE/ MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL AND DRUGS: INTERNATIONAL AND REGIONAL LAWS|publisher=The African Child Policy Forum|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| There is no national legislation prohibiting the sale of alcohol to minors.\n|-\n|[[Luanda Province]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" | 18<ref name=\"Decreto Executivo n\u00ba 87/08 de 10 julho\">{{cite web|url=http://www.luanda.gov.ao/verlegislacao.aspx?id=434|title=Sobre o acesso de menores a espect\u00e1culos nocturnos, e o consumo e a comercializa\u00e7\u00e3o de bebidas alco\u00f3licas por menores|publisher=Governo Provincial de Luanda|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| Legislation in [[Luanda Province]]:\nIt is prohibited to sell alcohol beverages to anyone under the age of 18. It is also prohibited for minors to buy and consume alcohol.<ref name=\"Decreto Executivo n\u00ba 87/08 de 10 julho\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{flag|Benin}}\n|None\n|20\n|Republic of Benin Report to UN Committee on the Rights of the Child CRC/C/BEN/2 (2005):\n\n* Article 8 of the decree of 10 June 1942 regulating the production, import, advertisement, sale, and consumption of alcohol beverages in French West Africa, prohibits the sale or free supply of alcohol beverages to minors under 20.\n* Article 13 stipulates fines ranging from CFAF 200,000 to CFAF 1 million for such offences, doubled in the case of repeat offences.\n* There are no official measures prohibiting children from consuming alcohol, tobacco or other substances harmful to their health.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{flag|Botswana}}\n| align=\"center\" |None<ref name=\"Botswana Liquor Act 2008\">{{cite web|url=https://www.a-mla.org/images/acts/LIQOUR%20ACT,%202004.pdf.pdf|title=Liquor Act 2008 - Section 32|publisher=Government of Botswana|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> <small>(prohibited for any person to supply)</small><ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\" />\n| align=\"center\" |18<ref name=\"Botswana Liquor Act 2008\" />\n| It is prohibited for any person with a liquor license to sell or supply alcohol beverages to minors under the age of 18 years. Because the law only applies to licensees, it is not prohibited for minors to buy, consume, or possess alcohol beverages.<ref name=\"Botswana Liquor Act 2008\" /> It is also prohibited for any person to expose or supply alcohol to a minor under the age of 18 years.<ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\" />\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{flag|Burundi}}\n| align=\"center\" |None<ref name=\"Code Penal Burundi\">{{cite web|url=https://ihl-databases.icrc.org/applic/ihl/ihl-nat.nsf/0/cb9d300d8db9fc37c125707300338af2/$FILE/Code%20P%C3%A9nal%20du%20Burundi%20.pdf|title=Code P\u00e9nal du Burundi - Article 501 et 502|publisher=MINISTRE DE LA JUSTICE ET GARDE|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |18 <small>(unless accompanied by parent or legal guardian)</small><ref name=\"Code Penal Burundi\" />\n| It is prohibited for any person with a liquor license to sell or supply alcohol beverages to unaccompanied minors under the age of 18 years.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flag|Cameroon}}\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | 21 <small>(18 if accompanied by a person 21 years of age or older)</small><ref name=\"Cameroon Penal Code\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wipo.int/wipolex/fr/text.jsp?file_id=425156|title=Law No. 2016/007 of July 12, 2016, relating to the Penal Code - Section 348|publisher=|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| It is prohibited for any person with a liquor license to sell or supply alcohol beverages to anyone under 18 years of age. The law permits adults from the ages 18 to 21 to consume, purchase and buy alcohol beverages if accompanied by a person 21 years of age or older. Anyone over the age of 21 years may buy or consume alcohol unaccompanied.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Cape Verde}}\n| align=\"center\" |None<ref name=\"Cap Verde Liquor Law\">{{cite web|url=https://www.minsaude.gov.cv/index.php/documentosite/342-1-plano-alcool-b-o-i-serie-n-29-de-18-de-abril-de-2016/file|title=Lei n.\u00b0 27/V/97|publisher=Imprensa Nacional de Cabo Verde|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |18<ref name=\"Cap Verde Liquor Law\"/>\n| It is prohibited for any person to sell or supply alcohol beverages to minors under the age of 18 years.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Central African Republic}}\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| 15 <small>(off-premises)</small>, or 21 <small>(on-premises)</small><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/publications/global_alcohol_report/profiles/caf.pdf|title=WHO Global Alcohol Report Central African Republic|date=2014|website=World Health Organization|access-date=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n|It is prohibited for any person to sell or supply alcohol beverages to minors under the age of 15 years when sold or supplied off-premises (e.g., liquor stores, wine stores, and supermarkets). It is prohibited for any person to sell or supply alcohol beverages to minors under the age of 21 years when sold or supplied on-premises (e.g., restaurants, bars, and cafes).<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{flag|Chad}}\n| align=\"center\" |None\n| align=\"center\" |18\n|Law 2017-01 Penal Code Chapter 6 Articles 376-378 establish penalties for licensees who permit entry to youth below age 16 unaccompanied by a supervising adult, sell or offer alcohol beverages to youth below age 18 unaccompanied by a supervising adult, or serve a person below age 18 to intoxication.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flag|Comoros}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/publications/global_alcohol_report/profiles/com.pdf|title=WHO Global Alcohol Report Comoros|date=2014|website=World Health Organization|access-date=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n|It is prohibited for any person to sell or supply alcohol beverages to minors under the age of 18 years.<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Egypt}}\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"|21 \n|Law No. 371 of 1956 concerning public shops and the resolutions implementing it\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Equatorial Guinea}}\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| 21<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/publications/global_alcohol_report/profiles/gnq.pdf|title=WHO Global Alcohol Reportal Equatorial Guinea|date=2014|website=World Health Organization|access-date=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Eritrea}}\n| align=\"center\" |None<ref name=\"Penal Code Eritrea\">{{cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/res/cld/document/penal-code_html/PENAL_CODE_ERITREA.pdf|title=Penal Code of Eritrea - Article 267|publisher=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crimes|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |18<ref name=\"Penal Code Eritrea\"/>\n| It is prohibited for any person to sell or serve alcohol beverages to minors under the age of 18 years.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Eswatini}}\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| 18<ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\"/> \n|Liquor Licenses Act (1964) Section 27\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Ethiopia}}\n| align=\"center\" |15<ref name=\"Penal of Ethiopia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wipo.int/edocs/lexdocs/laws/en/et/et011en.pdf|title=Criminal Code, 2004 - Article 531 & 818|publisher=WIPO|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |18<ref name=\"Penal of Ethiopia\"/>\n| It is prohibited for any person to sell, offer, serve or allow to serve alcohol beverages \"in substantial quantities\" to any infant or young person. The criminal code defines a young person as any person under the age of 15 years. But the Criminal Code Proclamation 414 (2004)  states: \"Whoever endangers the health of another, intentionally and unscrupulously, by administering or serving, or by causing or permitting to be administered or served, to minors (defined as anyone under the age of 18 years) (...) alcohol beverages or spirituous liquors of such kind or in such quantity as to make their injurious effect certain or probable, is punishable with simple imprisonment not exceeding one year, and fine. \nThe Revised Family Code Proclamation No. 213 (2000) Article 215 defines a minor as anyone who has not attained the full age of 18.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Gabon}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | None\n| align=\"center\" |18\n|Penal Code (1963), Article 209bis-1\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Gambia}}\n| align=\"center\" | None<ref name=\"UN Committee on the Rights of the Child: State Party Report: Gambia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/rwmain?page=search&docid=3df5a6d17&skip=0&query=liquor&coi=GMB|title=Drug Control Decree and Decree No. 80 of 1996|publisher=UN Committee on the Rights of the Child (CRC)|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\"/>\n| align=\"center\" | 16<ref name=\"UN Committee on the Rights of the Child: State Party Report: Gambia\"/><ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\"/>\n| Under the Liquor License Act (1957) it is prohibited to sell, serve or supply alcohol beverages to \"anyone under the apparent age of 16\".\nA \"young person\" is defined as anyone under the age of 17 by the Children and Young Persons Act, 1949 Section 2.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Ghana}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | None\n| align=\"center\" |18<ref name=\"Ghana LIQUOR LICENSING ACT - 1970\">{{cite web|url=http://laws.ghanalegal.com/acts/id/87/section/15/Young_Persons_To_Be_Excluded|title=LIQUOR LICENSING ACT - 1970 (ACT 331) - Section 15 - Young Persons to be Excluded.|publisher=Ghana Legal|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Guinea-Bissau}}\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| None<ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\"/>\n|\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Kenya}}\n| align=\"center\" | None<ref name=\"ALCOHOLIC DRINKS CONTROL ACT KENYA\">{{cite web|url=http://kenyalaw.org/kl/fileadmin/pdfdownloads/Acts/Alcoholic_Drinks_Control_Act__No4of2010.pdf|title=ALCOHOLIC DRINKS CONTROL ACT - SECTION 28|publisher=National Council for Law Reporting|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 18<ref name=\"ALCOHOLIC DRINKS CONTROL ACT KENYA\"/>\n| It is prohibited to sell, serve or supply alcohol beverages to anyone under the age of 18 years.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Lesotho}}\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| 18<ref name=\"LIQUOR LICENSING ACT 1998 LESOTHO\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lesothotradeportal.org.ls/index.php?r=site/display&id=57#39|title=LIQUOR LICENSING ACT 1998 - Section 39|publisher=Ministry of Tourism Environment and Culture|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| It is prohibited to sell, serve or supply any alcohol beverage to a minor under the age of 18 years. It is also prohibited for minors to consume, buy or attempt to buy alcohol.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Liberia}}\n| align=\"center\" | None\n| align=\"center\" | 18\n| It is prohibited to sell, serve or supply alcohol beverages to anyone under the age of 18 years; \"this section shall not apply to a parent or guardian who serves an alcoholic beverage to his child or ward\" Penal Law of 1976 Sec 16.\n|-\n| colspan=2| {{flag|Libya}}\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| Prohibited <ref name=\"Penal Code Libya\">{{cite web|url=http://security-legislation.ly/node/33464|title=Penal Code - Article (21) of Law No. (89) of 1974 prohibiting alcohol and establish the hudud punishment for drinking|publisher=Geneva Centre for the Democratic Control of Armed Forces|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n| Previously Article 498 of the Libyan Penal Code prohibited the sale of alcohol beverages to juveniles under the age of 16 years.<ref name=\"ACPF: MINIMUM AGE FOR SALE OF ALCOHOL\"/>\n|