sm]]\n* [[National Youth Rights Association]]\n* [[Shoulder tap (alcohol)]]\n* [[Foundation for Advancing Alcohol Responsibility]]\n* [[Choose Responsibility]]\n* [[Mature minor doctrine]]\n* [[Youth]]\n* [[Youth suffrage]]\n* [[Youth rights]]\n* [[Age of candidacy]]\n* [[Legal drinking age controversy]]\n* [[Smoking age]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160504144607/http://www.iard.org/policy-tables/minimum-legal-age-limits/ Minimum legal age limits] online table updated on a rolling basis, [[International Alliance for Responsible Drinking]]\n\n{{Law country lists}}\n{{Alcohol and health}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legal Drinking Age}}\n[[Category:Alcohol law]]\n[[Category:Drinking culture]]\n[[Category:Juvenile law]]\n[[Category:Law-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists by country]]\n[[Category:Minimum ages]]\n", "name_user": "StrahinjaSrbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "There was an error that said the autonomous province of Kosovo and Metohija was independent.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legal_drinking_age"}
{"title_page": "Sport Select", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n'''Sport Select''' is a group of [[sport]]s [[betting]] games offered by [[Canada]]'s [[province|provincial]] [[government]]s.  In [[Quebec]], the program is known as '''Pari sportif'''; in Ontario and Atlantic Canada, it is known as '''Pro-Line''' while in [[British Columbia]], it is known as '''Sports Action'''.  However, the rules for the games are similar in all [[Provinces of Canada|provinces]].  Initially created to offer betting primarily on the [[North America]]n [[major professional sports league]]s, Sport Select has expanded to offer betting on competitions such as the English [[Premier League]] and [[college sports]].\n\nSport Select (or equivalent) tickets can be purchased at all lottery centres across Canada, thus creating one of the most dense sports betting networks in the world.  In addition, some provinces are now accepting wagers over the [[Internet]].\n\n==Sport Select games==\nEach province offers versions of these three games under rules similar to those described below:\n\n===Pro-Line===\nKnown as '''Oddset''' in British Columbia and '''Mise-O-Jeu''' in Quebec, '''Pro-Line''' offers [[Fixed-odds gambling|fixed-odds]] sports betting, and is the most popular Sport Select game.  It does not offer betting on individual matches, partly because betting on a single sporting event is illegal under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]].  Therefore, Pro-Line is a parlay game where bettors wager on the outcome of anywhere from two to six (BC and Atlantic) and three to six (Quebec, Ontario and Western Canada) of the matches offered by the lottery corporation.  [[Fixed-odds gambling|Decimal odds]] are quoted for individual matches, the odds for each selection being multiplied to calculate the potential payout of the ticket.  For the ticket to pay out, all selections must be correct.  Some provinces offer ''Combo Play'' which does not require all selections to be correct for a payout, but a Combo Play ticket is effectively nothing more than a number of similar, individual Pro-Line tickets rolled into one.  [[Overtime (sport)|Overtime]] is considered when determining results, but overtime in [[soccer]] is not.\n\n===Point spread===\n''Point Spread'' is similar to those games offered by other [[bookmaker]]s where bettors are wagering against a quoted [[point spread]].  Bettors can make predictions on the outcomes of two to twelve games, depending on the province.  The payouts offered vary by province.\n\n===Over/Under===\nAlso known as ''Total'' in Quebec, ''Over/Under'' is similar to those games offered by other [[bookmaker]]s where bettors are wagering that the number of points scored in each match are over or under the quoted total.  Bettors can make predictions on the outcomes of two to twelve games, depending on the province.  The payouts offered vary by province.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://sieukeo.com/ |title= Sieukeo.com }} Saturday, April 11, 2020 </ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n{{refimprove|date=November 2016}}\n{{npov|date=November 2016}}\n===Odds===\n\nIn recent years, Sport Select has come under increasingly heavy criticism from Canadian gamblers due to the poor odds it offers (from the gambler's perspective).  A private bookmaker licensed in the [[United Kingdom]] or [[Nevada]] generally maintains an [[overround]] (or \"vig\") of about 110%, meaning the bookmaker can expect to pay out $100 for every $110 that is wagered.  In Canada, however, the overround for an individual match in Sport Select odds often exceeds 130%.  To make matters worse for the bettor, the parlay requirement compounds the overround - the actual vigorish is a minimum of 160% but can climb to well over ''300%'' (if six selections are made).  In jurisdictions such as the [[United Kingdom]] where genuine competition is allowed, bookies often pay bonuses for winning parlay bets to help offset the compounded vig.  Sport Select does not.\n\nAnother controversial frustration for Pro-Line players in Atlantic Canada is the occurrence of Atlantic Lottery (ALC) 'capping' wagering on combinations and, on rare occasion, individual selections.  This occurs when a significant amount of wagering is placed within a short span of time, typically on a specific combination of outcomes. The reasoning behind having such caps is to dissuade professional, or 'block', bettors from attempting to take advantage of potential flaws in the posted odds, and thus limits the liability for the corporation on a given combination of outcomes.  Typical block betting behaviour involves placing large sums (often thousands of $) on a very small amount of combinations, trying to focus on perceived flaws as much as possible.  Ultimately the Pro-Line game is meant to be recreational and not for professionals.  Unlike online-only betting operations where all transactions must be submitted by identity verified accounts, Atlantic Lottery operates across a network of retailers where wagers are accepted anonymously, thus making it more susceptible to such 'block' bettors.  The capping of combinations serves to limit pro-betting while keeping all outcomes open for betting, in any other combination.  If a combination of outcomes is capped, any subsequent transaction submitted to the system attempting to wager on this particular combination is rejected.  This can be an annoyance to non-professional (casual) bettors legitimately trying to wager on a capped combination, but experienced bettors have come to understand the reasoning and adjust their wagers accordingly.<ref>{{cite web|title=Atlantic Lottery}}</ref>\n\nThough most experts agree that the odds offered on Sport Select are such that even the sharpest punter would have no hope of making a [[Profit (accounting)|profit]] in the long term, some have. See, for instance, the 2007 Tax Court of Canada case R. v. Leblanc, in which two brothers netted $5.5 million on $50 million in bets over five years. The Tax Court ruled the profit was not taxable.\n\n===Ties===\nWhile ties are a common in [[soccer]] and used to be common in [[ice hockey]] as well, unlike what would be the case with most bookmakers the rules of Sport Select provide for betting on \"ties\" in nearly every sport including [[gridiron football|football]], [[basketball]] and in some provinces [[baseball]], even though ties are never allowed in basketball or baseball and are rare in football.  Consequently, Sport Select mandates that any game decided by five points or less in basketball, three points or less in football or one run in baseball (where applicable) is declared a \"tie\".  Furthermore, when the NHL introduced [[shoot out|shootouts]] in for the [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306 season]] the lottery corporations (in contrast to most bookmakers) quickly ruled that shootout results would ''not'' count, specifically so they could keep offering \"ties\" in hockey. In Ontario, a hockey game that goes to a shootout counts as both a Tie and a Visitor or Home win, depending on the outcome.  The rule is loathed by most Canadian gamblers because the size of the winning margin often means little to the teams on the field/court.  Many bettors believe the rule's true purpose is to confuse gamblers and allow for larger vigs.\n\n===NBA===\nWagering on [[NBA]] games was an issue when [[Toronto]] and [[Vancouver]] were being considered for NBA expansion franchises, due to strict league rules at the time which prohibited gambling.  The [[Toronto Raptors]] and [[Vancouver Grizzlies]] began play in the league in 1995 only after the provincial lottery corporations agreed to stop offering wagering on all NBA games.  As part of the agreement, the Raptors paid $5 million in its first three years and $1 million annually afterwards to its charitable foundation to compensate the Ontario provincial lottery corporation for its loss of revenue.\n\nWhen the [[Vancouver Grizzlies relocation to Memphis|Grizzlies relocated to Memphis]] in 2001, British Columbia resumed allowing wagering on NBA games.  In 2010, it was revealed that the Ontario Lottery Gaming Corporation and the Raptors were in negotiations to return wagering on NBA games to the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/basketball/2010/01/26/12623001.html|title=OLG 'hopeful' of adding NBA to Pro-Line|first=Mike|last=Ganter|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=2010-01-27|accessdate=2015-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/basketball/nba/proline-raptors-wagering/|title=Pro-Line brings back wagering on all NBA games|date=2010-01-26|accessdate=2015-06-16|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2010/01/27/negotiations_to_add_nba_to_proline_tickets_in_ontario.html|title=Negotiations to add NBA to Pro-Line tickets in Ontario|date=2010-01-27|accessdate=2015-06-16|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  In September 2016, it was announced that an agreement had been reached between the parties to allow betting on NBA games on Pro-Line in Ontario to resume beginning with the 2016-17 season.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://corporate.olg.ca/olg-adds-nba-to-pro-line/|title=OLG ADDS NBA TO PRO-LINE|date=2016-09-16|accessdate=2016-09-17|publisher=[[Ontario Lottery and Gaming Corporation]]}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/basketball/2016/09/16/nba-back-on-olgs-pro-line-after-two-decade-absence.html|title=NBA back on OLG\u2019s Pro-Line after two-decade absence|date=2016-09-16|accessdate=2016-09-17|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  The move is projected to generate $5-10 million in profit for the province.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lotteries in Canada]]\n[[Category:Sports betting]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n'''Sport Select''' is a group of [[sport]]s [[betting]] games offered by [[Canada]]'s [[province|provincial]] [[government]]s.  In [[Quebec]], the program is known as '''Pari sportif'''; in Ontario and Atlantic Canada, it is known as '''Pro-Line''' while in [[British Columbia]], it is known as '''Sports Action'''.  However, the rules for the games are similar in all [[Provinces of Canada|provinces]].  Initially created to offer betting primarily on the [[North America]]n [[major professional sports league]]s, Sport Select has expanded to offer betting on competitions such as the English [[Premier League]] and [[college sports]].\n\nSport Select (or equivalent) tickets can be purchased at all lottery centres across Canada, thus creating one of the most dense sports betting networks in the world.  In addition, some provinces are now accepting wagers over the [[Internet]].\n\n==Sport Select games==\nEach province offers versions of these three games under rules similar to those described below:\n\n===Pro-Line===\nKnown as '''Oddset''' in British Columbia and '''Mise-O-Jeu''' in Quebec, '''Pro-Line''' offers [[Fixed-odds gambling|fixed-odds]] sports betting, and is the most popular Sport Select game.  It does not offer betting on individual matches, partly because betting on a single sporting event is illegal under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]].  Therefore, Pro-Line is a parlay game where bettors wager on the outcome of anywhere from two to six (BC and Atlantic) and three to six (Quebec, Ontario and Western Canada) of the matches offered by the lottery corporation.  [[Fixed-odds gambling|Decimal odds]] are quoted for individual matches, the odds for each selection being multiplied to calculate the potential payout of the ticket.  For the ticket to pay out, all selections must be correct.  Some provinces offer ''Combo Play'' which does not require all selections to be correct for a payout, but a Combo Play ticket is effectively nothing more than a number of similar, individual Pro-Line tickets rolled into one.  [[Overtime (sport)|Overtime]] is considered when determining results, but overtime in [[soccer]] is not.\n\n===Point spread===\n''Point Spread'' is similar to those games offered by other [[bookmaker]]s where bettors are wagering against a quoted [[point spread]].  Bettors can make predictions on the outcomes of two to twelve games, depending on the province.  The payouts offered vary by province.\n\n===Over/Under===\nAlso known as ''Total'' in Quebec, ''Over/Under'' is similar to those games offered by other [[bookmaker]]s where bettors are wagering that the number of points scored in each match are over or under the quoted total.  Bettors can make predictions on the outcomes of two to twelve games, depending on the province.  The payouts offered vary by province.\n\n==Controversy==\n{{refimprove|date=November 2016}}\n{{npov|date=November 2016}}\n===Odds===\n\nIn recent years, Sport Select has come under increasingly heavy criticism from Canadian gamblers due to the poor odds it offers (from the gambler's perspective).  A private bookmaker licensed in the [[United Kingdom]] or [[Nevada]] generally maintains an [[overround]] (or \"vig\") of about 110%, meaning the bookmaker can expect to pay out $100 for every $110 that is wagered.  In Canada, however, the overround for an individual match in Sport Select odds often exceeds 130%.  To make matters worse for the bettor, the parlay requirement compounds the overround - the actual vigorish is a minimum of 160% but can climb to well over ''300%'' (if six selections are made).  In jurisdictions such as the [[United Kingdom]] where genuine competition is allowed, bookies often pay bonuses for winning parlay bets to help offset the compounded vig.  Sport Select does not.\n\nAnother controversial frustration for Pro-Line players in Atlantic Canada is the occurrence of Atlantic Lottery (ALC) 'capping' wagering on combinations and, on rare occasion, individual selections.  This occurs when a significant amount of wagering is placed within a short span of time, typically on a specific combination of outcomes. The reasoning behind having such caps is to dissuade professional, or 'block', bettors from attempting to take advantage of potential flaws in the posted odds, and thus limits the liability for the corporation on a given combination of outcomes.  Typical block betting behaviour involves placing large sums (often thousands of $) on a very small amount of combinations, trying to focus on perceived flaws as much as possible.  Ultimately the Pro-Line game is meant to be recreational and not for professionals.  Unlike online-only betting operations where all transactions must be submitted by identity verified accounts, Atlantic Lottery operates across a network of retailers where wagers are accepted anonymously, thus making it more susceptible to such 'block' bettors.  The capping of combinations serves to limit pro-betting while keeping all outcomes open for betting, in any other combination.  If a combination of outcomes is capped, any subsequent transaction submitted to the system attempting to wager on this particular combination is rejected.  This can be an annoyance to non-professional (casual) bettors legitimately trying to wager on a capped combination, but experienced bettors have come to understand the reasoning and adjust their wagers accordingly.<ref>{{cite web|title=Atlantic Lottery}}</ref>\n\nThough most experts agree that the odds offered on Sport Select are such that even the sharpest punter would have no hope of making a [[Profit (accounting)|profit]] in the long term, some have. See, for instance, the 2007 Tax Court of Canada case R. v. Leblanc, in which two brothers netted $5.5 million on $50 million in bets over five years. The Tax Court ruled the profit was not taxable.\n\n===Ties===\nWhile ties are a common in [[soccer]] and used to be common in [[ice hockey]] as well, unlike what would be the case with most bookmakers the rules of Sport Select provide for betting on \"ties\" in nearly every sport including [[gridiron football|football]], [[basketball]] and in some provinces [[baseball]], even though ties are never allowed in basketball or baseball and are rare in football.  Consequently, Sport Select mandates that any game decided by five points or less in basketball, three points or less in football or one run in baseball (where applicable) is declared a \"tie\".  Furthermore, when the NHL introduced [[shoot out|shootouts]] in for the [[2005\u201306 NHL season|2005\u201306 season]] the lottery corporations (in contrast to most bookmakers) quickly ruled that shootout results would ''not'' count, specifically so they could keep offering \"ties\" in hockey. In Ontario, a hockey game that goes to a shootout counts as both a Tie and a Visitor or Home win, depending on the outcome.  The rule is loathed by most Canadian gamblers because the size of the winning margin often means little to the teams on the field/court.  Many bettors believe the rule's true purpose is to confuse gamblers and allow for larger vigs.\n\n===NBA===\nWagering on [[NBA]] games was an issue when [[Toronto]] and [[Vancouver]] were being considered for NBA expansion franchises, due to strict league rules at the time which prohibited gambling.  The [[Toronto Raptors]] and [[Vancouver Grizzlies]] began play in the league in 1995 only after the provincial lottery corporations agreed to stop offering wagering on all NBA games.  As part of the agreement, the Raptors paid $5 million in its first three years and $1 million annually afterwards to its charitable foundation to compensate the Ontario provincial lottery corporation for its loss of revenue.\n\nWhen the [[Vancouver Grizzlies relocation to Memphis|Grizzlies relocated to Memphis]] in 2001, British Columbia resumed allowing wagering on NBA games.  In 2010, it was revealed that the Ontario Lottery Gaming Corporation and the Raptors were in negotiations to return wagering on NBA games to the province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/basketball/2010/01/26/12623001.html|title=OLG 'hopeful' of adding NBA to Pro-Line|first=Mike|last=Ganter|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=2010-01-27|accessdate=2015-06-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/basketball/nba/proline-raptors-wagering/|title=Pro-Line brings back wagering on all NBA games|date=2010-01-26|accessdate=2015-06-16|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2010/01/27/negotiations_to_add_nba_to_proline_tickets_in_ontario.html|title=Negotiations to add NBA to Pro-Line tickets in Ontario|date=2010-01-27|accessdate=2015-06-16|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  In September 2016, it was announced that an agreement had been reached between the parties to allow betting on NBA games on Pro-Line in Ontario to resume beginning with the 2016-17 season.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://corporate.olg.ca/olg-adds-nba-to-pro-line/|title=OLG ADDS NBA TO PRO-LINE|date=2016-09-16|accessdate=2016-09-17|publisher=[[Ontario Lottery and Gaming Corporation]]}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/basketball/2016/09/16/nba-back-on-olgs-pro-line-after-two-decade-absence.html|title=NBA back on OLG\u2019s Pro-Line after two-decade absence|date=2016-09-16|accessdate=2016-09-17|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  The move is projected to generate $5-10 million in profit for the province.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lotteries in Canada]]\n[[Category:Sports betting]]\n", "name_user": "39.48.21.253", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOver/Under)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sport_Select"}
{"title_page": "Kodachrome (song)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|1973 single by Paul Simon}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Kodachrome\n| cover      = Paulsimonkodachrome.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Paul Simon]]\n| album      = [[There Goes Rhymin' Simon]]\n| B-side     = Tenderness\n| released   = May 19, 1973\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 3:32\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = [[Paul Simon]]\n| producer   = {{Flat list|\n*Paul Simon\n*[[Phil Ramone]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Duncan (Paul Simon song)|Duncan]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Loves Me Like a Rock]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n}}\n[[Image:Kodachrome - Paul Simon; Vinyl record.jpg|thumb|upright|''Kodachrome'' \u2013 Paul Simon; [[Vinyl record]]]]\n\"'''Kodachrome'''\" is a song by the American singer-songwriter [[Paul Simon]]. It was the lead [[Single (music)|single]] from his third studio album, ''[[There Goes Rhymin' Simon]]'' (1973), released on [[Columbia Records]].  The song is named after the [[Kodak]] [[35 mm format]] [[Kodachrome]].\n\n==Description==\nAfter a review in ''Billboard'''s May 12 issue praising its \"cheerfully antisocial lyrics,\" the song debuted at #82 in the Hot 100 on the week-ending May 19, 1973.<ref>{{cite journal|date=May 19, 1973|title=Billboard Hot 100| journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|volume=85|issue=38|page=68|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> The lyrics to this song on ''There Goes Rhymin' Simon'' differed in wording from those on ''[[The Concert in Central Park]]'' (1982) and ''[[Paul Simon's Concert in the Park, August 15, 1991]]'' albums.  The former (the album) said, \"...everything looks '''worse''' in black and white,\" but the latter (the concerts) said, \"...everything looks '''better''' in black and white.\"  While it might be easy to read into the change in lyrics, Simon said, \"I can't remember which way I originally wrote it \u2013 'better' or 'worse' \u2013 but I always change it....'Kodachrome' was a song that was originally called 'Goin' Home.'\"<ref>\"Still Creative After All These Years,\" interview with Daniel J. Levitin, ''Grammy'' magazine, Winter, 1997.</ref>\n\nBut the real significance was that Kodachrome film gave unrealistic colour saturation. Pictures taken on a dull day looked as if they were taken on a sunny day. (To correct this, serious photographers would use a Wratten 2b UV filter to normalize the images).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kodak.com/US/en/motion/products/lab_and_post_production/kodak_filters/wratten_2_filters/default.htm|title=WRATTEN 2 Filters \u2013 Motion Picture Film|website=www.kodak.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.photo.net/discuss/threads/kodachrome-color-saturation-myth-revisited.393418/|title=Kodachrome Color Saturation Myth Revisited|website=Photo.net Photography Forums}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n\nIn an interview conducted in November 2008, Simon said that what he had in mind when writing the song was to call it \"Going Home\". However, finding this would have been \"too conventional\", he came up with \"Kodachrome\", because of its similar sound and larger innovative potential. He also refers to its first line as the \"most interesting\" part of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barnesandnoble.com/blog/category/interviews/|title=Interviews|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nFour weeks after its debut on the [[Hot 100]], the song moved to #9, sandwiched ahead of \"[[Tie a Yellow Ribbon Round the Ole Oak Tree]]\" by [[Tony Orlando and Dawn|Dawn featuring Tony Orlando]] and behind May 19, 1973, Hot 100 top debut (#59) \"[[Give Me Love (Give Me Peace on Earth)]]\" by [[George Harrison]];<ref>{{cite journal|date=June 16, 1973|title=Billboard Hot 100| journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|volume=85|issue=42|page=88|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> \n\nTwo weeks later \"Kodachrome\" peaked at #2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]]<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (1996). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 6th Edition (Billboard Publications)</ref>, behind [[Will It Go Round in Circles]] by [[Billy Preston]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100|title=Top 100 Songs \u2013 Billboard Hot 100 Chart|website=Billboard}}</ref> It peaked at #2 the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|adult contemporary chart]], as well.<ref>Hyatt, Wesley (1999). ''The Billboard Book of #1 Adult Contemporary Hits'' (Billboard Publications)</ref>  In the [[United Kingdom]], the song was marketed as the B-side to \"Take Me to the Mardi Gras\" (CBS 1578).<ref>See label photos at 45cat.com</ref> The song was also banned by the Federation of (Australian) Radio Broadcasters.<ref>''Billboard'' (Billboard Publications), July 7, 1973, page 53.</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nThe musicians on this session were the [[Muscle Shoals Rhythm Section]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=1216 |title=Kodachrome by Paul Simon Songfacts |website=Songfacts.com |date= |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aln2.albumlinernotes.com/Paul_Simon_Greatest_Hits.html|title=Paul Simon Greatest Hits|website=aln2.albumlinernotes}}</ref>\n\n* [[Paul Simon]] \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar\n* [[Pete Carr]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Jimmy Johnson (musician)|Jimmy Johnson]] \u2013 electric guitars\n* [[David Hood]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Roger Hawkins (drummer)|Roger Hawkins]] \u2013 [[Double tracking|double-tracked]] drums\n* [[Barry Beckett]] \u2013 [[Wurlitzer electric piano]], piano, [[tack piano]]\n* Uncredited \u2013 [[Horn section|horns]]\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (1973)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Australia (''[[Go-Set]]'')<ref name=\"AUS\">{{Cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]]|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Canada (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'') Top Singles<ref name=\"RPM1\">\n{{cite journal| url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f2/nlc008388.4853.pdf| title= RPM100: Singles|volume=19|number=23|date=July 21, 1973| work = [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]| publisher = [[Ottawa]]:  [[Library and Archives Canada]]| format      = PDF| accessdate  =November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Canada [[Adult contemporary|Adult Contemporary]] (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref name=\"RPM2\">\n{{cite journal| url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f2/nlc008388.4855.pdf| title= The Programmers' Adult Contemporary Playlist|volume=19|number=23|date=July 21, 1973| work = [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]| publisher   = [[Ottawa]]:  [[Library and Archives Canada]]| format      = PDF| accessdate  =November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|8|artist=Paul Simon|song=Kodachrome|accessdate=November 12, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=\"France\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|15|artist=Paul Simon|song=Kodachrome|accessdate=November 12, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=\"Dutch100\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>[Flavour of New Zealand, August 27, 1973]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002 <!--|accessdate=January 26, 2011-->|edition=1st |date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|location=Spain|isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"AC\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Paul Simon|chart=Adult Contemporary}} |title=Paul Simon \u2013 Chart history |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.billboard.com%2F%23%2Fartist%2FRihanna%2Fchart-history%2F658897%3Ff%3D793%26g%3DSingles&date=2011-10-02 |archivedate=October 2, 2011 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|2|artist=Paul Simon|song=Kodachrome|accessdate=November 12, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=\"Billboardhot100\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19730714.html|title=Cash Box Top 100 7/14/73|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609220746/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19730714.html|archive-date=June 9, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1973)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM''  Top Singles<ref>http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.100214&type=2&interval=24&PHPSESSID=dtlhqtcdftn9t40n27r4hds2h0</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|35\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1973.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1973/Top 100 Songs of 1973|website=www.musicoutfitters.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|74\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1973YESP.html|title=Cash Box YE Pop Singles \u2013 1973|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715135835/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1973YESP.html|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|64\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bennighof|first=James|title=The Words and Music of Paul Simon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ShBhKL-9SLIC|year=2007|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-99163-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Marc |last=Eliot | title= Paul Simon: A Life | publisher= John Wiley and Sons | year= 2010 | isbn= 978-0-470-43363-8  | url= https://archive.org/details/paulsimonlife0000elio |url-access=registration | ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|paul-simon|kodachrome}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n{{Paul Simon songs}}\n\n[[Category:Paul Simon songs]]\n[[Category:1973 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Paul Simon]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Phil Ramone]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Paul Simon]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Kodak]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|1973 single by Paul Simon}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Kodachrome\n| cover      = Paulsimonkodachrome.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Paul Simon]]\n| album      = [[There Goes Rhymin' Simon]]\n| B-side     = Tenderness\n| released   = May 19, 1973\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 3:32\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = [[Paul Simon]]\n| producer   = {{Flat list|\n*Paul Simon\n*[[Phil Ramone]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Duncan (Paul Simon song)|Duncan]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Loves Me Like a Rock]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n}}\n[[Image:Kodachrome - Paul Simon; Vinyl record.jpg|thumb|upright|''Kodachrome'' \u2013 Paul Simon; [[Vinyl record]]]]\n\"'''Kodachrome'''\" is a song by the American singer-songwriter [[Paul Simon]]. It was the lead [[Single (music)|single]] from his third studio album, ''[[There Goes Rhymin' Simon]]'' (1973), released on [[Columbia Records]].  The song is named after the [[Kodak]] [[35 mm format]] [[Kodachrome]].\n\n==Description==\nAfter a review in ''Billboard'''s May 12 issue praising its \"cheerfully antisocial lyrics,\" the song debuted at #82 in the Hot 100 on the week-ending May 19, 1973.<ref>{{cite journal|date=May 19, 1973|title=Billboard Hot 100| journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|volume=85|issue=38|page=68|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> The lyrics to this song on ''There Goes Rhymin' Simon'' differed in wording from those on ''[[The Concert in Central Park]]'' (1982) and ''[[Paul Simon's Concert in the Park, August 15, 1991]]'' albums.  The former (the album) said, \"...everything looks '''worse''' in black and white,\" but the latter (the concerts) said, \"...everything looks '''better''' in black and white.\"  While it might be easy to read into the change in lyrics, Simon said, \"I can't remember which way I originally wrote it \u2013 'better' or 'worse' \u2013 but I always change it....'Kodachrome' was a song that was originally called 'Goin' Home.'\"<ref>\"Still Creative After All These Years,\" interview with Daniel J. Levitin, ''Grammy'' magazine, Winter, 1997.</ref>\n\nBut the real significance was that Kodachrome film gave unrealistic colour saturation. Pictures taken on a dull day looked as if they were taken on a sunny day. (To correct this, serious photographers would use a Wratten 2b UV filter to normalize the images).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kodak.com/US/en/motion/products/lab_and_post_production/kodak_filters/wratten_2_filters/default.htm|title=WRATTEN 2 Filters \u2013 Motion Picture Film|website=www.kodak.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.photo.net/discuss/threads/kodachrome-color-saturation-myth-revisited.393418/|title=Kodachrome Color Saturation Myth Revisited|website=Photo.net Photography Forums}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n\nIn an interview conducted in November 2008, Simon said that what he had in mind when writing the song was to call it \"Going Home\". However, finding this would have been \"too conventional\", he came up with \"Kodachrome\", because of its similar sound and larger innovative potential. He also refers to its first line as the \"most interesting\" part of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barnesandnoble.com/blog/category/interviews/|title=Interviews|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nFour weeks after its debut on the [[Hot 100]], the song moved to #9, sandwiched ahead of \"[[Tie a Yellow Ribbon Round the Ole Oak Tree]]\" by [[Tony Orlando and Dawn|Dawn featuring Tony Orlando]] and behind May 19, 1973, Hot 100 top debut (#59) \"[[Give Me Love (Give Me Peace on Earth)]]\" by [[George Harrison]];<ref>{{cite journal|date=June 16, 1973|title=Billboard Hot 100| journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|volume=85|issue=42|page=88|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media, Inc.]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> \n\nTwo weeks later \"Kodachrome\" peaked at #2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]]<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (1996). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 6th Edition (Billboard Publications)</ref>, behind [[Will It Go Round in Circles]] by [[Billy Preston]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100|title=Top 100 Songs \u2013 Billboard Hot 100 Chart|website=Billboard}}</ref> It peaked at #2 the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|adult contemporary chart]], as well.<ref>Hyatt, Wesley (1999). ''The Billboard Book of #1 Adult Contemporary Hits'' (Billboard Publications)</ref>  In the [[United Kingdom]], the song was marketed as the B-side to \"Take Me to the Mardi Gras\" (CBS 1578).<ref>See label photos at 45cat.com</ref> The song was also banned by the Federation of (Australian) Radio Broadcasters.<ref>''Billboard'' (Billboard Publications), July 7, 1973, page 53.</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nThe musicians on this session were the [[Muscle Shoals Rhythm Section]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=1216 |title=Kodachrome by Paul Simon Songfacts |website=Songfacts.com |date= |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aln2.albumlinernotes.com/Paul_Simon_Greatest_Hits.html|title=Paul Simon Greatest Hits|website=aln2.albumlinernotes}}</ref>\n\n* [[Paul Simon]] \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar\n* [[Pete Carr]] \u2013 acoustic guitar\n* [[Jimmy Johnson (musician)|Jimmy Johnson]] \u2013 electric guitars\n* [[David Hood]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Roger Hawkins (drummer)|Roger Hawkins]] \u2013 [[Double tracking|double-tracked]] drums\n* [[Barry Beckett]] \u2013 [[Wurlitzer electric piano]], piano, [[tack piano]]\n* Uncredited \u2013 [[Horn section|horns]]\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (1973)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Australia (''[[Go-Set]]'')<ref name=\"AUS\">{{Cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]]|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Canada (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'') Top Singles<ref name=\"RPM1\">\n{{cite journal| url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f2/nlc008388.4853.pdf| title= RPM100: Singles|volume=19|number=23|date=July 21, 1973| work = [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]| publisher = [[Ottawa]]:  [[Library and Archives Canada]]| format      = PDF| accessdate  =November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Canada [[Adult contemporary|Adult Contemporary Playlist]] (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref name=\"RPM2\">\n{{cite journal| url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f2/nlc008388.4855.pdf| title= The Programmers' Adult Contemporary Playlist|volume=19|number=23|date=July 21, 1973| work = [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]| publisher   = [[Ottawa]]:  [[Library and Archives Canada]]| format      = PDF| accessdate  =November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|8|artist=Paul Simon|song=Kodachrome|accessdate=November 12, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=\"France\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|15|artist=Paul Simon|song=Kodachrome|accessdate=November 12, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=\"Dutch100\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>[Flavour of New Zealand, August 27, 1973]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002 <!--|accessdate=January 26, 2011-->|edition=1st |date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|location=Spain|isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"AC\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Paul Simon|chart=Adult Contemporary}} |title=Paul Simon \u2013 Chart history |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.billboard.com%2F%23%2Fartist%2FRihanna%2Fchart-history%2F658897%3Ff%3D793%26g%3DSingles&date=2011-10-02 |archivedate=October 2, 2011 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|2|artist=Paul Simon|song=Kodachrome|accessdate=November 12, 2015|rowheader=true|refname=\"Billboardhot100\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19730714.html|title=Cash Box Top 100 7/14/73|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609220746/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19730714.html|archive-date=June 9, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1973)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM''  Top Singles<ref>http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.100214&type=2&interval=24&PHPSESSID=dtlhqtcdftn9t40n27r4hds2h0</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|35\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1973.htm|title=Top 100 Hits of 1973/Top 100 Songs of 1973|website=www.musicoutfitters.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|74\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1973YESP.html|title=Cash Box YE Pop Singles \u2013 1973|website=tropicalglen.com|access-date=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715135835/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1973YESP.html|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|64\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bennighof|first=James|title=The Words and Music of Paul Simon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ShBhKL-9SLIC|year=2007|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-99163-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Marc |last=Eliot | title= Paul Simon: A Life | publisher= John Wiley and Sons | year= 2010 | isbn= 978-0-470-43363-8  | url= https://archive.org/details/paulsimonlife0000elio |url-access=registration | ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|paul-simon|kodachrome}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n{{Paul Simon songs}}\n\n[[Category:Paul Simon songs]]\n[[Category:1973 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Paul Simon]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Phil Ramone]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Paul Simon]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Kodak]]\n", "name_user": "JGabbard", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeekly charts:-w", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kodachrome_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Corrupted Blood incident", "text_new": "{{short description|Incident in World of Warcraft}}\n{{About|a virtual plague|the legal concept \"corruption of blood\"|Attainder}}\n[[File:Corrupted_blood_(World_Of_Warcraft).jpg|thumb|right|The Corrupted Blood debuff.]]\n[[Image:WoW Corrupted Blood Plague.jpg|right|256px|thumb|The Corrupted Blood debuff being spread among characters in Ironforge, one of ''World of Warcraft's'' in-game cities.]]\n\nThe '''Corrupted Blood incident''' was a virtual [[pandemic]] in the [[MMORPG]] ''[[World of Warcraft]]'', which began on September 13, 2005, and lasted for one week. The epidemic began with the introduction of the new [[raid (gaming)|raid]] Zul'Gurub and its [[boss (video gaming)|end boss]] Hakkar the Soulflayer. When confronted and attacked, Hakkar would cast a [[Health (gaming)|hit point]]-draining and highly contagious [[debuff]] spell called \"Corrupted Blood\" on players.\n\nThe spell, intended to last only seconds and function only within the new area of Zul'Gurub, soon spread across the [[virtual world]] by way of an oversight that allowed pets and minions to take the affliction out of its intended confines. By both accidental and purposeful intent, a pandemic ensued that quickly killed lower-level characters and drastically changed normal gameplay, as players did what they could do to avoid infection. Despite measures such as programmer-imposed quarantines, and the players' abandoning of densely populated cities (or even just not playing the game), it lasted until a combination of patches and resets of the virtual world finally controlled the spread.\n\nThe conditions and reactions of the event attracted the attention of [[epidemiology|epidemiologists]] for its implications of how human populations could react to a real-world epidemic.\n\n==History==\nThe epidemic began on September 13, 2005, when [[Blizzard Entertainment|Blizzard]] introduced a new raid called Zul'Gurub into the game as part of a new update. Its end boss, Hakkar the Soulflayer, could affect players by draining their blood and using it to heal himself. By intentionally poisoning one's own blood using a debuff called Corrupted Blood, which did a significant amount of damage to the player over time, Hakkar would drain blood and apply the disease to himself, allowing him to be killed. However, Corrupted Blood could be passed on between any nearby characters, and would kill characters of lower levels in a few seconds, while higher level characters could keep themselves alive. It would disappear as time passed or when the character died.\n\nDue to a programming oversight, when hunters or warlocks dismissed their pets, those pets would keep any active debuffs when summoned again. [[Non-player character]]s could contract the debuff, and could not be killed by it but could still spread it to players; in effect, this turned them into [[asymptomatic]] disease carriers and a form of [[Vector (epidemiology)|vector]] for the debuff.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> At least three of the game's servers were affected. The difficulty in killing Hakkar may have limited the spread of the disease. Discussion forum posters described seeing hundreds of bodies lying in the streets of the towns and cities. Deaths in ''World of Warcraft'' are not permanent, as characters are resurrected shortly afterward.<ref name=\"BBCwow\">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Ward |title=Deadly plague hits Warcraft world |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4272418.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2005-09-22 |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331184723/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4272418.stm |archive-date=2019-03-31 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, dying in such a way is disadvantageous to the player's character and incurs inconvenience.<ref name=\"ign20050922\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/22/world-of-warcraft-gets-plagued |title=World of Warcraft Gets Plagued |access-date=2019-04-13 |last=McNamara |first=Tom |date=2005-09-22 |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |quote=In-game disease spreads throughout the realm. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142432/https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/22/world-of-warcraft-gets-plagued |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring the epidemic, normal gameplay was disrupted. The major towns and cities were abandoned by the population as panic set in and players rushed to evacuate to the relative safety of the countryside, leaving urban areas filled with dead player characters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-flu-virtual/online-blood-plague-offers-lessons-for-pandemics-idUKTRE53Q4HI20090427 |work=Reuters |title=Online 'blood plague' offers lessons for pandemics |date=2009-04-27 |first=Andrew |last=Marshall |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-flu-virtual/online-blood-plague-offers-lessons-for-pandemics-idUKTRE53Q4HI20090427 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPlayer responses varied but resembled real-world behaviors. Some characters with healing abilities volunteered their services, some lower-level characters who could not help would direct people away from infected areas, some characters would flee to uninfected areas, and some characters attempted to spread the disease to others.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> Players in the game reacted to the disease as if there were real risk to their well-being.<ref name=\"bbcnews20070821\">{{cite news |title=Virtual game is a 'disease model' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/6951918.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2007-08-21 |access-date=2019-04-13 |quote=An outbreak of a deadly disease in a virtual world can offer insights into real life epidemics, scientists suggest. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090127003336/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/6951918.stm |archive-date=2009-01-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> Blizzard Entertainment attempted to institute a voluntary [[quarantine]] to stem the disease, but it failed, as some players didn't take it seriously, while others took advantage of the pandemonium.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> Despite certain security measures, players overcame them by giving the disease to [[summon]]able pets.<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nBlizzard was forced to fix the problem by instituting [[hard reset]]s of the servers and applying quick fixes.<ref name=\"BBCwow\" /> The plague ended on October 8, 2005, when Blizzard made pets unable to be affected by Corrupted Blood, thereby rendering it unable to exist outside of Zul'Gurub.\n\n===Reaction===\nAt the time, ''World of Warcraft'' had more than two million players all over the world.<ref name=\"register\">{{cite web |title=World of Warcraft Plague Swamps Servers |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/09/21/wow_virtual_plague/ |first=Tony |last=Smith |website=[[The Register]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2005-09-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022125318/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/09/21/wow_virtual_plague/ |archive-date=2018-10-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> Before Blizzard Entertainment commented on the outbreak, there was debate whether it was intentional or a glitch.<ref name=\"BBCwow\" /> On Blizzard's forums, posters were commenting about how it was a fantastic world event, and calling it \"the day the plague wiped out Ironforge.\"<ref name=\"c&vg\" /> An editor of a World of Warcraft fan site described it as the first proper world event.<ref name=\"BBCwow\" /> After the incident began, Blizzard received calls from angry customers complaining about how they just died.<ref name=\"c&vg\" /> Some players abandoned the game altogether until the problem was fixed.<ref name=\"science\">{{cite magazine |title=Virtual worlds, real science: epidemiologists, social scientists flock to online world. |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Virtual+worlds%2c+real+science%3a+epidemiologists%2c+social+scientists...-a0171623497 |magazine=[[Science News]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2007-10-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Virtual%2Bworlds,%2Breal%2Bscience:%2Bepidemiologists,%2Bsocial%2Bscientists...-a0171623497 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The hard resets were described as a \"blunt ending\" by [[Gamasutra]].<ref name=\"gamasutra\" />\n\nThe people who spread the disease out of malice were described by Security Focus editor Robert Lemos as [[terrorist]]s of ''World of Warcraft''.<ref name=\"security\">{{cite web |title=Digital plague hits online game World of Warcraft |url=https://www.securityfocus.com/news/11330 |publisher=Security Focus |access-date=2019-04-13 |first=Robert |last=Lemos |date=2005-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102080027/https://www.securityfocus.com/news/11330 |archive-date=2019-11-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n[[Jeffrey Kaplan (game designer)|Jeffrey Kaplan]]\u2014a game designer for ''[[World of Warcraft]]''\u2014stated that it gave them ideas for possible real events in the future.<ref name=\"c&vg\">{{cite magazine |title=Looking Back... World of Warcraft |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=131791 |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2005-01-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219105923/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/131791/features/looking-back-world-of-warcraft/ |archive-date=2014-02-19}}</ref> Brian Martin\u2014independent security consultant for ''World of Warcraft''\u2014commented that it presented an in-game dynamic that was not expected by players or Blizzard developers and that it reminds people that even in controlled online atmospheres, unexpected consequences can occur. He also compared it to a [[computer virus]], stating that while it is not as serious, it also reminds people of the impact computer code can have on them, and they're not always safe, regardless of the precautions they take.<ref name=\"security\" />\n\n===Great Zombie Plague of '08===\nDuring one week of October 2008, a [[zombie apocalypse|zombie plague]] was spread to promote the second ''World of Warcraft'' expansion, ''[[World of Warcraft: Wrath of the Lich King|Wrath of the Lich King]]'', before its release. Unlike Corrupted Blood, this plague was intentional and was dubbed by an authorized representative of Blizzard Entertainment as the \"Great Zombie Plague of '08\".<ref name=\"Blizzard-forum\">{{cite web |url=http://forums.worldofwarcraft.com/thread.html?topicId=11829528491&postId=118283640325&sid=1#0 |title=Regarding the Zombie Plague\u2026 |author=Tigole |date=2008-10-27 |publisher=[[Blizzard Entertainment]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5tbDJnwZh?url=http://forums.worldofwarcraft.com/thread.html?topicId=11829528491&postId=118283640325&sid=1 |archive-date=2010-10-19 |access-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It was compared to Corrupted Blood by ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', which described the zombie plague as being more true-to-life. The plague was contagious, but in contrast to Corrupted Blood, which had 100% transmission to nearby characters, being in the vicinity of a character infected with the zombie plague represented only a small risk of transmission. This meant that encountering a lone zombie was not as dangerous as encountering a large mass of infected individuals.<ref name=\"times20081028\">{{cite news |title=Analysis: Absence of risk limits parallels with real life |first=Mark |last=Henderson |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/analysis-absence-of-risk-limits-parallels-with-real-life-7fcg52zqfrd |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |publisher=[[News International]] |issn=0956-1382 |date=2008-10-28 |access-date=2010-10-19 |quote=Why avoid anything like the plague if you can just come back to life? |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142435/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/analysis-absence-of-risk-limits-parallels-with-real-life-7fcg52zqfrd |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The event\u2014which Blizzard ended on 28 October\u2014earned the company both praise and criticism from its fans.<ref name=\"times20081028a\">{{cite news |title=World of Warcraft plague halted by Blizzard |first=Murad |last=Ahmed |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/world-of-warcraft-plague-halted-by-blizzard-nswlfnx3zn2 |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |publisher=[[News International]] |issn=0956-1382 |date=2008-10-28 |access-date=2019-04-13 |quote=The Warcraft's authorities have acted to control a virtual plague they released into the popular online game last week |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/world-of-warcraft-plague-halted-by-blizzard-nswlfnx3zn2 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Green fire ===\nOn 12 January 2017, lasting for a day until a [[hotfix]] was released by Blizzard,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://worldofwarcraft.com/en-gb/news/20478238/hotfixes-january-13 |title=Hotfixes January 13 |date=2017-01-13 |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328153333/https://worldofwarcraft.com/en-gb/news/20478238/hotfixes-january-13 |archive-date=2019-03-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> a plague involving a [[Debuff (MMORPG Terminology)|debuff]] called Burn, that increasingly damaged players over time, started in a boss area. The debuff could be passed between players of the same faction and could kill low-level players in a few sceonds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu.battle.net/forums/en/wow/topic/17614772510 |title=Green fire killing everyone |date=2017-01-12 |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328164807/https://eu.battle.net/forums/en/wow/topic/17614772510 |archive-date=2019-03-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> It's believed that the debuff had been taken out of the boss area by a pet. During the incident Blizzard gamemasters \"disinfected\" players and kept the plague under control.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://funnyjunk.com/channel/wow/Wow+another+blood+plague/nkqnLax/ |title=WoW, another blood plague |date=2017-01-12 |access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Models for real-world research==\n\n===Model for epidemic research===\nIn March 2007, Ran D. Balicer, an epidemiologist physician at the [[Ben-Gurion University of the Negev]] in [[Beersheba]], [[Israel]], published an article in the journal ''Epidemiology'' that described the similarities between this outbreak and the recent [[SARS]] and [[avian influenza]] outbreaks. Dr. Balicer suggested that role-playing games could serve as an advanced platform for modeling the dissemination of infectious diseases.<ref name=\"LWW\">{{cite journal |last=Balicer |first=Ran |date=2005-10-05 |doi=10.1097/01.ede.0000254692.80550.60 |title=Modeling Infectious Diseases Dissemination Through Online Role-Playing Games |journal=Epidemiology |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=260\u2013261 |pmid=17301707 }}</ref> In a follow-up article in the journal ''Science'', the game ''[[Second Life]]'' was suggested as another possible platform for these studies.<ref name=\"AAAS\">{{cite journal |date=2007-05-18 |title=Playing With Epidemics |journal=Science |volume=316 |issue=5827 |pages=961 |doi=10.1126/science.316.5827.961a}}</ref> The [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] contacted Blizzard Entertainment and requested statistics on this event for research on epidemics, but was told that it was a glitch.<ref name=\"c&vg\" />\n\nThe Corrupted Blood incident was described as a fascinating yet accidental case study of modeling disease origins and control at the Games for Health conference in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] by [[Gamasutra]].<ref name=\"gamasutra\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=18571 |title=GFH: The Real Life Lessons Of ''WoW''{{'}}s Corrupted Blood |access-date=2019-04-13 |last=Orland |first=Kyle |date=2008-05-20 |work=[[Gamasutra]] |publisher=[[Game Developer (magazine)|Game Developer]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142434/https://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php%3Fstory%3D18571 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> They compared it to a real-life epidemic, in that it originated in a remote, uninhabited region and was carried by travelers to larger regions; hosts were both human and animal, comparing it to the [[avian flu]]; was passed through close contact; and there were people, in this case non-playable characters, who could contract it but were [[asymptomatic]].<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> However, there were elements that differed from a real-world epidemic, including an indicator for carriers that they have the disease and how much risk they are at, which cannot be done in the real world.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> One aspect of the epidemic that was not considered by [[epidemiologist]]s in their models was curiosity, describing how players would rush into infected areas to witness the infection and then rush out. This was paralleled to real-world behavior, specifically with how [[journalist]]s would cover an incident, and then leave the area.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" />\n\nIn August 2007, Nina Fefferman\u2014a [[Tufts University]] assistant research professor of public health and family medicine\u2014called for research on this incident, citing the resemblances with biological plagues. Some scientists want to study how people would react to environmental [[pathogen]]s, by using the virtual counterpart as a point of reference.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web |last=Sydell |first=Laura |author-link=Laura Sydell |date=2005-10-05 |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4946772 |title='Virtual' Virus Sheds Light on Real-World Behavior |publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825055717/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4946772 |archive-date=2019-08-25 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/how-a-computer-game-glitch-could-help-to-fight-off-global-pandemic-n02w6zqjwcj |title=How a computer game glitch could help to fight off global pandemic |first=Lucy |last=Bannerman |access-date=2019-04-13 |work=The Times |date=2007-08-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722125809/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/how-a-computer-game-glitch-could-help-to-fight-off-global-pandemic-n02w6zqjwcj |archive-date=2018-07-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, she co-authored a paper in [[The Lancet|''Lancet Infectious Disease'']] discussing the epidemiological and disease modeling implications of the outbreak, along with Eric Lofgren, a [[University of North Carolina]] graduate student.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lofgren |first1=Eric T. |last2=Fefferman |first2=Nina H. |title=The untapped potential of virtual game worlds to shed light on real world epidemics |journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(07)70212-8/fulltext |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2007-09-01 |volume=7 |issue=9 |pages=625\u2013629 |doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(07)70212-8 |pmid=17714675 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124083048/http://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(07)70212-8/fulltext |archive-date=2010-01-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> She spoke at the 2008 [[Games for Health]] conference in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] and the 2011 [[Game Developers Conference]] about the incident and how massively multiplayer online populations could solve the problems inherent with more traditional models of epidemics.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Graft |first=Kris |date=2011-02-28 |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/33276/gdc_2011_an_epidemiologists_view_.php |title=GDC 2011: An Epidemiologist's View Of ''World Of Warcraft''{{'}}s Corrupted Blood Plague |website=[[Gamasutra]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/33276/gdc_2011_an_epidemiologists_view_.php |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFefferman added that the three base models have their strengths and weaknesses, but make significant behavioral assumptions. She also compared Corrupted Blood to a [[drug trial]] with mice\u2014\"a real good first step.\" She stated, \"These are my mice [and] I want this to be my new experiment setup.\" She expressed an interest in designing new diseases, perhaps non-fatal ones, to be introduced to the game so she could study how risk is viewed, how rumors would spread, and how public health notices are handled. She added that Blizzard made such notices in the original outbreak, but kept changing its position as it could not effectively deal with the problem. She commented that she did not believe it would ruin gameplay, as ''World of Warcraft'' dealt with health challenges in combat, and that games set in medieval times had such health risk. She argued that if researchers and developers worked together, it could be fun. While Blizzard was initially excited about the proposition, it became less outwardly excited over time, though never rejected it. She has been in contact with other developers, hoping to conduct the simulation in games similar to ''World of Warcraft''.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" />\n\nDr. Gary Smith, professor of Population Biology and Epidemiology at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], commented that very few mathematical models of disease transmission take host behavior into account, but also questioned how representative of real life a virtual model could be. He stated that while the characteristics of the disease could be defined beforehand, the study is just as observational as one conducted on a real-life disease outbreak. However, he added that one could argue that the proposal could give an opportunity for a study that epidemiologists may never have.<ref name=\"bbcnews20070821\"/> Neil Ferguson, director of the MRC Centre for Outbreak Analysis and Modelling at Imperial College, London, felt skeptical of the idea, commenting that such a study could not properly mimic genuine behavior. Using the zombie plague used to promote ''[[World of Warcraft: Wrath of the Lich King]]'' before its release as an example, players would intentionally become infected to gain zombie powers. He added that characters could also regenerate, meaning there was low risk in becoming infected. He felt that while online games such as ''World of Warcraft'' could be set up to help scientists study epidemics, it will always be limited as their primary use is for entertainment.<ref name=\"times20081028a\" />\n\n===Comparison to COVID-19 pandemic===\nThe [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] has been compared to the Corrupted Blood incident, and epidemologists who studied the Corrupted Blood outbreak are using the research from the incident to better understand coronavirus' spread - primarily its sociological factors.<ref name=pcgamer /><ref name=pcgamesN /><ref name=extremetech /><ref name=arstechnica /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Krotoski |first1=Aleks |title=Corrupted Blood: what the virus that took down World of Warcraft can tell us about coronavirus |url=https://www.sciencefocus.com/the-human-body/corrupted-blood-what-the-virus-that-took-down-world-of-warcraft-can-tell-us-about-coronavirus/ |website=BBC Science Focus |publisher=Immediate Media Company |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Dr. Eric Lofgren, an epidemologist and co-author of a research paper about Corrupted Blood, stated in an interview with ''[[PC Gamer]]'' that  \"When people react to public health emergencies, how those reactions really shape the course of things. We often view epidemics as these things that sort of ''happen'' to people. There's a virus and it's doing things. But really it's a virus that's spreading between people, and how people interact and behave and comply with authority figures, or don't, those are all very important things. And also that these things are very chaotic. You can't really predict 'oh yeah, everyone will quarantine. It'll be fine.' No, they won't.\"<ref name=pcgamer /><ref name=pcgamesN /><ref name=extremetech>{{cite web |last1=Hruska |first1=Joel |title=Researchers Are Dusting Off WoW\u2019s Corrupted Blood Plague to Understand Coronavirus Infections |url=https://www.extremetech.com/gaming/307717-researchers-wow-corrupted-blood-plague-to-understand-coronavirus-infections |website=ExtremeTech |publisher=Ziff Davis Media |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=arstechnica /> [[Griefer|Griefing]], such as players intentionally spreading Corrupted Blood to others, was one of the aspects of the Corrupted Blood study that has been criticized as lacking a real-world basis; Dr. Lofgren expressed in the wake of the coronavirus epidemic that \"one of the critiques we got from a lot of people, both gamers and scientists, was over this idea of griefing, ... How griefing isn't really analogous to anything that takes place in the real world. People aren't intentionally getting people sick. And they might not be ''intentionally'' getting people sick, but wilfully ignoring your potential to get people sick is pretty close to that. You start to see people like 'oh this isn't a big deal, I'm not going to change my behavior.' ... Epidemics are a social problem... Minimizing the seriousness of something is sort of real-world griefing.\"<ref name=pcgamer />\n\nThe Corrupted Blood incident was abrupt and far-reaching; Dr. Lofgren expressed that this abruptness is a property of a real pandemic, stating \"Corrupted Blood was this unexpected black swan event. We treat this [coronavirus] as if it's unexpected, but nature is really good at getting people sick\".<ref name=pcgamer /><ref name=arstechnica /> Dr. Nina Fefferman, a co-author of the Corrupted Blood study, expressed that the incident particularly exemplified \"how people perceive threats and how differences in that perception can change how they behave\", and how people discuss a threat on social media, stating that \"A lot of my work since then has been in trying to build models of the social construction of risk perception and I don't think I would have come to that as easily if I hadn't spent time thinking about the discussions ''WoW'' players had in real time about Corrupted Blood and how to act in the game based on the understanding they built from those discussions.\"<ref name=pcgamer>{{cite web |last1=Fenlon |first1=Wes |title=The researchers who once studied WoW's Corrupted Blood plague are now fighting the coronavirus |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-researchers-who-once-studied-wows-corrupted-blood-plague-are-now-fighting-the-coronavirus/ |website=PC Gamer |publisher=Future plc |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=pcgamesN>{{cite web |last1=Maskell |first1=Ryan |title=The doctors who studied WoW\u2019s virtual blood plague warn of the reality of coronavirus |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/world-of-warcraft/blood-plague-coronavirus |website=PCGamesN |publisher=Network N |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=arstechnica>{{cite web |last1=Ouellette |first1=Jennifer |title=What a WoW virtual outbreak taught us about how humans behave in epidemics |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/that-time-world-of-warcraft-helped-epidemiologists-model-an-outbreak/ |website=Ars Technica |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Model for terrorism research===\nIn an analysis of the Corrupted Blood incident, [[Charles Blair (intelligence analyst)|Charles Blair]], deputy director of the Center of Terrorism and Intelligence Studies, said that ''World of Warcraft'' could provide a powerful new way to study how [[terrorist cell]]s form and operate. While his organization already uses computer models to study terrorists' tactics, Blair explained that because ''World of Warcraft'' involves real people making real decisions in a world with controllable bounds, it could provide a more realistic models for military intelligence analysts.<ref name= \"wired\">{{cite journal |title=''World of Warcraft'' Shines Light on Terror Tactics |first=David |last=Thier |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/03/wow-terror/ |journal=[[Wired.com]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2008-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805135433/https://www.wired.com/2008/03/wow-terror/ |archive-date=2019-08-05 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Yale University]] terrorism expert Stuart Gottlieb admitted that while the outbreak was interesting and relevant to the times, he would not base a counter-terrorism strategy on a video game. Gottlieb expressed skepticism that analyzing the incident could shed light on the complex underlying causes of terrorism in the real world, as the stakes for both terrorists and civilians are lowered in a virtual setting. However, as commented by the editor of the article, \"the biggest weakness for using a game as an analytical tool is that death in ''World of Warcraft'' is a nuisance at most\".<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nBlizzard has maintained a position that ''World of Warcraft'' is first and foremost a game, and that it was never designed to mirror reality or anything in the real world.<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wowpedia|Corrupted Blood (debuff)}}\n\n{{Warcraft universe}}\n{{Video game controversy}}\n\n[[Category:Video game controversies]]\n[[Category:Fictional diseases and disorders]]\n[[Category:Video game glitches]]\n[[Category:World of Warcraft]]\n[[Category:2005 in video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Incident in World of Warcraft}}\n{{About|a virtual plague|the legal concept \"corruption of blood\"|Attainder}}\n[[File:Corrupted_blood_(World_Of_Warcraft).jpg|thumb|right|The Corrupted Blood debuff.]]\n[[Image:WoW Corrupted Blood Plague.jpg|right|256px|thumb|The Corrupted Blood debuff being spread among characters in Ironforge, one of ''World of Warcraft's'' in-game cities.]]\n\nThe '''Corrupted Blood incident''' was a virtual [[pandemic]] in the [[MMORPG]] ''[[World of Warcraft]]'', which began on September 13, 2005, and lasted for one week. The epidemic began with the introduction of the new [[raid (gaming)|raid]] Zul'Gurub and its [[boss (video gaming)|end boss]] Hakkar the Soulflayer. When confronted and attacked, Hakkar would cast a [[Health (gaming)|hit point]]-draining and highly contagious [[debuff]] spell called \"Corrupted Blood\" on players.\n\nThe spell, intended to last only seconds and function only within the new area of Zul'Gurub, soon spread across the [[virtual world]] by way of an oversight that allowed pets and minions to take the affliction out of its intended confines. By both accidental and purposeful intent, a pandemic ensued that quickly killed lower-level characters and drastically changed normal gameplay, as players did what they could do to avoid infection. Despite measures such as programmer-imposed quarantines, and the players' abandoning of densely populated cities (or even just not playing the game), it lasted until a combination of patches and resets of the virtual world finally controlled the spread.\n\nThe conditions and reactions of the event attracted the attention of [[epidemiology|epidemiologists]] for its implications of how human populations could react to a real-world epidemic.\n\n==History==\nThe epidemic began on September 13, 2005, when [[Blizzard Entertainment|Blizzard]] introduced a new raid called Zul'Gurub into the game as part of a new update. Its end boss, Hakkar the Soulflayer, could affect players by draining their blood and using it to heal himself. By intentionally poisoning one's own blood using a debuff called Corrupted Blood, which did a significant amount of damage to the player over time, Hakkar would drain blood and apply the disease to himself, allowing him to be killed. However, Corrupted Blood could be passed on between any nearby characters, and would kill characters of lower levels in a few seconds, while higher level characters could keep themselves alive. It would disappear as time passed or when the character died.\n\nDue to a programming oversight, when hunters or warlocks dismissed their pets, those pets would keep any active debuffs when summoned again. [[Non-player character]]s could contract the debuff, and could not be killed by it but could still spread it to players; in effect, this turned them into [[asymptomatic]] disease carriers and a form of [[Vector (epidemiology)|vector]] for the debuff.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> At least three of the game's servers were affected. The difficulty in killing Hakkar may have limited the spread of the disease. Discussion forum posters described seeing hundreds of bodies lying in the streets of the towns and cities. Deaths in ''World of Warcraft'' are not permanent, as characters are resurrected shortly afterward.<ref name=\"BBCwow\">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Ward |title=Deadly plague hits Warcraft world |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4272418.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2005-09-22 |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331184723/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/4272418.stm |archive-date=2019-03-31 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, dying in such a way is disadvantageous to the player's character and incurs inconvenience.<ref name=\"ign20050922\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/22/world-of-warcraft-gets-plagued |title=World of Warcraft Gets Plagued |access-date=2019-04-13 |last=McNamara |first=Tom |date=2005-09-22 |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |quote=In-game disease spreads throughout the realm. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142432/https://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/22/world-of-warcraft-gets-plagued |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring the epidemic, normal gameplay was disrupted. The major towns and cities were abandoned by the population as panic set in and players rushed to evacuate to the relative safety of the countryside, leaving urban areas filled with dead player characters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-flu-virtual/online-blood-plague-offers-lessons-for-pandemics-idUKTRE53Q4HI20090427 |work=Reuters |title=Online 'blood plague' offers lessons for pandemics |date=2009-04-27 |first=Andrew |last=Marshall |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-flu-virtual/online-blood-plague-offers-lessons-for-pandemics-idUKTRE53Q4HI20090427 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPlayer responses varied but resembled real-world behaviors. Some characters with healing abilities volunteered their services, some lower-level characters who could not help would direct people away from infected areas, some characters would flee to uninfected areas, and some characters attempted to spread the disease to others.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> Players in the game reacted to the disease as if there were real risk to their well-being.<ref name=\"bbcnews20070821\">{{cite news |title=Virtual game is a 'disease model' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/6951918.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2007-08-21 |access-date=2019-04-13 |quote=An outbreak of a deadly disease in a virtual world can offer insights into real life epidemics, scientists suggest. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090127003336/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/6951918.stm |archive-date=2009-01-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> Blizzard Entertainment attempted to institute a voluntary [[quarantine]] to stem the disease, but it failed, as some players didn't take it seriously, while others took advantage of the pandemonium.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> Despite certain security measures, players overcame them by giving the disease to [[summon]]able pets.<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nBlizzard was forced to fix the problem by instituting [[hard reset]]s of the servers and applying quick fixes.<ref name=\"BBCwow\" /> The plague ended on October 8, 2005, when Blizzard made pets unable to be affected by Corrupted Blood, thereby rendering it unable to exist outside of Zul'Gurub.\n\n===Reaction===\nAt the time, ''World of Warcraft'' had more than two million players all over the world.<ref name=\"register\">{{cite web |title=World of Warcraft Plague Swamps Servers |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/09/21/wow_virtual_plague/ |first=Tony |last=Smith |website=[[The Register]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2005-09-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022125318/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/09/21/wow_virtual_plague/ |archive-date=2018-10-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> Before Blizzard Entertainment commented on the outbreak, there was debate whether it was intentional or a glitch.<ref name=\"BBCwow\" /> On Blizzard's forums, posters were commenting about how it was a fantastic world event, and calling it \"the day the plague wiped out Ironforge.\"<ref name=\"c&vg\" /> An editor of a World of Warcraft fan site described it as the first proper world event.<ref name=\"BBCwow\" /> After the incident began, Blizzard received calls from angry customers complaining about how they just died.<ref name=\"c&vg\" /> Some players abandoned the game altogether until the problem was fixed.<ref name=\"science\">{{cite magazine |title=Virtual worlds, real science: epidemiologists, social scientists flock to online world. |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Virtual+worlds%2c+real+science%3a+epidemiologists%2c+social+scientists...-a0171623497 |magazine=[[Science News]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2007-10-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Virtual%2Bworlds,%2Breal%2Bscience:%2Bepidemiologists,%2Bsocial%2Bscientists...-a0171623497 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The hard resets were described as a \"blunt ending\" by [[Gamasutra]].<ref name=\"gamasutra\" />\n\nThe people who spread the disease out of malice were described by Security Focus editor Robert Lemos as [[terrorist]]s of ''World of Warcraft''.<ref name=\"security\">{{cite web |title=Digital plague hits online game World of Warcraft |url=https://www.securityfocus.com/news/11330 |publisher=Security Focus |access-date=2019-04-13 |first=Robert |last=Lemos |date=2005-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102080027/https://www.securityfocus.com/news/11330 |archive-date=2019-11-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n[[Jeffrey Kaplan (game designer)|Jeffrey Kaplan]]\u2014a game designer for ''[[World of Warcraft]]''\u2014stated that it gave them ideas for possible real events in the future.<ref name=\"c&vg\">{{cite magazine |title=Looking Back... World of Warcraft |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=131791 |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2005-01-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219105923/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/131791/features/looking-back-world-of-warcraft/ |archive-date=2014-02-19}}</ref> Brian Martin\u2014independent security consultant for ''World of Warcraft''\u2014commented that it presented an in-game dynamic that was not expected by players or Blizzard developers and that it reminds people that even in controlled online atmospheres, unexpected consequences can occur. He also compared it to a [[computer virus]], stating that while it is not as serious, it also reminds people of the impact computer code can have on them, and they're not always safe, regardless of the precautions they take.<ref name=\"security\" />\n\n===Great Zombie Plague of '08===\nDuring one week of October 2008, a [[zombie apocalypse|zombie plague]] was spread to promote the second ''World of Warcraft'' expansion, ''[[World of Warcraft: Wrath of the Lich King|Wrath of the Lich King]]'', before its release. Unlike Corrupted Blood, this plague was intentional and was dubbed by an authorized representative of Blizzard Entertainment as the \"Great Zombie Plague of '08\".<ref name=\"Blizzard-forum\">{{cite web |url=http://forums.worldofwarcraft.com/thread.html?topicId=11829528491&postId=118283640325&sid=1#0 |title=Regarding the Zombie Plague\u2026 |author=Tigole |date=2008-10-27 |publisher=[[Blizzard Entertainment]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5tbDJnwZh?url=http://forums.worldofwarcraft.com/thread.html?topicId=11829528491&postId=118283640325&sid=1 |archive-date=2010-10-19 |access-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It was compared to Corrupted Blood by ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', which described the zombie plague as being more true-to-life. The plague was contagious, but in contrast to Corrupted Blood, which had 100% transmission to nearby characters, being in the vicinity of a character infected with the zombie plague represented only a small risk of transmission. This meant that encountering a lone zombie was not as dangerous as encountering a large mass of infected individuals.<ref name=\"times20081028\">{{cite news |title=Analysis: Absence of risk limits parallels with real life |first=Mark |last=Henderson |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/analysis-absence-of-risk-limits-parallels-with-real-life-7fcg52zqfrd |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |publisher=[[News International]] |issn=0956-1382 |date=2008-10-28 |access-date=2010-10-19 |quote=Why avoid anything like the plague if you can just come back to life? |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142435/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/analysis-absence-of-risk-limits-parallels-with-real-life-7fcg52zqfrd |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> The event\u2014which Blizzard ended on 28 October\u2014earned the company both praise and criticism from its fans.<ref name=\"times20081028a\">{{cite news |title=World of Warcraft plague halted by Blizzard |first=Murad |last=Ahmed |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/world-of-warcraft-plague-halted-by-blizzard-nswlfnx3zn2 |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |publisher=[[News International]] |issn=0956-1382 |date=2008-10-28 |access-date=2019-04-13 |quote=The Warcraft's authorities have acted to control a virtual plague they released into the popular online game last week |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/world-of-warcraft-plague-halted-by-blizzard-nswlfnx3zn2 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Green fire ===\nOn 12 January 2017, lasting for a day until a [[hotfix]] was released by Blizzard,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://worldofwarcraft.com/en-gb/news/20478238/hotfixes-january-13 |title=Hotfixes January 13 |date=2017-01-13 |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328153333/https://worldofwarcraft.com/en-gb/news/20478238/hotfixes-january-13 |archive-date=2019-03-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> a plague involving a [[Debuff (MMORPG Terminology)|debuff]] called Burn, that increasingly damaged players over time, started in a boss area. The debuff could be passed between players of the same faction and could kill low-level players in a few sceonds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu.battle.net/forums/en/wow/topic/17614772510 |title=Green fire killing everyone |date=2017-01-12 |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328164807/https://eu.battle.net/forums/en/wow/topic/17614772510 |archive-date=2019-03-28 |url-status=live }}</ref> It's believed that the debuff had been taken out of the instance by a [[Hunter (World of Warcraft)|hunter]] pet. During the incident Blizzard gamemasters \"disinfected\" players and kept the plague under control.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://funnyjunk.com/channel/wow/Wow+another+blood+plague/nkqnLax/ |title=WoW, another blood plague |date=2017-01-12 |access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Models for real-world research==\n\n===Model for epidemic research===\nIn March 2007, Ran D. Balicer, an epidemiologist physician at the [[Ben-Gurion University of the Negev]] in [[Beersheba]], [[Israel]], published an article in the journal ''Epidemiology'' that described the similarities between this outbreak and the recent [[SARS]] and [[avian influenza]] outbreaks. Dr. Balicer suggested that role-playing games could serve as an advanced platform for modeling the dissemination of infectious diseases.<ref name=\"LWW\">{{cite journal |last=Balicer |first=Ran |date=2005-10-05 |doi=10.1097/01.ede.0000254692.80550.60 |title=Modeling Infectious Diseases Dissemination Through Online Role-Playing Games |journal=Epidemiology |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=260\u2013261 |pmid=17301707 }}</ref> In a follow-up article in the journal ''Science'', the game ''[[Second Life]]'' was suggested as another possible platform for these studies.<ref name=\"AAAS\">{{cite journal |date=2007-05-18 |title=Playing With Epidemics |journal=Science |volume=316 |issue=5827 |pages=961 |doi=10.1126/science.316.5827.961a}}</ref> The [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] contacted Blizzard Entertainment and requested statistics on this event for research on epidemics, but was told that it was a glitch.<ref name=\"c&vg\" />\n\nThe Corrupted Blood incident was described as a fascinating yet accidental case study of modeling disease origins and control at the Games for Health conference in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] by [[Gamasutra]].<ref name=\"gamasutra\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=18571 |title=GFH: The Real Life Lessons Of ''WoW''{{'}}s Corrupted Blood |access-date=2019-04-13 |last=Orland |first=Kyle |date=2008-05-20 |work=[[Gamasutra]] |publisher=[[Game Developer (magazine)|Game Developer]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142434/https://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php%3Fstory%3D18571 |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> They compared it to a real-life epidemic, in that it originated in a remote, uninhabited region and was carried by travelers to larger regions; hosts were both human and animal, comparing it to the [[avian flu]]; was passed through close contact; and there were people, in this case non-playable characters, who could contract it but were [[asymptomatic]].<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> However, there were elements that differed from a real-world epidemic, including an indicator for carriers that they have the disease and how much risk they are at, which cannot be done in the real world.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /> One aspect of the epidemic that was not considered by [[epidemiologist]]s in their models was curiosity, describing how players would rush into infected areas to witness the infection and then rush out. This was paralleled to real-world behavior, specifically with how [[journalist]]s would cover an incident, and then leave the area.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" />\n\nIn August 2007, Nina Fefferman\u2014a [[Tufts University]] assistant research professor of public health and family medicine\u2014called for research on this incident, citing the resemblances with biological plagues. Some scientists want to study how people would react to environmental [[pathogen]]s, by using the virtual counterpart as a point of reference.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web |last=Sydell |first=Laura |author-link=Laura Sydell |date=2005-10-05 |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4946772 |title='Virtual' Virus Sheds Light on Real-World Behavior |publisher=[[National Public Radio|NPR]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825055717/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4946772 |archive-date=2019-08-25 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/how-a-computer-game-glitch-could-help-to-fight-off-global-pandemic-n02w6zqjwcj |title=How a computer game glitch could help to fight off global pandemic |first=Lucy |last=Bannerman |access-date=2019-04-13 |work=The Times |date=2007-08-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722125809/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/how-a-computer-game-glitch-could-help-to-fight-off-global-pandemic-n02w6zqjwcj |archive-date=2018-07-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, she co-authored a paper in [[The Lancet|''Lancet Infectious Disease'']] discussing the epidemiological and disease modeling implications of the outbreak, along with Eric Lofgren, a [[University of North Carolina]] graduate student.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lofgren |first1=Eric T. |last2=Fefferman |first2=Nina H. |title=The untapped potential of virtual game worlds to shed light on real world epidemics |journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(07)70212-8/fulltext |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2007-09-01 |volume=7 |issue=9 |pages=625\u2013629 |doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(07)70212-8 |pmid=17714675 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124083048/http://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(07)70212-8/fulltext |archive-date=2010-01-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> She spoke at the 2008 [[Games for Health]] conference in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] and the 2011 [[Game Developers Conference]] about the incident and how massively multiplayer online populations could solve the problems inherent with more traditional models of epidemics.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Graft |first=Kris |date=2011-02-28 |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/33276/gdc_2011_an_epidemiologists_view_.php |title=GDC 2011: An Epidemiologist's View Of ''World Of Warcraft''{{'}}s Corrupted Blood Plague |website=[[Gamasutra]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413142436/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/33276/gdc_2011_an_epidemiologists_view_.php |archive-date=2019-04-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFefferman added that the three base models have their strengths and weaknesses, but make significant behavioral assumptions. She also compared Corrupted Blood to a [[drug trial]] with mice\u2014\"a real good first step.\" She stated, \"These are my mice [and] I want this to be my new experiment setup.\" She expressed an interest in designing new diseases, perhaps non-fatal ones, to be introduced to the game so she could study how risk is viewed, how rumors would spread, and how public health notices are handled. She added that Blizzard made such notices in the original outbreak, but kept changing its position as it could not effectively deal with the problem. She commented that she did not believe it would ruin gameplay, as ''World of Warcraft'' dealt with health challenges in combat, and that games set in medieval times had such health risk. She argued that if researchers and developers worked together, it could be fun. While Blizzard was initially excited about the proposition, it became less outwardly excited over time, though never rejected it. She has been in contact with other developers, hoping to conduct the simulation in games similar to ''World of Warcraft''.<ref name=\"gamasutra\" />\n\nDr. Gary Smith, professor of Population Biology and Epidemiology at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], commented that very few mathematical models of disease transmission take host behavior into account, but also questioned how representative of real life a virtual model could be. He stated that while the characteristics of the disease could be defined beforehand, the study is just as observational as one conducted on a real-life disease outbreak. However, he added that one could argue that the proposal could give an opportunity for a study that epidemiologists may never have.<ref name=\"bbcnews20070821\"/> Neil Ferguson, director of the MRC Centre for Outbreak Analysis and Modelling at Imperial College, London, felt skeptical of the idea, commenting that such a study could not properly mimic genuine behavior. Using the zombie plague used to promote ''[[World of Warcraft: Wrath of the Lich King]]'' before its release as an example, players would intentionally become infected to gain zombie powers. He added that characters could also regenerate, meaning there was low risk in becoming infected. He felt that while online games such as ''World of Warcraft'' could be set up to help scientists study epidemics, it will always be limited as their primary use is for entertainment.<ref name=\"times20081028a\" />\n\n===Comparison to COVID-19 pandemic===\nThe [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] has been compared to the Corrupted Blood incident, and epidemologists who studied the Corrupted Blood outbreak are using the research from the incident to better understand coronavirus' spread - primarily its sociological factors.<ref name=pcgamer /><ref name=pcgamesN /><ref name=extremetech /><ref name=arstechnica /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Krotoski |first1=Aleks |title=Corrupted Blood: what the virus that took down World of Warcraft can tell us about coronavirus |url=https://www.sciencefocus.com/the-human-body/corrupted-blood-what-the-virus-that-took-down-world-of-warcraft-can-tell-us-about-coronavirus/ |website=BBC Science Focus |publisher=Immediate Media Company |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Dr. Eric Lofgren, an epidemologist and co-author of a research paper about Corrupted Blood, stated in an interview with ''[[PC Gamer]]'' that  \"When people react to public health emergencies, how those reactions really shape the course of things. We often view epidemics as these things that sort of ''happen'' to people. There's a virus and it's doing things. But really it's a virus that's spreading between people, and how people interact and behave and comply with authority figures, or don't, those are all very important things. And also that these things are very chaotic. You can't really predict 'oh yeah, everyone will quarantine. It'll be fine.' No, they won't.\"<ref name=pcgamer /><ref name=pcgamesN /><ref name=extremetech>{{cite web |last1=Hruska |first1=Joel |title=Researchers Are Dusting Off WoW\u2019s Corrupted Blood Plague to Understand Coronavirus Infections |url=https://www.extremetech.com/gaming/307717-researchers-wow-corrupted-blood-plague-to-understand-coronavirus-infections |website=ExtremeTech |publisher=Ziff Davis Media |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=arstechnica /> [[Griefer|Griefing]], such as players intentionally spreading Corrupted Blood to others, was one of the aspects of the Corrupted Blood study that has been criticized as lacking a real-world basis; Dr. Lofgren expressed in the wake of the coronavirus epidemic that \"one of the critiques we got from a lot of people, both gamers and scientists, was over this idea of griefing, ... How griefing isn't really analogous to anything that takes place in the real world. People aren't intentionally getting people sick. And they might not be ''intentionally'' getting people sick, but wilfully ignoring your potential to get people sick is pretty close to that. You start to see people like 'oh this isn't a big deal, I'm not going to change my behavior.' ... Epidemics are a social problem... Minimizing the seriousness of something is sort of real-world griefing.\"<ref name=pcgamer />\n\nThe Corrupted Blood incident was abrupt and far-reaching; Dr. Lofgren expressed that this abruptness is a property of a real pandemic, stating \"Corrupted Blood was this unexpected black swan event. We treat this [coronavirus] as if it's unexpected, but nature is really good at getting people sick\".<ref name=pcgamer /><ref name=arstechnica /> Dr. Nina Fefferman, a co-author of the Corrupted Blood study, expressed that the incident particularly exemplified \"how people perceive threats and how differences in that perception can change how they behave\", and how people discuss a threat on social media, stating that \"A lot of my work since then has been in trying to build models of the social construction of risk perception and I don't think I would have come to that as easily if I hadn't spent time thinking about the discussions ''WoW'' players had in real time about Corrupted Blood and how to act in the game based on the understanding they built from those discussions.\"<ref name=pcgamer>{{cite web |last1=Fenlon |first1=Wes |title=The researchers who once studied WoW's Corrupted Blood plague are now fighting the coronavirus |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-researchers-who-once-studied-wows-corrupted-blood-plague-are-now-fighting-the-coronavirus/ |website=PC Gamer |publisher=Future plc |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=pcgamesN>{{cite web |last1=Maskell |first1=Ryan |title=The doctors who studied WoW\u2019s virtual blood plague warn of the reality of coronavirus |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/world-of-warcraft/blood-plague-coronavirus |website=PCGamesN |publisher=Network N |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=arstechnica>{{cite web |last1=Ouellette |first1=Jennifer |title=What a WoW virtual outbreak taught us about how humans behave in epidemics |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/that-time-world-of-warcraft-helped-epidemiologists-model-an-outbreak/ |website=Ars Technica |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Model for terrorism research===\nIn an analysis of the Corrupted Blood incident, [[Charles Blair (intelligence analyst)|Charles Blair]], deputy director of the Center of Terrorism and Intelligence Studies, said that ''World of Warcraft'' could provide a powerful new way to study how [[terrorist cell]]s form and operate. While his organization already uses computer models to study terrorists' tactics, Blair explained that because ''World of Warcraft'' involves real people making real decisions in a world with controllable bounds, it could provide a more realistic models for military intelligence analysts.<ref name= \"wired\">{{cite journal |title=''World of Warcraft'' Shines Light on Terror Tactics |first=David |last=Thier |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/03/wow-terror/ |journal=[[Wired.com]] |access-date=2019-04-13 |date=2008-03-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805135433/https://www.wired.com/2008/03/wow-terror/ |archive-date=2019-08-05 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Yale University]] terrorism expert Stuart Gottlieb admitted that while the outbreak was interesting and relevant to the times, he would not base a counter-terrorism strategy on a video game. Gottlieb expressed skepticism that analyzing the incident could shed light on the complex underlying causes of terrorism in the real world, as the stakes for both terrorists and civilians are lowered in a virtual setting. However, as commented by the editor of the article, \"the biggest weakness for using a game as an analytical tool is that death in ''World of Warcraft'' is a nuisance at most\".<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nBlizzard has maintained a position that ''World of Warcraft'' is first and foremost a game, and that it was never designed to mirror reality or anything in the real world.<ref name=\"wired\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wowpedia|Corrupted Blood (debuff)}}\n\n{{Warcraft universe}}\n{{Video game controversy}}\n\n[[Category:Video game controversies]]\n[[Category:Fictional diseases and disorders]]\n[[Category:Video game glitches]]\n[[Category:World of Warcraft]]\n[[Category:2005 in video games]]\n", "name_user": "Th1rt3en", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGreen fire", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corrupted_Blood_incident"}
{"title_page": "Ane Iriarte", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Ane Iriarte\n| image          = 2017 UEC Track Elite European Championships 088.jpg\n| caption        = Iriarte in 2017\n| fullname       = Ane Iriarte Lasa\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1995|4|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Villabona]], Spain\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = {{ubl|Road|Track}}\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 2018\n| proteam1       = {{ct|BDP|2018}}\n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n{{spanish name|Iriarte|Lasa}}\n'''Ane Iriarte Lasa''' (born 4 April 1995) is a Spanish [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]], who last rode for [[UCI Women's Team]] {{ct|BDP|2018}}.<ref name=\"PCS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/ane-iriarte |title=Ane Iriarte |accessdate=28 February 2018 |work=Pro Cycling Stats}}</ref> She rode in the [[2018 UCI Track Cycling World Championships \u2013 Women's scratch|women's scratch event]] at the [[2018 UCI Track Cycling World Championships]].<ref>[http://www.tissottiming.com/File/0003100002020301FFFFFFFFFFFFFF01 Start list]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Procyclingstats}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iriarte, Ane}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish female cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Tolosaldea]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gipuzkoa]]\n[[Category:Basque cyclists]]\n{{Spain-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Ane Iriarte\n| image          = 2017 UEC Track Elite European Championships 088.jpg\n| caption        = Iriarte in 2017\n| fullname       = Ane Iriarte Lasa\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1995|4|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Villabona]], Spain\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = {{ubl|Road|Track}}\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 2018\n| proteam1       = {{ct|BDP|2018}}\n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n{{spanish name|Iriarte|Lasa}}\n'''Ane Iriarte Lasa''' (born 4 April 1995) is a Spanish [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]], who last rode for [[UCI Women's Team]] {{ct|BDP|2018}}.<ref name=\"PCS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/ane-iriarte |title=Ane Iriarte |accessdate=28 February 2018 |work=Pro Cycling Stats}}</ref> She rode in the [[2018 UCI Track Cycling World Championships \u2013 Women's scratch|women's scratch event]] at the [[2018 UCI Track Cycling World Championships]].<ref>[http://www.tissottiming.com/File/0003100002020301FFFFFFFFFFFFFF01 Start list]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Procyclingstats}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iriarte, Ane}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish female cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Tolosaldea]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gipuzkoa]]\n[[Category:Basque cyclists]]\n{{Spain-cycling-bio-1990s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ane_Iriarte"}
{"title_page": "Long Eaton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name = Long Eaton\n|country = England\n|region = East Midlands\n|population = 37,760\n|population_ref = (2011)\n|os_grid_reference = SK 49033 33679 \n|coordinates = {{coord|52.898|-1.271|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type = Elkinshire\n|post_town = NOTTINGHAM\n|postcode_area = NG\n|postcode_district = NG10\n|dial_code = 0115\n|constituency_westminster = [[Erewash (UK Parliament constituency)|Erewash]]\n|civil_parish = \n|shire_district = [[Borough of Erewash|Erewash]]\n|shire_county = [[Derbyshire]]\n|static_image_name = HSBC, Market Place, Long Eaton, Derbyshire.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Market Place, Long Eaton\n}}\n'''Long Eaton''' is a town in the [[Borough of Erewash|Erewash]] district of [[Derbyshire]], England, just north of the [[River Trent]] about {{convert|7|mi|km}} south-west of [[Nottingham]] and some {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} south-east of [[Derby]]. The population was 37,760 at the 2011 census.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/uk-england-eastmidlands.php?cityid=E35000992 |title=Town population 2011 |accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref> Since 1 April 1974, Long Eaton has been part of [[Borough of Erewash|Erewash]] borough, after the dissolution of the [[Long Eaton Urban District]] Council.\n\n==History==\nLong Eaton is referred to as ''Aitone'', in the ''[[Domesday Book]]''. Several meanings are associated with the name, for example \"farm between streams\" or \"low-lying land\". This farming settlement grew up close to the lowest bridging point of the [[River Erewash]].\n\nThe \"Great Fire of Long Eaton\" ripped through 14 houses and several other buildings in the market place in 1694.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.long-eaton.com/timeline.asp |title=The Long Eaton & Sawley Archive |publisher=Long-eaton.com |date=}}</ref>\n\nThe village remained a constant size until the coming of the [[Midland Counties Railway]] in 1839 and the [[Erewash Valley Line]] in 1844, which brought links that encouraged growth. Two industries came to employ many people in the growing town: [[lace|lace-making]] and [[Goods wagon|railway wagon]] manufacturing. A large railway yard at [[Toton TMD|Toton Sidings]] grew up just north of the town.\n\nBy 1900 the town had grown to have a population of over 10,000. It had expanded with the construction of many new houses, business premises and factories throughout the Victorian period. In 1921 Long Eaton's boundaries were extended bringing Wilsthorpe and parts of both [[Sandiacre]] and Sawley into the town.\n\n==Twin towns==\n*{{flagicon|Centre}} [[Romorantin-Lanthenay]], {{flagicon|France}} France\n*{{flagicon|Hesse}} [[Langen, Hesse|Langen]], {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany <ref>{{Cite book|title=Langen im Herzen Europas|last=Bremer|first=J\u00fcrgen|publisher=J\u00fcrgen Bremer in collaboration with municipal authority of Langen and Langener Stadtinitiative for history and culture|year=2010|isbn=978-3-00-033328-6|location=Langen (Hessen)|pages=220\u2013221|language=German, English, French, Spanish, Turkish|trans-title=Langen in the heart of Europe|chapter=Long Eaton}}</ref>\n\n==Notable architecture==\n[[File:Long Eaton Hall, Long Eaton, Derbyshire.jpg|thumb|right|Long Eaton Hall (built c.1778)]]\nA notable building in the town is the [[Palladian architecture|Palladian]] Long Eaton Hall. This was originally a private residence, but is now occupied by the borough council, and is attached to the Long Eaton Town Hall complex, which opened in 1991.\n\nThe [[St. Laurence's Church, Long Eaton|Parish Church of St Laurence]] stands to the east of the Market Place. Local tradition dates parts of the church to the 11th century, possibly built under Viking King of [[Denmark]] [[King Cnut|Cnut]]. Whilst some attribute the oldest parts of the church as having been erected after the [[Norman Conquest]], possibly into the 12th century. It was originally a daughter church of All Saints, Sawley, but gained its independence in the 19th century.\n\n[[File:Long Eaton - Harrington Mill.jpg|thumb|top|right|Harrington Mill]]There are several fine examples of industrial architecture in Long Eaton. Most are connected with the town's development as a lace-making centre. By 1907, the town housed almost 1,400 lace machines and the industry employed over 4,000 people (a quarter of the population). One of the largest lace-making mills, Harrington Mill, was built in 1885. It took one and a quarter million bricks to build the 167-metre long factory and it has 224 cast-iron windows down one side.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bussey |first=Linda|title=Photographers Britain - Derbyshire|year=1993 |publisher=Alan Sutton Publishing Ltd |isbn=0-7509-0157-8}}</ref> Harrington Mill is a traditional, four-storey, red lace mill, built by a consortium of lace manufacturers. The turrets on the sides of the building house the original staircases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/SPIRIT-ENTERPRISE-LIVES/article-413184-detail/article.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914112148/http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/SPIRIT-ENTERPRISE-LIVES/article-413184-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2012 |title=Spirit Of Enterprise Lives On At Mill |publisher=This is Derbyshire |date=21 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAbove the shops on High Street and the Market Place show large parts of the centre made of Victorian and early twentieth century architecture. The New Central Building is a good example of late Victorian architecture.\n[[File:Co-Operative Building, Long Eaton, Derbyshire.jpg|thumb|right|New Central Building, Station Street, Long Eaton]] In general Long Eaton's main shopping streets have retained more character than those of most towns of its size.\n\nThe High Street and Market Place were pedestrianised during the 1990s and in 2010 work to enhance and improve the layout and paving of Long Eaton town centre was completed.\n\n==Transport==\nThe main road through the town forms part of the [http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A6005 A6005] and junction 25 of the [[M1 motorway]] is on its north-western border. The area round the traffic island in the Town Centre is called The Green by locals.\n\n[[Long Eaton railway station]] is on the [[Midland Main Line]]. The [[Erewash Canal]] passes through the town.\n\nThere are bus services to the nearby cities of [[Nottingham]] and [[Derby]] departing every few minutes. Other local services include the East Midlands Airport.\n\n==County issue==\nLong Eaton is located in Derbyshire, forming part of the border with [[Nottinghamshire]] and very close to [[Leicestershire]]. The town is covered by the Nottingham [[post town]] and has a Nottingham telephone area code (0115).<ref>https://www.google.com/#hl=en&sclient=psy-ab&q=long+eaton%2Cnotts&oq=long+eaton%2Cnotts&aq=f&aqi=g-v4&aql=&gs_l=hp.3..0i15l4.871l7480l0l8681l16l13l0l3l3l0l408l1915l0j12j4-1l16l0.frgbld.&pbx=1&bav=on.2,or.r_gc.r_pw.r_qf.,cf.osb&fp=1e4575b7dd61de50&biw=1280&bih=747</ref> It is acceptable to use the county of Derbyshire in postal addresses for Long Eaton if the postcode is used.\n\nThe [[Local Government Commission for England (1958 - 1967)|Local Government Commission for England (1958\u20131967)]] recommended that Long Eaton become part of an enlarged Nottingham City Council. Earlier, the original draft of the [[Local Government Act 1972]] had proposed moving Long Eaton into [[Nottinghamshire]]. The [[Redcliffe-Maud Report]] proposals of 1969 also recommended the county move, but the incoming Conservative administration rejected the proposal. This issue has rumbled on over many years.\n\n==Schools==\nLong Eaton has two state [[secondary schools]], [[The Long Eaton School]] and [[Wilsthorpe Community School]], and several [[primary schools]], including Brooklands, St Lawrence, Dovedale, Sawley, Harrington, English Martyrs, Longmoor and Grange. It also contains the [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] [[Trent College]], the private [[Elms School]] for ages 3\u201311, and a special needs school: Stanton Vale.\n\nLong Eaton School was split into two separate sites, a Lower for years 7, 8 and 9, and an Upper for years 10, 11 and sixth form. The Lower School building, opened in 1965, was demolished in 2006, when a new school was built next door on the same grounds. Both Upper and Lower are now in one building, which was opened by [[Gordon Brown]] as Chancellor of the Exchequer. It has gained specialist status in science, become an eco school with an eco club, and recently gained academy relations. There is now a research-grade telescope built on school grounds, where regular stargazing sessions are open to the public. It has partnership and student-exchange relations with Spanish, French, Italian and Chinese schools abroad. The school was rebuilt in 2006.\n\nIn 2005 Wilsthorpe School gained specialist status in business and enterprise. In 2018, the re-built the school. Both Wilsthorpe and Long Eaton schools have an OFSTED rating of \"good\".\n\n==Brass band==\nLong Eaton also has a Long Eaton Silver Prize [[brass band]], one of only two still functioning in Erewash. It was formed in 1906 after severing from a local temperance society. At its height it reached the Brass Band Second Section. The original club building in Sailsbury Street closed in early 2015, but the band itself plays on.\n\nIn 2006, its centenary year, the band won the Midland Area Regional Championships, its first contest win since 1966. This secured promotion back to the Second Section and an invitation to the National Championships of Great Britain. The band also won this contest, in what were its best contest results since 1927.\n\n==Sport==\n[[Long Eaton Speedway]] raced at the Long Eaton Stadium on Station Road. The first meeting was held on 18 May 1929.<ref>Nottingham & Long Eaton Speedway. Philip Dalling. {{ISBN|978-0-7524-4163-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bygonederbyshire.co.uk/stories/8203-Speedway-Derbyshire/article-1809721-detail/article.html |title=Speedway in Derbyshire |publisher=Bygonederbyshire.co.uk |date=5 September 2012 }}</ref> The Long Eaton Invaders became National Speedway Champions in 1984. However, the speedway stadium closed in 1997. Its area now holds a new estate of houses and flats to let and buy, and in part a playing field for Grange Primary School.\n\n[[Long Eaton United F.C.]] plays in the [[Midland Football League (2014)|Midland Football League]], as founder members in 2014. The club was formed in 1956 but records show football prominent in the town for many years before. The Football Club has many junior sides and gained [[FA Charter Standard Community Club]] status in 2013. It also has a ladies' team competing in the [[East Midlands Womens Football League]]\n\n[[Long Eaton Rangers F.C.]] was founded in 1889 but went bankrupt ten years later.{{citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\nThe town has a [[Rugby union|rugby]] club, [[Long Eaton RFC]].\n\n==Recreation==\nThe main park is [[West Park, Long Eaton|West Park]] which has a caf\u00e9 and neighbours West Park Leisure Centre. \nLong Eaton holds an annual \"Chestnut Fair\" in November.\n\nIn a tradition which started in 1931,<ref>http://www.long-eaton.com/carnival.asp</ref> the town hosts an annual Carnival each year \u2013 currently on the third Saturday in June. The event commences with a parade of floats, decorated vehicles and walkers in fancy dress, which circulates round the town. It continues in the afternoon and evening with a range of entertainment, stalls and a funfair on the Carnival showground on West Park.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Albert Ball]] VC, attended Trent College, Long Eaton, in 1911\u20131913.\n*[[Garry Birtles]], footballer, signed for Nottingham Forest from Long Eaton United and won two European Cups with the club.\n*[[Mark Draper]], footballer<ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=630 Mark Draper at Sporting Heroes]. Retrieved June 2007.</ref>\n*[[Georgia Groome]], actress<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2102872/ Georgia Groome [[Internet Movie Database]] entry]</ref>\n*[[Paula Christine Hammond]], MBE, JP\n*[[Ernest Terah Hooley]] (1859-1947), business financier, four-times bankrupt, died in reduced circumstances at Long Eaton.<ref name=times>{{Cite news |title=Death of Mr. E. T. Hooley |work=The Times |page=2 |date=13 February 1947}}</ref>\n*[[Geoff Hoon]] (born 1953), Labour Party politician (Defence Secretary 1999\u20132006, Leader of the House of Commons 2006\u20132007, Government Chief Whip 2008) attended Brooklands School.\n*[[Douglas Houghton, Baron Houghton of Sowerby]], Labour politician, last cabinet member to have been born in the 19th century and to serve in the [[First World War]]<ref name=\"obit5\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lord-houghton-of-sowerby-1345486.html Obituary], The Independent, accessed 1 August 2012.</ref>\n*[[Saira Khan]], TV presenter\n*[[Laura Knight]], [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire|DBE]], impressionist painter (born 1877)\n*[[Eric Malpass]], writer\n*[[Lewis McGugan]], footballer\n*[[Dougie Squires]], [[OBE]], choreographer\n*[[John Walters (broadcaster)|John Walters]], broadcaster\n*[[Dan Wheeldon]], cricketer\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places in Derbyshire]]\n*[[Christ Church Methodist Church]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:LongEatonChurch236.JPG|St. Lawrence church located in the town centre\nFile:Market_Place_(North_End),_Long_Eaton,_Derbyshire.jpg|Above the shops is the architecture\nFile:Market_Place_(St_Lawrence_Church),_Market_Place,_Long_Eaton,_Derbyshire.jpg|Market Place, looking north\nFile:LongEatonChimney.jpg|The old factory chimney of Bridge Mills, situated on Derby Road\nFile:Long Eaton School.jpg|The newly built Long Eaton School\nFile:LongEatonRecGroundCyclists.jpg|A cycle race in 1885 at Long Eaton Recreation Ground\nFile:LEArchers.jpg|Long Eaton Speedway\nFile:LongEatonLibrary35.JPG|Long Eaton's distinctive library\n</gallery>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.erewash.gov.uk/ Erewash Borough Council]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title = '''Destinations from Long Eaton'''\n|Northwest = \n|North   = [[Stapleford, Nottinghamshire|Stapleford]], [[Ilkeston]]\n|Northeast = \n|West   = [[Derby]]\n|Centre  = Long Eaton\n|East   = [[Nottingham]], [[Beeston, Nottinghamshire|Beeston]]\n|Southwest = \n|South   = [[Sawley, Derbyshire|Sawley]], [[East Midlands Airport]]\n|Southeast = \n}}\n\n{{Derbyshire}}\n{{Commons category|Long Eaton}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Railway towns in England]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of Erewash]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name = Long Eaton\n|country = England\n|region = East Midlands\n|population = 37,760\n|population_ref = (2011)\n |os_grid_reference = SK 49033 33679 \n|coordinates = {{coord|52.898|-1.271|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type = Elkinshire\n|post_town = NOTTINGHAM\n|postcode_area = NG\n|postcode_district = NG10\n|dial_code = 0115\n|constituency_westminster = [[Erewash (UK Parliament constituency)|Erewash]]\n|civil_parish = \n|shire_district = [[Borough of Erewash|Erewash]]\n|shire_county = [[Derbyshire]]\n|static_image_name = HSBC, Market Place, Long Eaton, Derbyshire.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Market Place, Long Eaton\n}}\n'''Long Eaton''' is a town in the [[Borough of Erewash|Erewash]] district of [[Derbyshire]], England, just north of the [[River Trent]] about {{convert|7|mi|km}} south-west of [[Nottingham]] and some {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} south-east of [[Derby]]. The population was 37,760 at the 2011 census.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/uk-england-eastmidlands.php?cityid=E35000992 |title=Town population 2011 |accessdate=27 March 2016}}</ref> Since 1 April 1974, Long Eaton has been part of [[Borough of Erewash|Erewash]] borough, after the dissolution of the [[Long Eaton Urban District]] Council.\n\n==History==\nLong Eaton is referred to as ''Aitone'', in the ''[[Domesday Book]]''. Several meanings are associated with the name, for example \"farm between streams\" or \"low-lying land\". This farming settlement grew up close to the lowest bridging point of the [[River Erewash]].\n\nThe \"Great Fire of Long Eaton\" ripped through 14 houses and several other buildings in the market place in 1694.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.long-eaton.com/timeline.asp |title=The Long Eaton & Sawley Archive |publisher=Long-eaton.com |date=}}</ref>\n\nThe village remained a constant size until the coming of the [[Midland Counties Railway]] in 1839 and the [[Erewash Valley Line]] in 1844, which brought links that encouraged growth. Two industries came to employ many people in the growing town: [[lace|lace-making]] and [[Goods wagon|railway wagon]] manufacturing. A large railway yard at [[Toton TMD|Toton Sidings]] grew up just north of the town.\n\nBy 1900 the town had grown to have a population of over 10,000. It had expanded with the construction of many new houses, business premises and factories throughout the Victorian period. In 1921 Long Eaton's boundaries were extended bringing Wilsthorpe and parts of both [[Sandiacre]] and Sawley into the town.\n\n==Twin towns==\n*{{flagicon|Centre}} [[Romorantin-Lanthenay]], {{flagicon|France}} France\n*{{flagicon|Hesse}} [[Langen, Hesse|Langen]], {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany <ref>{{Cite book|title=Langen im Herzen Europas|last=Bremer|first=J\u00fcrgen|publisher=J\u00fcrgen Bremer in collaboration with municipal authority of Langen and Langener Stadtinitiative for history and culture|year=2010|isbn=978-3-00-033328-6|location=Langen (Hessen)|pages=220\u2013221|language=German, English, French, Spanish, Turkish|trans-title=Langen in the heart of Europe|chapter=Long Eaton}}</ref>\n\n==Notable architecture==\n[[File:Long Eaton Hall, Long Eaton, Derbyshire.jpg|thumb|right|Long Eaton Hall (built c.1778)]]\nA notable building in the town is the [[Palladian architecture|Palladian]] Long Eaton Hall. This was originally a private residence, but is now occupied by the borough council, and is attached to the Long Eaton Town Hall complex, which opened in 1991.\n\nThe [[St. Laurence's Church, Long Eaton|Parish Church of St Laurence]] stands to the east of the Market Place. Local tradition dates parts of the church to the 11th century, possibly built under Viking King of [[Denmark]] [[King Cnut|Cnut]]. Whilst some attribute the oldest parts of the church as having been erected after the [[Norman Conquest]], possibly into the 12th century. It was originally a daughter church of All Saints, Sawley, but gained its independence in the 19th century.\n\n[[File:Long Eaton - Harrington Mill.jpg|thumb|top|right|Harrington Mill]]There are several fine examples of industrial architecture in Long Eaton. Most are connected with the town's development as a lace-making centre. By 1907, the town housed almost 1,400 lace machines and the industry employed over 4,000 people (a quarter of the population). One of the largest lace-making mills, Harrington Mill, was built in 1885. It took one and a quarter million bricks to build the 167-metre long factory and it has 224 cast-iron windows down one side.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bussey |first=Linda|title=Photographers Britain - Derbyshire|year=1993 |publisher=Alan Sutton Publishing Ltd |isbn=0-7509-0157-8}}</ref> Harrington Mill is a traditional, four-storey, red lace mill, built by a consortium of lace manufacturers. The turrets on the sides of the building house the original staircases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/SPIRIT-ENTERPRISE-LIVES/article-413184-detail/article.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120914112148/http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/news/SPIRIT-ENTERPRISE-LIVES/article-413184-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2012 |title=Spirit Of Enterprise Lives On At Mill |publisher=This is Derbyshire |date=21 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAbove the shops on High Street and the Market Place show large parts of the centre made of Victorian and early twentieth century architecture. The New Central Building is a good example of late Victorian architecture.\n[[File:Co-Operative Building, Long Eaton, Derbyshire.jpg|thumb|right|New Central Building, Station Street, Long Eaton]] In general Long Eaton's main shopping streets have retained more character than those of most towns of its size.\n\nThe High Street and Market Place were pedestrianised during the 1990s and in 2010 work to enhance and improve the layout and paving of Long Eaton town centre was completed.\n\n==Transport==\nThe main road through the town forms part of the [http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A6005 A6005] and junction 25 of the [[M1 motorway]] is on its north-western border. The area round the traffic island in the Town Centre is called The Green by locals.\n\n[[Long Eaton railway station]] is on the [[Midland Main Line]]. The [[Erewash Canal]] passes through the town.\n\nThere are bus services to the nearby cities of [[Nottingham]] and [[Derby]] departing every few minutes. Other local services include the East Midlands Airport.\n\n==County issue==\nLong Eaton is located in Derbyshire, forming part of the border with [[Nottinghamshire]] and very close to [[Leicestershire]]. The town is covered by the Nottingham [[post town]] and has a Nottingham telephone area code (0115).<ref>https://www.google.com/#hl=en&sclient=psy-ab&q=long+eaton%2Cnotts&oq=long+eaton%2Cnotts&aq=f&aqi=g-v4&aql=&gs_l=hp.3..0i15l4.871l7480l0l8681l16l13l0l3l3l0l408l1915l0j12j4-1l16l0.frgbld.&pbx=1&bav=on.2,or.r_gc.r_pw.r_qf.,cf.osb&fp=1e4575b7dd61de50&biw=1280&bih=747</ref> It is acceptable to use the county of Derbyshire in postal addresses for Long Eaton if the postcode is used.\n\nThe [[Local Government Commission for England (1958 - 1967)|Local Government Commission for England (1958\u20131967)]] recommended that Long Eaton become part of an enlarged Nottingham City Council. Earlier, the original draft of the [[Local Government Act 1972]] had proposed moving Long Eaton into [[Nottinghamshire]]. The [[Redcliffe-Maud Report]] proposals of 1969 also recommended the county move, but the incoming Conservative administration rejected the proposal. This issue has rumbled on over many years.\n\n==Schools==\nLong Eaton has two state [[secondary schools]], [[The Long Eaton School]] and [[Wilsthorpe Community School]], and several [[primary schools]], including Brooklands, St Lawrence, Dovedale, Sawley, Harrington, English Martyrs, Longmoor and Grange. It also contains the [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public school]] [[Trent College]], the private [[Elms School]] for ages 3\u201311, and a special needs school: Stanton Vale.\n\nLong Eaton School was split into two separate sites, a Lower for years 7, 8 and 9, and an Upper for years 10, 11 and sixth form. The Lower School building, opened in 1965, was demolished in 2006, when a new school was built next door on the same grounds. Both Upper and Lower are now in one building, which was opened by [[Gordon Brown]] as Chancellor of the Exchequer. It has gained specialist status in science, become an eco school with an eco club, and recently gained academy relations. There is now a research-grade telescope built on school grounds, where regular stargazing sessions are open to the public. It has partnership and student-exchange relations with Spanish, French, Italian and Chinese schools abroad. The school was rebuilt in 2006.\n\nIn 2005 Wilsthorpe School gained specialist status in business and enterprise. In 2018, the re-built the school. Both Wilsthorpe and Long Eaton schools have an OFSTED rating of \"good\".\n\n==Brass band==\nLong Eaton also has a Long Eaton Silver Prize [[brass band]], one of only two still functioning in Erewash. It was formed in 1906 after severing from a local temperance society. At its height it reached the Brass Band Second Section. The original club building in Sailsbury Street closed in early 2015, but the band itself plays on.\n\nIn 2006, its centenary year, the band won the Midland Area Regional Championships, its first contest win since 1966. This secured promotion back to the Second Section and an invitation to the National Championships of Great Britain. The band also won this contest, in what were its best contest results since 1927.\n\n==Sport==\n[[Long Eaton Speedway]] raced at the Long Eaton Stadium on Station Road. The first meeting was held on 18 May 1929.<ref>Nottingham & Long Eaton Speedway. Philip Dalling. {{ISBN|978-0-7524-4163-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bygonederbyshire.co.uk/stories/8203-Speedway-Derbyshire/article-1809721-detail/article.html |title=Speedway in Derbyshire |publisher=Bygonederbyshire.co.uk |date=5 September 2012 }}</ref> The Long Eaton Invaders became National Speedway Champions in 1984. However, the speedway stadium closed in 1997. Its area now holds a new estate of houses and flats to let and buy, and in part a playing field for Grange Primary School.\n\n[[Long Eaton United F.C.]] plays in the [[Midland Football League (2014)|Midland Football League]], as founder members in 2014. The club was formed in 1956 but records show football prominent in the town for many years before. The Football Club has many junior sides and gained [[FA Charter Standard Community Club]] status in 2013. It also has a ladies' team competing in the [[East Midlands Womens Football League]]\n\n[[Long Eaton Rangers F.C.]] was founded in 1889 but went bankrupt ten years later.{{citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n\nThe town has a [[Rugby union|rugby]] club, [[Long Eaton RFC]].\n\n==Recreation==\nThe main park is [[West Park, Long Eaton|West Park]] which has a caf\u00e9 and neighbours West Park Leisure Centre. \nLong Eaton holds an annual \"Chestnut Fair\" in November.\n\nIn a tradition which started in 1931,<ref>http://www.long-eaton.com/carnival.asp</ref> the town hosts an annual Carnival each year \u2013 currently on the third Saturday in June. The event commences with a parade of floats, decorated vehicles and walkers in fancy dress, which circulates round the town. It continues in the afternoon and evening with a range of entertainment, stalls and a funfair on the Carnival showground on West Park.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Albert Ball]] VC, attended Trent College, Long Eaton, in 1911\u20131913.\n*[[Garry Birtles]], footballer, signed for Nottingham Forest from Long Eaton United and won two European Cups with the club.\n*[[Mark Draper]], footballer<ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=630 Mark Draper at Sporting Heroes]. Retrieved June 2007.</ref>\n*[[Georgia Groome]], actress<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2102872/ Georgia Groome [[Internet Movie Database]] entry]</ref>\n*[[Paula Christine Hammond]], MBE, JP\n*[[Ernest Terah Hooley]] (1859-1947), business financier, four-times bankrupt, died in reduced circumstances at Long Eaton.<ref name=times>{{Cite news |title=Death of Mr. E. T. Hooley |work=The Times |page=2 |date=13 February 1947}}</ref>\n*[[Geoff Hoon]] (born 1953), Labour Party politician (Defence Secretary 1999\u20132006, Leader of the House of Commons 2006\u20132007, Government Chief Whip 2008) attended Brooklands School.\n*[[Douglas Houghton, Baron Houghton of Sowerby]], Labour politician, last cabinet member to have been born in the 19th century and to serve in the [[First World War]]<ref name=\"obit5\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lord-houghton-of-sowerby-1345486.html Obituary], The Independent, accessed 1 August 2012.</ref>\n*[[Saira Khan]], TV presenter\n*[[Laura Knight]], [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire|DBE]], impressionist painter (born 1877)\n*[[Eric Malpass]], writer\n*[[Lewis McGugan]], footballer\n*[[Dougie Squires]], [[OBE]], choreographer\n*[[John Walters (broadcaster)|John Walters]], broadcaster\n*[[Dan Wheeldon]], cricketer\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places in Derbyshire]]\n*[[Christ Church Methodist Church]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:LongEatonChurch236.JPG|St. Lawrence church located in the town centre\nFile:Market_Place_(North_End),_Long_Eaton,_Derbyshire.jpg|Above the shops is the architecture\nFile:Market_Place_(St_Lawrence_Church),_Market_Place,_Long_Eaton,_Derbyshire.jpg|Market Place, looking north\nFile:LongEatonChimney.jpg|The old factory chimney of Bridge Mills, situated on Derby Road\nFile:Long Eaton School.jpg|The newly built Long Eaton School\nFile:LongEatonRecGroundCyclists.jpg|A cycle race in 1885 at Long Eaton Recreation Ground\nFile:LEArchers.jpg|Long Eaton Speedway\nFile:LongEatonLibrary35.JPG|Long Eaton's distinctive library\n</gallery>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.erewash.gov.uk/ Erewash Borough Council]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|title = '''Destinations from Long Eaton'''\n|Northwest = \n|North   = [[Stapleford, Nottinghamshire|Stapleford]], [[Ilkeston]]\n|Northeast = \n|West   = [[Derby]]\n|Centre  = Long Eaton\n|East   = [[Nottingham]], [[Beeston, Nottinghamshire|Beeston]]\n|Southwest = \n|South   = [[Sawley, Derbyshire|Sawley]], [[East Midlands Airport]]\n|Southeast = \n}}\n\n{{Derbyshire}}\n{{Commons category|Long Eaton}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Railway towns in England]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Borough of Erewash]]\n", "name_user": "Bmcln1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Eaton"}
{"title_page": "Cary, North Carolina", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = \n\n|official_name            = Town of Cary\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = \n|postal_code_type         = ZIP Code\n|postal_code              = 27511-27513, 27518, 27519\n|image_skyline            = Cary, North Carolina. Cary, NC.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Town Hall in Cary\n|image_flag               = Flag of Cary, North Carolina.png\n|image_seal               = Seal of Cary, North Carolina.png\n|image_map                = Wake County North Carolina incorporated and unincorporated areas Cary highlighted.svg\n|map_caption              = Location in [[Wake County, North Carolina|Wake County]] and the state of [[North Carolina]].\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[North Carolina]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in North Carolina|Counties]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Chatham County, North Carolina|Chatham]], [[Wake County, North Carolina|Wake]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Cary, North Carolina#Mayors|Mayor]]\n|leader_party             = \n|leader_name              = [[Harold Weinbrecht]]\n|established_title        = Founded\n|established_date         = 1750\n|established_title2       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date2        = April 3, 1871\n|established_title3       = \n|established_date3        = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_footnotes          = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://townofcary.uberflip.com/i/780666-q4-quarterly-2-1-17|title=TOC - Q4 Quarterly_2.1.17|website=townofcary.uberflip.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|title=U.S. Census website|author=U.S. Census Bureau|website=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 153.90\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 59.42\n|area_land_km2            = 151.07\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 58.33\n|area_water_km2           = 2.82\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 1.09\n|area_water_percent       = 1.83\n|area_urban_km2           = \n|area_urban_sq_mi         = \n|area_metro_km2           = \n|area_metro_sq_mi         = \n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_note          = \n|population_total         = 135234\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_metro_km2     = \n|population_density_metro_sq_mi   = \n|population_urban                 = \n|population_demonym       = Caryite\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = [[North American Eastern Time Zone#About its name|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|coordinates              = {{coord|35|47|30|N|78|46|52|W|region:US-NC|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 495\n|area_codes                = [[Area code 919|919, 984]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 37-10740<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1019552<ref name=GNIS1>{{Cite GNIS|1019552|Cary}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|1=https://www.townofcary.org}}\n|named_for                = [[Samuel Fenton Cary]]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|population_est = 168160\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n}}\n\n'''Cary''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u00e6r|i}} is the seventh-largest municipality in [[North Carolina]]. Cary is predominantly in [[Wake County, North Carolina|Wake County]], with a small area in [[Chatham County, North Carolina|Chatham County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[North Carolina]] and is the county's second-largest municipality, as well as the third-largest municipality in [[Research Triangle|The Triangle]] of North Carolina after [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] and [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]].\n\nThe town's population was 135,234 as of the [[2010 United States census|2010 census]] (an increase of 43.1% since 2000), making it the largest town and seventh-largest municipality statewide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/cities/files/SUB-EST2009_37.csv |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626124849/http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/files/SUB-EST2009_37.csv |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-06-26 |title=Subcounty population estimates: North Carolina 2000\u20132009 |format=[[comma-separated values|CSV]] |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]], Population Division |date=2010-06-22 |accessdate=2010-09-30 }}</ref> {{as of|2018|July}}, the town's estimated population was 168,160, though Cary is still classified a town because that is how it was incorporated with the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article207684979.html|title=Should Cary call itself a city or a town? Does it even matter?|last=Bolejack|first=Scott|work=[[News & Observer]]|date=2018-04-02|accessdate=2018-04-03}}</ref> Cary is the second most populous [[incorporated town]] (behind only [[Gilbert, Arizona]]) in the United States.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|US Census Bureau]], Cary was the fifth fastest-growing municipality in the United States between September 1, 2006, and September 1, 2007.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080713081930/http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/012242.html New Orleans Population Continues Katrina Recovery; Houston Leads in Numerical Growth], U.S. Census Bureau News, 2008-07-10</ref> In 2015 Cary had a crime rate of 84 violent crimes per 100,000 residents.<ref name=USSmartAssetRank>{{cite web | last = Wallace | first = Nick | title = The Safest Cities in America | url = https://smartasset.com/mortgage/safest-cities-in-america | work = [[SmartAsset]] | date = November 16, 2015 | accessdate = November 18, 2015}}</ref> Charlotte, the largest city in North Carolina, had a violent crime rate of 648 violent crimes per 100,000 residents, almost eight times higher than Cary.\n\nRaleigh, Durham, and [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]] make up the three primary metropolitan areas of the [[The Triangle (North Carolina)|Research Triangle]] metropolitan region. The regional nickname of \"The Triangle\" originated after the 1959 creation of the [[Research Triangle Park]], primarily located in Durham County, four miles from downtown Durham. RTP is bordered on three sides by the city of Durham and is roughly midway between the cities of Raleigh and Chapel Hill, and the three major research universities of [[NC State University]], [[Duke University]], and [[UNC-Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill]].\n\nEffective June 6, 2003, the U.S. [[Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB) redefined the Federal statistical areas. This resulted in the formation of the Raleigh-Cary, NC Metro Area and the Durham-Chapel Hill, NC Metro Area.\n\nThe Research Triangle region encompasses OMB's [[Combined Statistical Area|Combined Statistical Area (CSA)]] of Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill in the central [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]] region of North Carolina. {{as of|2012}}, the population of the Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill CSA was 1,998,808.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/metro/totals/2012/index.html |title=Population Estimates 2012 Combined Statistical Areas: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2012 |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=2013-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317045641/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/metro/totals/2012/index.html |archive-date=March 17, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Raleigh-Cary [[List of metropolitan statistical areas|Metropolitan Statistical Area (MSA)]] as of Census 2010 was 1,130,490.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Cary, North Carolina}}\n[[File:Page-WalkerHotel.jpg|thumb|right|[[Page-Walker Hotel]] (now local history museum)]]\n[[File:Prestontower.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Preston Clocktower in West Cary]]\n\nIn 1750, Cary began as a settlement called Bradford's Ordinary. About 100 years later, the [[North Carolina Railroad]] between [[New Bern, North Carolina|New Bern]] and [[Hillsborough, North Carolina|Hillsborough]] was constructed through the town, linking Bradford's Ordinary to a major transportation route.\n\nAllison Francis \"Frank\" Page is credited with founding the town. Page was a Wake County farmer and lumberman. He and his wife, Catherine \"Kate\" Raboteau Page bought {{convert|300|acre|km2|1}} surrounding the railroad junction in 1854 and named his development Cary, after [[Samuel Fenton Cary]]<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n69 70]}}</ref> (a former Ohio congressman and prohibitionist he admired). Page became a railroad agent and a town developer. He laid out the first streets in Cary and built a sawmill, a general store and a post office (Page became the first Postmaster). In 1868, Page built a hotel to serve railroad passengers coming through Cary. Cary was incorporated on April 3, 1871, with Page becoming the first mayor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.townofcary.org/New_to_Cary_/About_Cary_272/Looking_Back.htm |title=Looking Back |accessdate=2010-05-23 |publisher=Cary, North Carolina |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608192855/http://www.townofcary.org/New_to_Cary_/About_Cary_272/Looking_Back.htm |archivedate=2010-06-08 }}</ref> In 1879, the Raleigh and Augusta Air-Line Railroad (later the Seaboard, now [[CSX Transportation]]) arrived in Cary from the southwest, creating Fetner Junction just north of downtown and spurring further growth.\n\nIn the early years, Cary adopted zoning and other ordinances on an ad-hoc basis to control growth and give the town structure. Beginning in 1971, the town created [[Planned Unit Development]] (PUD) zoning to accommodate population growth related to the growth of [[Research Triangle Park]] nearby. A PUD allows a developer to plan an entire community before beginning development, thus allowing future residents to be aware of where churches, schools, commercial and industrial areas will be located well before such use begins. Kildaire Farms, a {{convert|967|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} Planned Unit Development in Cary, was North Carolina's first PUD. It was developed on the Pine State Dairy Farm by Thomas F. Adams, Jr. Adams named a section of Kildaire Farms \"Farmington Woods\" in their honor.\n\nIn addition to the Page-Walker Hotel, the [[Carpenter Historic District (Raleigh, North Carolina)|Carpenter Historic District]], [[Cary Historic District]], [[Green Level, Wake County, North Carolina|Green Level Historic District]], [[Ivey-Ellington House]], and [[Nancy Jones House]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nLocated in the [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]] region of the eastern United States, Cary is near North Carolina's [[Research Triangle Park|Research Triangle]]. It is bordered on the north and east by Raleigh, on the north and west by Research Triangle Park and [[Morrisville, North Carolina|Morrisville]], on the south by [[Apex, North Carolina|Apex]] and [[Holly Springs, North Carolina|Holly Springs]], and on the west by the [[Jordan Lake]] area.  The town is hilly, with much of the undeveloped land covered in dense woods. Several creeks and small lakes dot the area, most notably Lake Crabtree in the north.\n\nNearly all of Cary is in western Wake County, with neighborhood-sized sections in the northeast corner of [[Chatham County, North Carolina|Chatham County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townofcary.org/home/showdocument?id=1799|title=Town Limits Layout|last=|first=|date=March 14, 2019|website=Town of Cary|location=[[Cary, North Carolina]]|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of 43.5&nbsp;square miles (112.6&nbsp;km\u00b2), of which 42.1&nbsp;square miles (109.0&nbsp;km\u00b2) is land and 1.4&nbsp;square miles (3.6&nbsp;km\u00b2) (3.17%) is water. {{as of|2010}}, Cary claims a total area of 55.34&nbsp;mi\u00b2.<ref name='Our Community'>{{cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Publications/Citizen_s_Guide_to_Services/ourcommunity.htm |title=Town of Cary - Our Community |accessdate=2014-05-22 |publisher=Cary, North Carolina |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620154605/http://www.townofcary.org/Publications/Citizen_s_Guide_to_Services/ourcommunity.htm |archivedate=2014-06-20 }}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nCary has a [[humid subtropical climate]] (''Cfa'') under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system. It receives hot summers and mildly cold winters, with several months of pleasant weather each year. Temperature extremes here range from the negatives to over 100 degrees Fahrenheit.  Hurricanes and tropical storms can affect Cary, usually after weakening substantially from being over land. Some, such as [[Hurricane Fran]] in 1996, have caused great damage in the area. Snow falls every year, averaging approximately six inches annually.\n{{Weather box\n|location = Cary, North Carolina\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 80\n|Feb record high F = 84\n|Mar record high F = 94\n|Apr record high F = 95\n|May record high F = 99\n|Jun record high F = 104\n|Jul record high F = 105\n|Aug record high F = 105\n|Sep record high F = 104\n|Oct record high F = 98\n|Nov record high F = 88\n|Dec record high F = 81\n|year record high F= 105\n|Jan high F = 50\n|Feb high F = 54\n|Mar high F = 62\n|Apr high F = 72\n|May high F = 79\n|Jun high F = 86\n|Jul high F = 89\n|Aug high F = 87\n|Sep high F = 81\n|Oct high F = 72\n|Nov high F = 62\n|Dec high F = 53\n|year high F=\n|Jan low F = 30\n|Feb low F = 32\n|Mar low F = 39\n|Apr low F = 46\n|May low F = 55\n|Jun low F = 64\n|Jul low F = 69\n|Aug low F = 67\n|Sep low F = 61\n|Oct low F = 48\n|Nov low F = 40\n|Dec low F = 33\n|year low F=\n|Jan record low F = \u22129\n|Feb record low F = \u22122\n|Mar record low F = 11\n|Apr record low F = 23\n|May record low F = 29\n|Jun record low F = 38\n|Jul record low F = 48\n|Aug record low F = 46\n|Sep record low F = 37\n|Oct record low F = 19\n|Nov record low F = 11\n|Dec record low F = 0\n|year record low F= \u22129\n|Jan precipitation inch = 4.02\n|Feb precipitation inch = 3.47\n|Mar precipitation inch = 4.03\n|Apr precipitation inch = 2.8\n|May precipitation inch = 3.79\n|Jun precipitation inch = 3.42\n|Jul precipitation inch = 4.29\n|Aug precipitation inch = 3.78\n|Sep precipitation inch = 4.26\n|Oct precipitation inch = 3.18\n|Nov precipitation inch = 2.97\n|Dec precipitation inch = 3.04\n|year precipitation inch= 43.05\n|source 1 = http://www.weather.com/outlook/health/fitness/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USNC0107<ref>{{cite web | author=Weather Channel | title=Cary, NC Weather| url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/health/fitness/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USNC0107| publisher=Weather Channel | date= | accessdate=2010-04-05}}</ref>\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n===Townscape===\nCary is divided into distinct east and west sections. The eastern side contains the downtown area as well as the town's neighborhoods. Several of the town's iconic buildings, such as the Ashworth Drug Store, Fidelity Building, and Page-Walker Hotel are in the eastern part of town. The western side holds mostly residences and shopping. Almost completely suburbanized, the area features sprawling neighborhoods, parks, and lakes.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 316\n|1890= 423\n|1900= 333\n|1910= 383\n|1920= 645\n|1930= 909\n|1940= 1141\n|1950= 1446\n|1960= 3356\n|1970= 7686\n|1980= 21763\n|1990= 43858\n|2000= 94536\n|2010= 135234\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=168160\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]], there were 135,234 people and 55,303 households in the town. {{as of|2013}}, the population has increased to 151,088.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |accessdate=May 22, 2014 }}</ref> The population was 73.1% [[White American|White]], 13.1% [[Asian American|Asian]], 8.0% [[African American]], 7.7% [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] of any race, 2.6% identified as having ancestry of [[Multiracial Americans|two or more races]], 0.4% [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], and 0.0% [[Pacific Islander American|Pacific Islander]].\n\nThe median household income for Cary {{as of|2011|lc=y}} was $110,609.\n\n===Educational attainment===\nMore than two-thirds (68.0%) of Cary residents (aged 25 and older) hold an associate degree or higher, and 60.7% of adults possess a bachelor's degree or higher. Cary has one of the lowest crime rates (79% less than [[North Carolina]]) in the state for municipalities of its size.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 safest places to live in the US|url=http://www.clevelandsecuritybloggers.com/10-safest-places-to-live-in-the-us/|publisher=www.clevelandsecuritybloggers.com|accessdate=27 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628182630/http://www.clevelandsecuritybloggers.com/10-safest-places-to-live-in-the-us/|archivedate=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name='national geographic'>{{cite news | first=Joel | last=Bourne | title=Suburbia Unbound | date= | publisher= | url =http://www.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0106/feature7/index.html | work =National Geographic | pages = | accessdate = 2007-04-16 | language = }}</ref> The home ownership rate (owner-occupied housing units to total units) is 72.8%.\n\nIn 2013, Cary moved up in the latest rankings of safe U.S. cities and is now considered the third-safest among municipalities with populations of 100,000 to 499,999, behind [[Amherst, New York]], and [[Irvine, California]], according to CQ Press, publisher of the annual \"City Crime Rankings 2008-2009: Crime in Metropolitan America.\"\n\nData from the 2000 Census shows 29.2% of Cary residents are native to North Carolina; 55.2% were born in other states. Additionally, 15.6% of the town's population were born outside the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carychamber.com/money2.html |title=Money Magazine Article - Part 2 |accessdate=2010-05-23 |publisher=Cary Chamber of Commerce |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606150159/http://www.carychamber.com/money2.html |archivedate=June 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n===Notable businesses===\n*[[3Dsolve]] \u2013 Simulation software used in training by the military, recently purchased by [[Lockheed Martin]]\n*[[A10 Networks]] \u2013 U.S. public company specializing in the manufacturing of application delivery controllers\n*[[Arista Networks]] \u2013 Computer networking manufacturer\n*[[Cotton Incorporated]] \u2013 Industry trade-group\n*[[Epic Games]] \u2013 Video game developer\n*[[IntelliScanner Corporation]] \u2013 Home and small business organization products\n*[[Lord Corporation]] \u2013 Diversified technology company\n*[[SAS Institute]] \u2013 Large software company and Cary's largest employer\n*[[Western Wake Medical Center]] \u2013 Private hospital\n*[[ABB Group]] - Electrification, Robotics and Industrial Automation conglomerate\n\n===Top employers===\nAccording to the Cary's ''2018 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,''<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report |url=https://www.townofcary.org/home/showdocument?id=21674 |website=townofcary.org |publisher=Town of Cary |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> the top employers in the town are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of Employees\n|-\n| 1\n|[[SAS Institute]]\n|5,616\n|-\n| 2\n|[[MetLife]]\n|2,600\n|-\n| 3\n|[[Verizon Communications|Verizon]]\n|2,000\n|-\n| 4\n|Powersteam Services\n|1,993\n|-\n| 5\n|[[Siemens Medical Solutions|Siemens Medical Solutions  USA]]\n|1,600\n|-\n| 6\n|[[HCL Technologies|HCL America]]\n|1,500\n|-\n| 7\n|[[ABB Group|ABB, Inc.]]\n|1,300\n|-\n| 7\n|Town of Cary\n|1,222\n|-\n| 5\n|[[American Airlines]] Reservation Center\n|1,200\n|-\n| 10\n|[[Deutsche Bank|DB Global Technologies]]\n|1,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==Arts and culture==\n* Lazy Daze Arts & Crafts Festival<ref>{{cite web |title=All About Lazy Daze |url=http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/08/17/all-about-lazy-daze/ |publisher=Cary Citizen |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823230445/http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/08/17/all-about-lazy-daze/ |archivedate=2010-08-23 }}</ref>\n* Spring Daze Arts & Crafts Festival\n* Greater Triangle Area Dragon Boat Festival\n* Cary Diwali Celebration - Festival of Light\n* Ritmo Latino Music, Art and Dance Festival\n* NC Eid Festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nceidfestival.org/|title=NC Eid Festival|access-date=2010-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812070005/http://www.nceidfestival.org/|archive-date=2010-08-12|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Cary Band Day\n\n==Sports==\nCary is home to two professional sports teams. [[North Carolina FC]] of the [[USL Championship]] league, and [[North Carolina Courage]] of the [[National Women's Soccer League]] (NWSL). The USL Championship league is the second tier of the [[American Soccer Pyramid]]. Both teams play their home games at [[WakeMed Soccer Park]], known as '''Sahlen's Stadium at WakeMed Soccer Park'''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! Club\n! Sport\n! Founded\n! League\n! Venue\n|-\n| [[North Carolina FC]]\n| [[Association football|Soccer]]\n| align center|2006\n| [[USL Championship]]\n| [[WakeMed Soccer Park]]\n|-\n| [[North Carolina Courage]]\n| [[Association football|Soccer]]\n| align center|2009\n| [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]]\n| [[WakeMed Soccer Park]]\n|}\n\nCary has also been the host site for various different [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] sports national championships.<ref>(Apr 23, 2019). [https://www.townofcary.org/Home/Components/News/News/14777/715 Cary to Host NCAA Division II Baseball Championship for 10th time]. ''Town of Cary''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.ncaa.com/championships/soccer-men/d1/future-info College Cup: Men's DI soccer championship]. ''ncaa.com''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Parks and recreation==\n*[[Koka Booth Amphitheatre at Regency Park]]\n*[[WakeMed Soccer Park]], home of North Carolina FC of USL Championship, and North Carolina Courage of the NWSL.\n*[[William B. Umstead State Park]]\n*[[USA Baseball National Training Complex]]\n* Thomas Brooks Park\n* Sk8 Cary Skate Park<ref>[http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/Parks__Recreation___Cultural_Resources/Facilities/Sports_Facilities/Sk8-Cary_Skate_Park.htm Cary Parks: Sk8 Cary Skate Park], Cary, North Caroline. Retrieved 2012-04-16.</ref>\n* [[Bond Park|Fred G. Bond Metropolitan Park]]\n* [[Hemlock Bluffs Nature Preserve]]\n* MacDonald Woods Park<ref>[http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/11/03/cary-parks-macdonald-woods/ Cary Parks: MacDonald Woods], CaryCitizen, November 3, 2010.</ref>\n* Walnut Street Park\n* Jack Smith Park\n* North Cary Park<ref>[https://www.townofcary.org/department/parks_recreation]</ref>\n\n===Tennis===\n*Cary Tennis Park\n*Recreation Club of Lochmere\n\n==Government==\nCary has a [[council-manager government]]; the mayor and council members serve a four-year term, with half of the council seats being up for election each odd-numbered year. Four of the six council seats are elected by [[single-member district]]s; the remaining two seats are elected as [[at-large]]representatives, meaning they must attract a majority of votes across the whole town.\n\nThe current ({{as of|2016|December|lc=y}}) town council consists of Mayor Harold Weinbrecht and Representatives Jennifer Robinson (District A), Don Frantz (District B), Jack W. Smith (District C), Ken George (District D), Lori Bush (at-large), and Ed Yerha (at-large).\n\nOn October 9, 2007, Harold Weinbrecht defeated incumbent Mayor Ernie McAlister in the 2007 mayoral election. Citizen concerns that rapid growth was adversely affecting infrastructure and environment over the effect rapid growth was having on the town, especially on roads, schools, and the environment, led to McAlister's ouster.<ref>{{cite news | first = Kelcey | last = Carlson | title = Town of CaryWeinbrecht Wins Upset in Cary Mayoral Race | date = 2007-10-09 | publisher = [[Capitol Broadcasting Company]] | url = http://www.wral.com/news/local/politics/story/1908306/ | work = WRAL News | accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>\n\nOn December 26, 2009, ''[[The Nation]]'' reported that Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) had secret prisons in the United States, where it held suspected illegal immigrants indefinitely before deportation. It reported that at least one of these secret federal prisons is allegedly located in an office building in Cary.<ref>{{cite news | first = Jacqueline | last = Stevens | title = America's Secret ICE Castles | date = 2009-12-16 | publisher = [[Katrina vanden Heuvel]] | url = http://www.thenation.com/article/americas-secret-ice-castles | work = The Nation | accessdate = 2010-07-20}}</ref> Part of the federal government's Department of Homeland Security, ICE has leased an office in Cary for more than 10 years. The town says that no detainees are kept at this location overnight. Other than protesters of punitive ICE policies picketing the facility, the town does not acknowledge any issues associated with the Cary ICE office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/Administration/pio/factsheet-caryice.htm |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628232324/http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/Administration/pio/factsheet-caryice.htm |archivedate=June 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Mayors===<!-- This section is linked from [[Cary, North Carolina]] -->\n;From 1871 to present\n<small>Read in columns.</small>\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n|-\n| A. F. Page<ref>[http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/04/22/cary-history-frank-page/ Cary History: Frank Page], ''CaryCitizen,'' 22 April 2010.</ref>\n| 1871\n| G. S. Leacock\n| 1914\n| Dr. J. P. Hunter\n| 1933\u20131935\n| Joseph R. Veasey\n| 1969\u20131971\n|-\n| J. H. Adams\n| 1884\n| T. H. Taylor\n| 1916\n| M. T. Jones\n| 1935\n| Fred G. Bond\n| 1971\u20131983\n|-\n| R. J. Harrison\n| 1887\n| W. G. Crowder\n| 1916\n| T. W. Addicks\n| 1935\n| Harold D. Ritter\n| 1983\u20131987\n|-\n| John Nugeer\n| 1897\n| E. P. Bradshaw\n| 1921\n| L. L. Raines\n| 1937\u20131947\n| Koka E. Booth<ref>[http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/06/30/profile-former-cary-mayor-koka-booth/ Profile: Former Cary Mayor Koka Booth], CaryCitizen, June 30, 2010.</ref>\n| 1987\u20131999\n|-\n| E. C. Hayes\n| 1900\n| W. H. Atkins\n| 1921\u20131925\n| R. W. Mayton\n| 1935\u20131937\n| [[Glen Lang]]\n| 1999\u20132003\n|-\n| A.R. McGarrity\n| 1902\n| G. H. Jordan\n| 1925\n| Robert G. Setzer\n| 1947\u20131949\n| Ernie McAlister\n| 2003\u20132007\n|-\n| R. J. Harrison\n| 1903\n| E. P. Bradshaw\n| 1925\n| H. Waldo Rood\n| 1949\u20131961\n| [[Harold Weinbrecht]]\n| 2007\u2013present\n|-\n| H. B. Jordan\n| 1903\n| Dr. F. R. Yarborough\n| 1927\u20131928\n| Dr. W. H. Justice\n| 1961\u20131962\n|\n|\n|-\n| N. C. Hines\n| 1910\n| A. N. Jackson\n| 1928\u20131929\n| James Hogarth\n| 1962\u20131963\n|\n|\n|-\n| J. M. Templeton, Jr.\n| 1912\n| H. H. Waddell\n| 1929\u20131933\n| Dr. E. B. Davis\n| 1963\u20131969\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Education==\n===Public schools===\n[[File:Green Hope High School (Front Entrance) 2006.jpg|thumb|200px|Green Hope High School]]\nBased in Cary, the Wake County Public School System is the largest public school system in North Carolina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http/%3A%2F%2Fwww.wcpss.net%2Fsite%2Fdefault.aspx%3FDomainID%3D2334|title=Contact Us / Overview|website=Wake County Public Schools|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*High Schools\n**[[Cary High School]]\n**Crossroads FLEX High School\n**[[Green Hope High School]]\n**Green Level High School\n**[[Middle Creek High School]]\n**[[Panther Creek High School (North Carolina)|Panther Creek High School]]\n*Middle Schools\n**Davis Drive Middle School\n**East Cary Middle School\n**Mills Park Middle School\n**Reedy Creek Middle School\n**West Cary Middle School\n**Alston Ridge Middle School\n*Elementary Schools\n**Adams Elementary School\n**Alston Ridge Elementary School\n**Briarcliff Elementary School\n**Carpenter Elementary School\n**Cary Elementary School\n**Davis Drive Elementary School\n**Farmington Woods Elementary School\n**Green Hope Elementary School\n**Highcroft Drive Elementary School\n**Hortons Creek Elementary\n**Kingswood Elementary School\n**Mills Park Elementary School\n**Northwoods Elementary School\n**Oak Grove Elementary School\n**Penny Road Elementary School\n**Reedy Creek Elementary School\n**Turner Creek Elementary School\n**Weatherstone Elementary School\n\n===Private schools===\n*[[Cary Academy]], middle/high school\n*[[Cary Christian School]], K-12 grade\n*Chesterbrook Academy\n*[[Grace Christian School (North Carolina)|Grace Christian School]], K-12 grade\n*[[Hopewell Academy]]\n*[[Saint Michael the Archangel Catholic School]]\n*Resurrection Lutheran School, K\u20138th grade\n*Landmark Christian Academy, K3\u201310th grade\n*Cardinal Charter Academy, K-8th grade\n\n===Higher education===\n*[[Wake Technical Community College]]\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transportation===\n====Public transit====\nPublic transit within the town is provided by [[GoCary]], with six fixed-routes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/fdts/trafficandtransportation/GoCary/fixedroute.htm|title=Fixed Route Service|website=www.townofcary.org|access-date=2016-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012222926/http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/fdts/trafficandtransportation/GoCary/fixedroute.htm|archive-date=2016-10-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> There is a door-to-door service for the senior citizens (60+) and riders with disabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/fdts/trafficandtransportation/GoCary/doortodoor.htm|title=GoCary Door to Door Service|website=www.townofcary.org|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref> [[GoTriangle]] operates fixed-route buses that serve the metropolitan region and connect to the local municipal transit systems in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]] and [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gotriangle.org/maps-and-schedules|title=Maps & Schedules {{!}} GoTriangle|website=gotriangle.org|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref>\n\n====Intercity rail====\n[[Amtrak]]'s [[Silver Star (Amtrak train)|Silver Star]], [[Carolinian and Piedmont]] passenger trains stop at the [[Cary (Amtrak station)|Cary Amtrak station]]. They offer service to [[Charlotte]], [[New York City]], [[Miami]], and intermediate points.\n\n====Bicycle====\nIn 2010 the [[League of American Bicyclists]] designated Cary as one of the fourteen recipients of the first ''Bicycle-Friendly Community'' awards for \"providing safe accommodation and facilities for bicyclists and encouraging residents to bike for transportation and recreation\".<ref name=\"greenways\">{{cite web | url = http://townofcary.org/Departments/Parks__Recreation___Cultural_Resources/Parks_and_Greenways/Greenways.htm | title = Greenways | accessdate = 2010-05-23 | publisher = Cary, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nThe Maine-to-Florida [[U.S. Bicycle Route 1]] passes through suburban Cary, as does [[North Carolina Bicycle Route 2|N.C. Bicycle Route #2]], the \"Mountains to Sea\" route.\n\n====Pedestrian====\nCary Greenways and Trails maintains a network of sidewalks and paved trails connecting neighborhoods and parks throughout the town.<ref name=\"greenways\" /> These greenways place strict requirements on environmental conditions to preserve a park-like atmosphere. In addition, standard sidewalks and paths exist throughout the town.\n\n====Air====\nThe [[Raleigh-Durham International Airport]], north of Cary via [[Interstate 40]] between Cary, [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] and [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], serves Cary and the greater Research Triangle metropolitan region. Raleigh-Durham offers more than 35 destinations, serving approximately 9 million passengers per year.\n\n====Freeways and primary routes====\n{{Main|North Carolina Highway System}}\n[[File:Chathamstreetcary.png|thumb|right|Downtown Cary, on Chatham Street]]\n*[[Interstate 40]]\n*[[U.S. Route 1 in North Carolina|U.S. 1]]\n*[[U.S. Route 64|U.S. 64]]\n*[[NC 54|State Highway 54]]\n*[[NC 55|State Highway 55]]\n*[[NC 147|State Highway 147]]\n*[[NC 540|State Highway 540]]\n*[[NC 751|State Highway 751]]\n*[[Cary Parkway]]\n*Kildaire Farm Road\n*Walnut Street (which appears on some maps as Cary-Macedonia Road)\n*High House Road\n*Harrison Avenue\n*Maynard Road Loop\n*Davis Drive (links to [[Research Triangle Park]])\n*Holly Springs Road\n\n==Notable people==\n{{maincat|People from Cary, North Carolina}}\n* [[Jesse Boulerice]], former [[National Hockey League|NHL]] player\n* [[Marshall Brain]], founder of the [[HowStuffWorks]] website\n* [[Carter Cruise]], pornographic actress\n*[[Casey Cole]], American [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] friar, Catholic priest, writer, and blogger<ref>Howard, Mandy. (Jun 26, 2019). [https://dioceseofraleigh.org/news/sharing-habit-newly-ordained-priest-celebrates-mass-sacraments-and-social-media Sharing the habit: Newly ordained priest celebrates Mass, sacraments, and ... social media]. ''Catholic Diocese of Raleigh''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Cotto]], Olympic track and field athlete representing [[Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Anoop Desai]], singer-songwriter best known for his time as a contestant on the eighth season of ''[[American Idol]]''<ref>Menconi, David. (Apr 1, 2016). [https://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/on-the-beat-blog/article68264742.html Catching up with North Carolina's 'Idols']. ''The News & Observer''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Spright Dowell]], former President of Alabama Polytechnic Institute, now known as [[Auburn University]]\n* [[Tim Downs]], American author<ref>[https://www.simonandschuster.com/authors/Tim-Downs/38977864 Tim Downs | Official Publisher Page]. ''Simon & Schuster''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Chris Flemmings]], professional [[basketball]] player<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/chris-flemmings-1.html Chris Flemmings College Stats]. ''Sports-Reference.com''.</ref>\n* [[Kendall Fletcher]], professional [[association football|women's soccer]] player<ref>[https://goheels.com/sports/womens-soccer/roster/kendall-fletcher/6228 Kendall Fletcher - Women's Soccer - UNC]. ''goheels.com''.</ref>\n* [[James Goodnight]], co-founder and CEO of [[SAS Institute]]\n* [[Ron Hendren]], former co-host of [[Entertainment Tonight]]\n* [[Justin Jedlica]], model and businessman\n* [[Alfred Daniel Jones]], US Consul General in Shanghai (1893), lived in Cary\n* [[Isaiah Johnson (American football, born October 1992)|Isaiah Johnson]], [[NFL]] defensive back<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnIs00.htm Isaiah Johnson Stats]. ''Pro-Football-Reference''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[U. Alexis Johnson]], United States [[diplomat]]\n* [[Scott Kooistra]], NFL [[tackle (gridiron football position)|offensive tackle]]<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KooiSc20.htm Scott Kooistra Stats]. ''Pro-Football-Reference''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Nathan Macias]], former member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]]; lived in Cary while in the [[United States Air Force]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lrl.state.tx.us/scanned/members/bios/TLO/80th_Macias_Nathan.pdf|title=House Membership: Representative Nathan Mathias|publisher=Texas Legislative Reference Library|accessdate=February 22, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Luke Maye]], professional [[basketball]] player<ref>[https://goheels.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/luke-maye/14653 Luke Maye - Men's Basketball - UNC]. ''goheels.com''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Walter Hines Page]], former United States ambassador to the United Kingdom\n* [[Max Povse]], professional [[baseball]] pitcher<ref>[http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=605428#/career/R/pitching/2019/ALL Max Povse Stats, Highlights, Bio]. ''milb.com''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Bevin Prince]], actress from ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]''\n* [[Morgan Reid]], professional [[association football|women's soccer]] player<ref>[https://www.orlandocitysc.com/players/198/morgan-reid Morgan Reid| Orlando City Soccer Club]. ''orlandocitysc.com''.</ref>\n* [[John Sall]], co-founder of [[SAS Institute]]\n* [[Ryan Spaulding]], professional [[association football|soccer]] player<ref>[https://www.northcarolinafc.com/ryanspaulding #20 Ryan Spaulding]. ''northcarolinafc.com''.</ref>\n* [[Azur\u00e1 Stevens]], [[WNBA]] player<ref>[https://www.usab.com/basketball/players/womens/s/stevens-azura.aspx Azur\u00e0 Stevens]. ''USA Basketball''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Tim Sweeney (game developer)|Tim Sweeney]], founder and CEO of [[Epic Games]]\n* [[Rysa Walker]], award-winning author of the ''Chronos Files'' series\n* [[Aaron Ward (ice hockey)|Aaron Ward]], former [[National Hockey League|NHL]] player\n* [[Jennifer Weiss]], former [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[North Carolina General Assembly]]<ref>Geary, Bob. (Feb 7, 2012). [https://indyweek.com/news/archives/rep.-jennifer-weiss-run-again-bad-news/ Rep. Jennifer Weiss won't run again: Bad news]. ''Indy Week''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Glen Wesley]], former [[National Hockey League|NHL]] player\n* [[Evan Rachel Wood]], actress in ''[[Thirteen (2003 film)|Thirteen]]'', ''[[True Blood]]'', ''[[The Conspirator]]''\n* [[Kay Yow]], former head coach of the women's basketball team at [[North Carolina State University]]\n\n==Accolades==\n* ''[[Money Magazine]]'' Best Place to Live ranked Cary as #5 in the nation in 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2006/snapshots/PL3710740.html | title = Best Places to Live 2006| accessdate = 2010-05-23 |date =2006| publisher = [[CNN]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061221000332/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2006/snapshots/PL3710740.html| archivedate= December 21, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Sister cities==\n{{SisterCities|Cary|four}}<ref name=sister>{{cite web|title=Interactive City Directory|url=http://sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Cary,%20North%20Carolina|publisher=[[Sister Cities International]]|accessdate=5 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106002801/http://sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Cary,%20North%20Carolina|archive-date=2014-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sistercitiesofcary.org/ |title=Sister Cities of Cary |publisher=Town of Cary|access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n*{{flagdeco|CAN}} [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n*{{flagdeco|IRL}} [[County Meath]], Ireland\n*{{flagdeco|ROC}} [[Hsinchu City]], Taiwan\n*{{flagdeco|FRA}} [[Le Touquet-Paris-Plage|Le Touquet]], [[Pas-de-Calais]], France\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n*[[I-85 Corridor]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Cary}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|1=https://www.townofcary.org}}\n* [http://www.carychamber.com/ Cary Chamber of Commerce]\n\n{{Cary, North Carolina}}\n{{Chatham County, North Carolina}}\n{{Wake County, North Carolina}}\n{{North Carolina}}\n{{Triangle, NC}}\n{{North Carolina cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Cary, North Carolina| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1750]]\n[[Category:1750 establishments in North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Cary, North Carolina\n|official_name            = Town of Cary\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = \n|postal_code_type         = ZIP Code\n|postal_code              = 27511-27513, 27518, 27519\n|image_skyline            = Cary, North Carolina. Cary, NC.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Town Hall in Cary\n|image_flag               = Flag of Cary, North Carolina.png\n|image_seal               = Seal of Cary, North Carolina.png\n|image_map                = Wake County North Carolina incorporated and unincorporated areas Cary highlighted.svg\n|map_caption              = Location in [[Wake County, North Carolina|Wake County]] and the state of [[North Carolina]].\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1   