{coord|35|47|30|N|78|46|52|W|region:US-NC|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 495\n|area_codes                = [[Area code 919|919, 984]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 37-10740<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1019552<ref name=GNIS1>{{Cite GNIS|1019552|Cary}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|1=https://www.townofcary.org}}\n|named_for                = [[Samuel Fenton Cary]]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|population_est = 168160\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n}}\n\n'''Cary''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u00e6r|i}} is the seventh-largest municipality in [[North Carolina]]. Cary is predominantly in [[Wake County, North Carolina|Wake County]], with a small area in [[Chatham County, North Carolina|Chatham County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[North Carolina]] and is the county's second-largest municipality, as well as the third-largest municipality in [[Research Triangle|The Triangle]] of North Carolina after [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] and [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]].\n\nThe town's population was 135,234 as of the [[2010 United States census|2010 census]] (an increase of 43.1% since 2000), making it the largest town and seventh-largest municipality statewide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/cities/files/SUB-EST2009_37.csv |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626124849/http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/files/SUB-EST2009_37.csv |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-06-26 |title=Subcounty population estimates: North Carolina 2000\u20132009 |format=[[comma-separated values|CSV]] |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]], Population Division |date=2010-06-22 |accessdate=2010-09-30 }}</ref> {{as of|2018|July}}, the town's estimated population was 168,160, though Cary is still classified a town because that is how it was incorporated with the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article207684979.html|title=Should Cary call itself a city or a town? Does it even matter?|last=Bolejack|first=Scott|work=[[News & Observer]]|date=2018-04-02|accessdate=2018-04-03}}</ref> Cary is the second most populous [[incorporated town]] (behind only [[Gilbert, Arizona]]) in the United States.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|US Census Bureau]], Cary was the fifth fastest-growing municipality in the United States between September 1, 2006, and September 1, 2007.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080713081930/http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/012242.html New Orleans Population Continues Katrina Recovery; Houston Leads in Numerical Growth], U.S. Census Bureau News, 2008-07-10</ref> In 2015 Cary had a crime rate of 84 violent crimes per 100,000 residents.<ref name=USSmartAssetRank>{{cite web | last = Wallace | first = Nick | title = The Safest Cities in America | url = https://smartasset.com/mortgage/safest-cities-in-america | work = [[SmartAsset]] | date = November 16, 2015 | accessdate = November 18, 2015}}</ref> Charlotte, the largest city in North Carolina, had a violent crime rate of 648 violent crimes per 100,000 residents, almost eight times higher than Cary.\n\nRaleigh, Durham, and [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]] make up the three primary metropolitan areas of the [[The Triangle (North Carolina)|Research Triangle]] metropolitan region. The regional nickname of \"The Triangle\" originated after the 1959 creation of the [[Research Triangle Park]], primarily located in Durham County, four miles from downtown Durham. RTP is bordered on three sides by the city of Durham and is roughly midway between the cities of Raleigh and Chapel Hill, and the three major research universities of [[NC State University]], [[Duke University]], and [[UNC-Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill]].\n\nEffective June 6, 2003, the U.S. [[Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB) redefined the Federal statistical areas. This resulted in the formation of the Raleigh-Cary, NC Metro Area and the Durham-Chapel Hill, NC Metro Area.\n\nThe Research Triangle region encompasses OMB's [[Combined Statistical Area|Combined Statistical Area (CSA)]] of Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill in the central [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]] region of North Carolina. {{as of|2012}}, the population of the Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill CSA was 1,998,808.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/metro/totals/2012/index.html |title=Population Estimates 2012 Combined Statistical Areas: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2012 |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=2013-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317045641/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/metro/totals/2012/index.html |archive-date=March 17, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Raleigh-Cary [[List of metropolitan statistical areas|Metropolitan Statistical Area (MSA)]] as of Census 2010 was 1,130,490.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Cary, North Carolina}}\n[[File:Page-WalkerHotel.jpg|thumb|right|[[Page-Walker Hotel]] (now local history museum)]]\n[[File:Prestontower.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Preston Clocktower in West Cary]]\n\nIn 1750, Cary began as a settlement called Bradford's Ordinary. About 100 years later, the [[North Carolina Railroad]] between [[New Bern, North Carolina|New Bern]] and [[Hillsborough, North Carolina|Hillsborough]] was constructed through the town, linking Bradford's Ordinary to a major transportation route.\n\nAllison Francis \"Frank\" Page is credited with founding the town. Page was a Wake County farmer and lumberman. He and his wife, Catherine \"Kate\" Raboteau Page bought {{convert|300|acre|km2|1}} surrounding the railroad junction in 1854 and named his development Cary, after [[Samuel Fenton Cary]]<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n69 70]}}</ref> (a former Ohio congressman and prohibitionist he admired). Page became a railroad agent and a town developer. He laid out the first streets in Cary and built a sawmill, a general store and a post office (Page became the first Postmaster). In 1868, Page built a hotel to serve railroad passengers coming through Cary. Cary was incorporated on April 3, 1871, with Page becoming the first mayor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.townofcary.org/New_to_Cary_/About_Cary_272/Looking_Back.htm |title=Looking Back |accessdate=2010-05-23 |publisher=Cary, North Carolina |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608192855/http://www.townofcary.org/New_to_Cary_/About_Cary_272/Looking_Back.htm |archivedate=2010-06-08 }}</ref> In 1879, the Raleigh and Augusta Air-Line Railroad (later the Seaboard, now [[CSX Transportation]]) arrived in Cary from the southwest, creating Fetner Junction just north of downtown and spurring further growth.\n\nIn the early years, Cary adopted zoning and other ordinances on an ad-hoc basis to control growth and give the town structure. Beginning in 1971, the town created [[Planned Unit Development]] (PUD) zoning to accommodate population growth related to the growth of [[Research Triangle Park]] nearby. A PUD allows a developer to plan an entire community before beginning development, thus allowing future residents to be aware of where churches, schools, commercial and industrial areas will be located well before such use begins. Kildaire Farms, a {{convert|967|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} Planned Unit Development in Cary, was North Carolina's first PUD. It was developed on the Pine State Dairy Farm by Thomas F. Adams, Jr. Adams named a section of Kildaire Farms \"Farmington Woods\" in their honor.\n\nIn addition to the Page-Walker Hotel, the [[Carpenter Historic District (Raleigh, North Carolina)|Carpenter Historic District]], [[Cary Historic District]], [[Green Level, Wake County, North Carolina|Green Level Historic District]], [[Ivey-Ellington House]], and [[Nancy Jones House]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nLocated in the [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]] region of the eastern United States, Cary is near North Carolina's [[Research Triangle Park|Research Triangle]]. It is bordered on the north and east by Raleigh, on the north and west by Research Triangle Park and [[Morrisville, North Carolina|Morrisville]], on the south by [[Apex, North Carolina|Apex]] and [[Holly Springs, North Carolina|Holly Springs]], and on the west by the [[Jordan Lake]] area.  The town is hilly, with much of the undeveloped land covered in dense woods. Several creeks and small lakes dot the area, most notably Lake Crabtree in the north.\n\nNearly all of Cary is in western Wake County, with neighborhood-sized sections in the northeast corner of [[Chatham County, North Carolina|Chatham County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townofcary.org/home/showdocument?id=1799|title=Town Limits Layout|last=|first=|date=March 14, 2019|website=Town of Cary|location=[[Cary, North Carolina]]|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of 43.5&nbsp;square miles (112.6&nbsp;km\u00b2), of which 42.1&nbsp;square miles (109.0&nbsp;km\u00b2) is land and 1.4&nbsp;square miles (3.6&nbsp;km\u00b2) (3.17%) is water. {{as of|2010}}, Cary claims a total area of 55.34&nbsp;mi\u00b2.<ref name='Our Community'>{{cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Publications/Citizen_s_Guide_to_Services/ourcommunity.htm |title=Town of Cary - Our Community |accessdate=2014-05-22 |publisher=Cary, North Carolina |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620154605/http://www.townofcary.org/Publications/Citizen_s_Guide_to_Services/ourcommunity.htm |archivedate=2014-06-20 }}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nCary has a [[humid subtropical climate]] (''Cfa'') under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system. It receives hot summers and mildly cold winters, with several months of pleasant weather each year. Temperature extremes here range from the negatives to over 100 degrees Fahrenheit.  Hurricanes and tropical storms can affect Cary, usually after weakening substantially from being over land. Some, such as [[Hurricane Fran]] in 1996, have caused great damage in the area. Snow falls every year, averaging approximately six inches annually.\n{{Weather box\n|location = Cary, North Carolina\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 80\n|Feb record high F = 84\n|Mar record high F = 94\n|Apr record high F = 95\n|May record high F = 99\n|Jun record high F = 104\n|Jul record high F = 105\n|Aug record high F = 105\n|Sep record high F = 104\n|Oct record high F = 98\n|Nov record high F = 88\n|Dec record high F = 81\n|year record high F= 105\n|Jan high F = 50\n|Feb high F = 54\n|Mar high F = 62\n|Apr high F = 72\n|May high F = 79\n|Jun high F = 86\n|Jul high F = 89\n|Aug high F = 87\n|Sep high F = 81\n|Oct high F = 72\n|Nov high F = 62\n|Dec high F = 53\n|year high F=\n|Jan low F = 30\n|Feb low F = 32\n|Mar low F = 39\n|Apr low F = 46\n|May low F = 55\n|Jun low F = 64\n|Jul low F = 69\n|Aug low F = 67\n|Sep low F = 61\n|Oct low F = 48\n|Nov low F = 40\n|Dec low F = 33\n|year low F=\n|Jan record low F = \u22129\n|Feb record low F = \u22122\n|Mar record low F = 11\n|Apr record low F = 23\n|May record low F = 29\n|Jun record low F = 38\n|Jul record low F = 48\n|Aug recor