nts/News/News/14777/715 Cary to Host NCAA Division II Baseball Championship for 10th time]. ''Town of Cary''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.ncaa.com/championships/soccer-men/d1/future-info College Cup: Men's DI soccer championship]. ''ncaa.com''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Parks and recreation==\n*[[Koka Booth Amphitheatre at Regency Park]]\n*[[WakeMed Soccer Park]], home of North Carolina FC of USL Championship, and North Carolina Courage of the NWSL.\n*[[William B. Umstead State Park]]\n*[[USA Baseball National Training Complex]]\n* Thomas Brooks Park\n* Sk8 Cary Skate Park<ref>[http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/Parks__Recreation___Cultural_Resources/Facilities/Sports_Facilities/Sk8-Cary_Skate_Park.htm Cary Parks: Sk8 Cary Skate Park], Cary, North Caroline. Retrieved 2012-04-16.</ref>\n* [[Bond Park|Fred G. Bond Metropolitan Park]]\n* [[Hemlock Bluffs Nature Preserve]]\n* MacDonald Woods Park<ref>[http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/11/03/cary-parks-macdonald-woods/ Cary Parks: MacDonald Woods], CaryCitizen, November 3, 2010.</ref>\n* Walnut Street Park\n* Jack Smith Park\n* North Cary Park<ref>[https://www.townofcary.org/department/parks_recreation]</ref>\n\n===Tennis===\n*Cary Tennis Park\n*Recreation Club of Lochmere\n\n==Government==\nCary has a [[council-manager government]]; the mayor and council members serve a four-year term, with half of the council seats being up for election each odd-numbered year. Four of the six council seats are elected by [[single-member district]]s; the remaining two seats are elected as [[at-large]]representatives, meaning they must attract a majority of votes across the whole town.\n\nThe current ({{as of|2016|December|lc=y}}) town council consists of Mayor Harold Weinbrecht and Representatives Jennifer Robinson (District A), Don Frantz (District B), Jack W. Smith (District C), Ken George (District D), Lori Bush (at-large), and Ed Yerha (at-large).\n\nOn October 9, 2007, Harold Weinbrecht defeated incumbent Mayor Ernie McAlister in the 2007 mayoral election. Citizen concerns that rapid growth was adversely affecting infrastructure and environment over the effect rapid growth was having on the town, especially on roads, schools, and the environment, led to McAlister's ouster.<ref>{{cite news | first = Kelcey | last = Carlson | title = Town of CaryWeinbrecht Wins Upset in Cary Mayoral Race | date = 2007-10-09 | publisher = [[Capitol Broadcasting Company]] | url = http://www.wral.com/news/local/politics/story/1908306/ | work = WRAL News | accessdate = 2010-05-23}}</ref>\n\nOn December 26, 2009, ''[[The Nation]]'' reported that Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) had secret prisons in the United States, where it held suspected illegal immigrants indefinitely before deportation. It reported that at least one of these secret federal prisons is allegedly located in an office building in Cary.<ref>{{cite news | first = Jacqueline | last = Stevens | title = America's Secret ICE Castles | date = 2009-12-16 | publisher = [[Katrina vanden Heuvel]] | url = http://www.thenation.com/article/americas-secret-ice-castles | work = The Nation | accessdate = 2010-07-20}}</ref> Part of the federal government's Department of Homeland Security, ICE has leased an office in Cary for more than 10 years. The town says that no detainees are kept at this location overnight. Other than protesters of punitive ICE policies picketing the facility, the town does not acknowledge any issues associated with the Cary ICE office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/Administration/pio/factsheet-caryice.htm |accessdate=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628232324/http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/Administration/pio/factsheet-caryice.htm |archivedate=June 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Mayors===<!-- This section is linked from [[Cary, North Carolina]] -->\n;From 1871 to present\n<small>Read in columns.</small>\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n! Name\n! Year(s)\n|-\n| A. F. Page<ref>[http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/04/22/cary-history-frank-page/ Cary History: Frank Page], ''CaryCitizen,'' 22 April 2010.</ref>\n| 1871\n| G. S. Leacock\n| 1914\n| Dr. J. P. Hunter\n| 1933\u20131935\n| Joseph R. Veasey\n| 1969\u20131971\n|-\n| J. H. Adams\n| 1884\n| T. H. Taylor\n| 1916\n| M. T. Jones\n| 1935\n| Fred G. Bond\n| 1971\u20131983\n|-\n| R. J. Harrison\n| 1887\n| W. G. Crowder\n| 1916\n| T. W. Addicks\n| 1935\n| Harold D. Ritter\n| 1983\u20131987\n|-\n| John Nugeer\n| 1897\n| E. P. Bradshaw\n| 1921\n| L. L. Raines\n| 1937\u20131947\n| Koka E. Booth<ref>[http://www.carycitizen.com/2010/06/30/profile-former-cary-mayor-koka-booth/ Profile: Former Cary Mayor Koka Booth], CaryCitizen, June 30, 2010.</ref>\n| 1987\u20131999\n|-\n| E. C. Hayes\n| 1900\n| W. H. Atkins\n| 1921\u20131925\n| R. W. Mayton\n| 1935\u20131937\n| [[Glen Lang]]\n| 1999\u20132003\n|-\n| A.R. McGarrity\n| 1902\n| G. H. Jordan\n| 1925\n| Robert G. Setzer\n| 1947\u20131949\n| Ernie McAlister\n| 2003\u20132007\n|-\n| R. J. Harrison\n| 1903\n| E. P. Bradshaw\n| 1925\n| H. Waldo Rood\n| 1949\u20131961\n| [[Harold Weinbrecht]]\n| 2007\u2013present\n|-\n| H. B. Jordan\n| 1903\n| Dr. F. R. Yarborough\n| 1927\u20131928\n| Dr. W. H. Justice\n| 1961\u20131962\n|\n|\n|-\n| N. C. Hines\n| 1910\n| A. N. Jackson\n| 1928\u20131929\n| James Hogarth\n| 1962\u20131963\n|\n|\n|-\n| J. M. Templeton, Jr.\n| 1912\n| H. H. Waddell\n| 1929\u20131933\n| Dr. E. B. Davis\n| 1963\u20131969\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Education==\n===Public schools===\n[[File:Green Hope High School (Front Entrance) 2006.jpg|thumb|200px|Green Hope High School]]\nBased in Cary, the Wake County Public School System is the largest public school system in North Carolina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://http/%3A%2F%2Fwww.wcpss.net%2Fsite%2Fdefault.aspx%3FDomainID%3D2334|title=Contact Us / Overview|website=Wake County Public Schools|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*High Schools\n**[[Cary High School]]\n**Crossroads FLEX High School\n**[[Green Hope High School]]\n**Green Level High School\n**[[Middle Creek High School]]\n**[[Panther Creek High School (North Carolina)|Panther Creek High School]]\n*Middle Schools\n**Davis Drive Middle School\n**East Cary Middle School\n**Mills Park Middle School\n**Reedy Creek Middle School\n**West Cary Middle School\n**Alston Ridge Middle School\n*Elementary Schools\n**Adams Elementary School\n**Alston Ridge Elementary School\n**Briarcliff Elementary School\n**Carpenter Elementary School\n**Cary Elementary School\n**Davis Drive Elementary School\n**Farmington Woods Elementary School\n**Green Hope Elementary School\n**Highcroft Drive Elementary School\n**Hortons Creek Elementary\n**Kingswood Elementary School\n**Mills Park Elementary School\n**Northwoods Elementary School\n**Oak Grove Elementary School\n**Penny Road Elementary School\n**Reedy Creek Elementary School\n**Turner Creek Elementary School\n**Weatherstone Elementary School\n\n===Private schools===\n*[[Cary Academy]], middle/high school\n*[[Cary Christian School]], K-12 grade\n*Chesterbrook Academy\n*[[Grace Christian School (North Carolina)|Grace Christian School]], K-12 grade\n*[[Hopewell Academy]]\n*[[Saint Michael the Archangel Catholic School]]\n*Resurrection Lutheran School, K\u20138th grade\n*Landmark Christian Academy, K3\u201310th grade\n*Cardinal Charter Academy, K-8th grade\n\n===Higher education===\n*[[Wake Technical Community College]]\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transportation===\n====Public transit====\nPublic transit within the town is provided by [[GoCary]], with six fixed-routes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/fdts/trafficandtransportation/GoCary/fixedroute.htm|title=Fixed Route Service|website=www.townofcary.org|access-date=2016-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012222926/http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/fdts/trafficandtransportation/GoCary/fixedroute.htm|archive-date=2016-10-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> There is a door-to-door service for the senior citizens (60+) and riders with disabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townofcary.org/Departments/fdts/trafficandtransportation/GoCary/doortodoor.htm|title=GoCary Door to Door Service|website=www.townofcary.org|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref> [[GoTriangle]] operates fixed-route buses that serve the metropolitan region and connect to the local municipal transit systems in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]] and [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gotriangle.org/maps-and-schedules|title=Maps & Schedules {{!}} GoTriangle|website=gotriangle.org|access-date=2016-10-10}}</ref>\n\n====Intercity rail====\n[[Amtrak]]'s [[Silver Star (Amtrak train)|Silver Star]], [[Carolinian and Piedmont]] passenger trains stop at the [[Cary (Amtrak station)|Cary Amtrak station]]. They offer service to [[Charlotte]], [[New York City]], [[Miami]], and intermediate points.\n\n====Bicycle====\nIn 2010 the [[League of American Bicyclists]] designated Cary as one of the fourteen recipients of the first ''Bicycle-Friendly Community'' awards for \"providing safe accommodation and facilities for bicyclists and encouraging residents to bike for transportation and recreation\".<ref name=\"greenways\">{{cite web | url = http://townofcary.org/Departments/Parks__Recreation___Cultural_Resources/Parks_and_Greenways/Greenways.htm | title = Greenways | accessdate = 2010-05-23 | publisher = Cary, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nThe Maine-to-Florida [[U.S. Bicycle Route 1]] passes through suburban Cary, as does [[North Carolina Bicycle Route 2|N.C. Bicycle Route #2]], the \"Mountains to Sea\" route.\n\n====Pedestrian====\nCary Greenways and Trails maintains a network of sidewalks and paved trails connecting neighborhoods and parks throughout the town.<ref name=\"greenways\" /> These greenways place strict requirements on environmental conditions to preserve a park-like atmosphere. In addition, standard sidewalks and paths exist throughout the town.\n\n====Air====\nThe [[Raleigh-Durham International Airport]], north of Cary via [[Interstate 40]] between Cary, [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] and [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], serves Cary and the greater Research Triangle metropolitan region. Raleigh-Durham offers more than 35 destinations, serving approximately 9 million passengers per year.\n\n====Freeways and primary routes====\n{{Main|North Carolina Highway System}}\n[[File:Chathamstreetcary.png|thumb|right|Downtown Cary, on Chatham Street]]\n*[[Interstate 40]]\n*[[U.S. Route 1 in North Carolina|U.S. 1]]\n*[[U.S. Route 64|U.S. 64]]\n*[[NC 54|State Highway 54]]\n*[[NC 55|State Highway 55]]\n*[[NC 147|State Highway 147]]\n*[[NC 540|State Highway 540]]\n*[[NC 751|State Highway 751]]\n*[[Cary Parkway]]\n*Kildaire Farm Road\n*Walnut Street (which appears on some maps as Cary-Macedonia Road)\n*High House Road\n*Harrison Avenue\n*Maynard Road Loop\n*Davis Drive (links to [[Research Triangle Park]])\n*Holly Springs Road\n\n==Notable people==\n{{maincat|People from Cary, North Carolina}}\n* [[Jesse Boulerice]], former [[National Hockey League|NHL]] player\n* [[Marshall Brain]], founder of the [[HowStuffWorks]] website\n* [[Carter Cruise]], pornographic actress\n*[[Casey Cole]], American [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] friar, Catholic priest, writer, and blogger<ref>Howard, Mandy. (Jun 26, 2019). [https://dioceseofraleigh.org/news/sharing-habit-newly-ordained-priest-celebrates-mass-sacraments-and-social-media Sharing the habit: Newly ordained priest celebrates Mass, sacraments, and ... social media]. ''Catholic Diocese of Raleigh''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Cotto]], Olympic track and field athlete representing [[Puerto Rico]]\n* [[Anoop Desai]], singer-songwriter best known for his time as a contestant on the eighth season of ''[[American Idol]]''<ref>Menconi, David. (Apr 1, 2016). [https://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/on-the-beat-blog/article68264742.html Catching up with North Carolina's 'Idols']. ''The News & Observer''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Spright Dowell]], former President of Alabama Polytechnic Institute, now known as [[Auburn University]]\n* [[Tim Downs]], American author<ref>[https://www.simonandschuster.com/authors/Tim-Downs/38977864 Tim Downs | Official Publisher Page]. ''Simon & Schuster''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Chris Flemmings]], professional [[basketball]] player<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/chris-flemmings-1.html Chris Flemmings College Stats]. ''Sports-Reference.com''.</ref>\n* [[Kendall Fletcher]], professional [[association football|women's soccer]] player<ref>[https://goheels.com/sports/womens-soccer/roster/kendall-fletcher/6228 Kendall Fletcher - Women's Soccer - UNC]. ''goheels.com''.</ref>\n* [[James Goodnight]], co-founder and CEO of [[SAS Institute]]\n* [[Ron Hendren]], former co-host of [[Entertainment Tonight]]\n* [[Justin Jedlica]], model and businessman\n* [[Alfred Daniel Jones]], US Consul General in Shanghai (1893), lived in Cary\n* [[Isaiah Johnson (American football, born October 1992)|Isaiah Johnson]], [[NFL]] defensive back<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnIs00.htm Isaiah Johnson Stats]. ''Pro-Football-Reference''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[U. Alexis Johnson]], United States [[diplomat]]\n* [[Scott Kooistra]], NFL [[tackle (gridiron football position)|offensive tackle]]<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/K/KooiSc20.htm Scott Kooistra Stats]. ''Pro-Football-Reference''. Retrieved Feb 6, 2020.</ref>\n* [[Nathan Macias]], former member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]]; lived in Cary while in the [[United States Air Force]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lrl.state.tx.us/scanned/members/bios/TLO/80th_Macias_Nathan.pdf|title=House Membership: Representative Nathan Mathias|publisher=Texas Legislative Reference Library|accessd